WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.680
[Amit Varma]: When we think of ourselves, we think of ourselves as something fixed.

00:00:08.680 --> 00:00:09.880
[Amit Varma]: This is what I am.

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:11.180
[Amit Varma]: This is no accident.

00:00:11.180 --> 00:00:16.960
[Amit Varma]: Even if we accept that some aspects of ourselves are contingent, we hold that others are essential.

00:00:16.960 --> 00:00:20.040
[Amit Varma]: One of those, oddly enough, can be musical taste.

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:21.400
[Amit Varma]: Think of the music you like.

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:25.280
[Amit Varma]: To like that kind of music almost seems hardwired into you, doesn't it?

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:30.200
[Amit Varma]: You may discover stuff through your peers or your environment, but what you like feels

00:00:30.200 --> 00:00:31.680
[Amit Varma]: a part of what you are.

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:33.680
[Amit Varma]: Well, here's a thought experiment.

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:35.520
[Amit Varma]: What if you were born in North Africa?

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:37.440
[Amit Varma]: What kind of music would you have liked then?

00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:38.440
[Amit Varma]: Or interior Jharkhand?

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:39.440
[Amit Varma]: Or Iceland?

00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:40.440
[Amit Varma]: Or Peru?

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:41.440
[Amit Varma]: Or Kazakhstan?

00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:44.360
[Amit Varma]: It's likely that your favorite artist would have been someone you haven't even heard of

00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:45.360
[Amit Varma]: right now.

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:50.000
[Amit Varma]: It's also possible that all the music you take with you to a desert island today would

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.280
[Amit Varma]: be stuff that you'd never discover in this thought experiment world.

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:58.360
[Amit Varma]: But my point is not that all our tastes are contingent on accidents like the accident

00:00:58.360 --> 00:00:59.360
[Amit Varma]: of birth.

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:00.800
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I believe the opposite.

00:01:00.800 --> 00:01:06.080
[Amit Varma]: I believe that our brains are wired to find pleasures in certain kinds of sound, and that

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:10.560
[Amit Varma]: there is something universal in music everywhere, however different it may seem to us.

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:16.040
[Amit Varma]: We can find rapture in Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan or Led Zeppelin or Tenorivan, and that rapture

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:20.200
[Amit Varma]: is rooted in the human condition, in the effect that music has on us.

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:22.280
[Amit Varma]: And it's basically the same rapture.

00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:26.960
[Amit Varma]: It may seem at a superficial level that we are different like our music is different.

00:01:26.960 --> 00:01:29.640
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, the music isn't different.

00:01:29.640 --> 00:01:32.120
[Amit Varma]: There is a universal pentatonic.

