00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:35.240
[Amit Varma]: from his home in Auckland.

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:39.960
[Amit Varma]: I love this episode, not just because of this conversation, but also because it took me

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:45.200
[Amit Varma]: on a superb journey of discovering that part of Warren's music that I hadn't heard yet.

00:02:45.200 --> 00:02:49.440
[Amit Varma]: I've been driving people nuts by playing Ode to a Sunny Day on repeat.

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:54.200
[Amit Varma]: Before we get to this conversation, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:58.520
[Amit Varma]: One of the themes of this episode is that even though all music has local flavour, music

00:02:58.520 --> 00:02:59.800
[Amit Varma]: itself is universal.

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:02.880
[Amit Varma]: Well, you can turn that around when it comes to crime.

00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:08.080
[Amit Varma]: Human nature is twisted and crime is everywhere, but it has a local flavour everywhere.

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:12.120
[Amit Varma]: This episode is sponsored by a podcast that is all about desi crime.

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:17.640
[Amit Varma]: Aishwarya Singh and Aryan Misra are the hosts of the Desi Crime podcast, which covers crimes

00:03:17.640 --> 00:03:21.400
[Amit Varma]: from India, Pakistan, Nepal, basically any place you'd call desi.

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:25.640
[Amit Varma]: Their show description has this sentence which hooked me right away.

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:30.360
[Amit Varma]: Quote, crimes that take place in the Indian subcontinent aren't remotely similar to Western

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:31.360
[Amit Varma]: crimes.

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:34.760
[Amit Varma]: Desi crimes are gory, complicated, corrupt, and hardly documented.

