[Amit Varma]: They tell us about the most prolific murderer in history, Thug Bairam.

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:49.640
[Amit Varma]: They give us the inside dope on the massacre of the Nepali royal family.

00:03:49.640 --> 00:03:54.040
[Amit Varma]: We get suicide pacts and police brutality, disappearing journalists and charming serial

00:03:54.040 --> 00:03:55.040
[Amit Varma]: killers.

00:03:55.040 --> 00:04:00.200
[Amit Varma]: If you like storytelling and crime interests you, you should listen to the Desi Crime podcast.

00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:04.180
[Amit Varma]: You can find it on Apple, Spotify, Amazon Music, wherever you listen to your podcast.

00:04:04.180 --> 00:04:11.200
[Amit Varma]: So check out the Desi Crime podcast, there is no better way to kill time.

00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:13.160
[Amit Varma]: Warren and Chuck, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:04:13.160 --> 00:04:14.160
[Guest]: Oh, thank you.

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:16.200
[Unknown]: It's a pleasure to be here.

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:18.800
[Unknown]: And thank you for having me as a co-host.

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:22.880
[Amit Varma]: Okay, so, you know, in the spirit of how these episodes sometimes go, let's just talk about

00:04:22.880 --> 00:04:28.000
[Amit Varma]: what we were talking about in the moment, which is that we had great trouble getting

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:29.520
[Amit Varma]: Chuck's mic to work.

00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:31.680
[Amit Varma]: And he finally got it to work.

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:36.720
[Amit Varma]: And he said, as soon as it started working that I'm not going to touch anything, right?

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:37.720
[Amit Varma]: Something like that.

00:04:37.720 --> 00:04:38.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, something of that sort.

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:39.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:40.720
[Amit Varma]: And Warren, you mentioned you had a story about that.

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:41.720
[Amit Varma]: So let's start with the story.

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:46.000
[Guest]: Okay, the story is, I used to be in a band called Zero.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:50.120
[Guest]: And we used to practice in this old house in Shivaji Park called Uday Vihar.

00:04:50.120 --> 00:04:56.080
[Guest]: Now being an old house, you know, of like, I think, 30s or 40s or whenever it was built,

00:04:56.080 --> 00:04:59.280
[Guest]: the electric grounding was a bit suspect.

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:02.720
[Guest]: So when we used to practice, first of all, we used to get shocks from each other.

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:05.640
[Guest]: If one person touched the other person, it was like a severe jhatka.

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:09.760
[Guest]: So we learned not to touch each other while practicing, you know.

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:15.120
[Guest]: So the issue then became with distortion, all that noise became amplified.

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:17.880
[Guest]: So you had to find a way of grounding the amplifiers.

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:24.320
[Guest]: So me being electrical engineering student knew that there was a water pipe running outside.

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:28.320
[Guest]: So we got some sandpaper, cleaned it a little bit, put a wire around it, soldered it in

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:31.840
[Guest]: place, brought that wire in and grounded the amps.

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:35.480
[Guest]: Problem became in the monsoon, the connection would become intermittent.

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:40.320
[Guest]: So Raji had to go outside while we were playing our guitars and jiggle the wire till the noise

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:41.560
[Guest]: was gone.

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:45.360
[Guest]: And then he was told, okay, leave it, leave it, don't touch anything, it's just fine right

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:46.360
[Guest]: now.

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:49.520
[Guest]: And then again, if the noise came, he would have to go out and repeat the process.

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:54.560
[Guest]: Then a few months, I think, later, we got complaints that your guys are too loud, neighbors

00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:55.720
[Guest]: are complaining.

00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:59.640
[Guest]: So we figured the room we were practicing in was the first room closest to the main

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:00.640
[Guest]: road.

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:01.640
[Guest]: So we said we'll go to the next room.

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:05.240
[Guest]: When we went to the next room, the power was grounded over there.

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:09.520
[Guest]: And we realized we could have just taken an extension box and plugged it into that room.

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:18.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's such, you know, such Jugaadu lives kind of musicians live with, you know, I remember

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:20.940
[Amit Varma]: reading somewhere that a musician's best friend is duct tape.

00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:24.520
[Amit Varma]: So this episode really happened when you heard the episode between Chuck and me and you said

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:27.680
[Amit Varma]: next time we discuss you discuss the Beatles kindly call me.

00:06:27.680 --> 00:06:28.680
[Amit Varma]: So here we are.

00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:32.560
[Amit Varma]: Now there's a lot we want to discuss apart from the Beatles, but we thought a nice way

00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:37.560
[Amit Varma]: to kind of get it going is actually to talk about the Beatles because I you know, in one

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:42.680
[Amit Varma]: of your interviews, I read something moving where you said that, you know, the most memorable

00:06:42.680 --> 00:06:47.360
[Amit Varma]: memory from your childhood, as it were, was when you heard the Beatles for the first time.

00:06:47.360 --> 00:06:51.240
[Amit Varma]: So tell us a little bit about, you know, what they meant to you and what they have meant

00:06:51.240 --> 00:06:52.240
[Amit Varma]: to you since.

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:58.320
[Guest]: Well, from the moment I was a kid, and I could barely talk, like my aunt who used to live

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:02.600
[Guest]: with us at the time, had this big poster of the Beatles, so I'd learned all their names,

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:05.000
[Guest]: you know, as we say, John, Paul, George Ringo and everything.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:09.440
[Guest]: So, you know, that was like the awareness for, you know, who the Beatles were when I

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:11.360
[Guest]: was from a young age.

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:15.520
[Guest]: And it was a bit later, I think, when I was around eight, after I went through a beef

00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:21.280
[Guest]: MC Hammer phase, someone gave me this compilation cassette, and there was a Beatles medley in

00:07:21.280 --> 00:07:22.280
[Guest]: that.

00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:25.360
[Guest]: And it was one of those, you know, the now party, whatever, you know, this compilation

00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:26.360
[Guest]: thing.

00:07:26.360 --> 00:07:30.160
[Guest]: And that Beatles medley, suddenly of all the songs that made the most sense to me, age

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:31.160
[Guest]: eight.

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:32.160
[Guest]: So I said, what is this?

00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:36.880
[Guest]: I went to my dad, who's also a musician, and he said, well, you know, you should probably

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:40.000
[Guest]: get into the Beatles at this point, you'll kind of, you know, understand a little bit

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.400
[Guest]: more about the, you know, the basics of music and everything like that.

00:07:44.400 --> 00:07:49.080
[Guest]: So I tried getting my hands, we had some cassettes at home, so I listened to that.

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:53.200
[Guest]: And then my uncle had the motherlode, he had all the albums on vinyl.

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:58.960
[Guest]: My dad's sister's husband, his name is Kalayil, awesome guy.

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:04.280
[Guest]: So he used to give me one by one, like a lending library vinyl, I used to take it to the local

00:08:04.280 --> 00:08:08.080
[Guest]: guy who had one vinyl player and one cassette deck, and he would do the transfer because

00:08:08.080 --> 00:08:10.800
[Guest]: I didn't have a working, you know, vinyl player at home.

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:13.680
[Guest]: So all these cassette transfers became then like my textbook, you know.

00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:20.960
[Guest]: So I think between age eight to 13, I literally did not listen to anything else.

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:21.960
[Guest]: That was it.

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:25.960
[Guest]: So every single album, everything went into, you know, and I used to sit with my guitar

00:08:25.960 --> 00:08:27.320
[Guest]: and slowly, slowly tried.

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:32.960
[Guest]: And then I found out how to slow down the tape, learn solos in half speed and stuff

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:34.480
[Guest]: like that.

00:08:34.480 --> 00:08:38.320
[Guest]: And for bass lines, you have to speed up the tape so you could hear the bass more clearly,

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:39.960
[Guest]: all that kind of stuff.

00:08:39.960 --> 00:08:45.160
[Guest]: So then, you know, kind of what I became as a musician, a large part of that came from

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:49.320
[Guest]: that initial grounding experience, because at the same time, I started, you know, sitting

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:51.880
[Guest]: with the guitar a little bit more seriously.

00:08:51.880 --> 00:08:55.740
[Unknown]: So there you go, that's the, that's the Beatles story for you.

00:08:55.740 --> 00:09:00.720
[Unknown]: So one follow up question that I'll ask is, interestingly, also, you said, that was your

00:09:00.720 --> 00:09:04.480
[Unknown]: basic grounding, and you have two grounding stories really over there, but two different

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:05.480
[Unknown]: kinds of grounding entirely.

00:09:05.480 --> 00:09:09.880
[Unknown]: Anyone who listens to the Beatles now, it's very apparent that there's been an evolution

00:09:09.880 --> 00:09:13.760
[Unknown]: right from the early, I want to say boy band phase, right to the later psychedelic and

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:14.760
[Unknown]: experimental phase.

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:19.560
[Unknown]: But how did you react to that as a eight to 13 year old, were you able to track that evolution?

00:09:19.560 --> 00:09:22.760
[Unknown]: Did you hear the albums chronologically?

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:26.800
[Unknown]: Just curious to hear about, you know, something like that.

00:09:26.800 --> 00:09:30.600
[Guest]: The older I got, the more sense the later albums made to me.

00:09:30.600 --> 00:09:35.720
[Guest]: So initially, the, you know, the initial, the first early albums, Please Please Me,

00:09:35.720 --> 00:09:39.480
[Guest]: the first two or three albums, that was what I gravitated to most.

00:09:39.480 --> 00:09:43.040
[Guest]: And then obviously, there are songs on the later albums, like Let It Be and Hey Jude,

00:09:43.040 --> 00:09:45.320
[Guest]: which are very accessible.

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:47.000
[Guest]: So I still love those as well.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:50.000
[Guest]: But then the first time I heard a song like Tomorrow Never Knows, I got really scared.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.040
[Guest]: I was like, I don't think I'm supposed to be listening to this music.

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:55.160
[Guest]: It's kind of like weird and everything.

00:09:55.160 --> 00:09:56.920
[Guest]: So I kind of put that on the back burner.

00:09:56.920 --> 00:10:00.440
[Guest]: And then, you know, as you go closer to puberty, all that stuff starts making a little bit

00:10:00.440 --> 00:10:01.800
[Unknown]: more sense to you.

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:04.760
[Unknown]: So you did listen to them chronologically?

00:10:04.760 --> 00:10:10.200
[Guest]: I tried to, I mean, I can still tell you like, which album comes after what, and it's like,

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:15.160
[Guest]: so you know, well etched in my mind, the moment one song stops, I can hear the next song starting.

00:10:15.160 --> 00:10:21.960
[Guest]: My daughter thinks I'm nuts because I start singing the next song and then it starts.

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:22.960
[Amit Varma]: That must be spooky.

00:10:22.960 --> 00:10:27.240
[Amit Varma]: I read this essay by Ted Joya recently, or I think it was in his interview with Tyler

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:32.920
[Amit Varma]: Carvin where he mentioned how the Beatles for those five or six years, the significant

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:35.520
[Amit Varma]: thing about them was they kept evolving every five, six months.

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And the reason according to him that was important is that every time you have somebody who becomes

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.760
[Amit Varma]: a breakthrough hit, what they're doing becomes a formula.

00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:47.680
[Amit Varma]: And people immediately rush to imitate that and copy that and they were changing every

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:48.680
[Amit Varma]: six months.

00:10:48.680 --> 00:10:51.040
[Amit Varma]: And his point was, look, they do something in 1964.

00:10:51.040 --> 00:10:53.480
[Amit Varma]: The monkeys comes along and does something really similar.

00:10:53.480 --> 00:10:55.960
[Amit Varma]: But by the time the monkeys is out, they moved on.

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:58.400
[Amit Varma]: And they're moving on over a period.

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:03.840
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, would you then say that it's kind of listening to the Beatles discography

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:08.560
[Amit Varma]: is like an accelerated education in music also, where you're just getting so many different

00:11:08.560 --> 00:11:15.520
[Amit Varma]: styles from your really basic pop song, like the early stuff to, you know, much more complicated

00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:16.880
[Amit Varma]: stuff later on?

00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:17.880
[Guest]: Yeah, certainly.

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:22.760
[Guest]: But I mean, even by the second or the third album, you could hear like them changing things

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:25.200
[Guest]: like in She Loves You, for example, she loves you.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:28.240
[Guest]: And then one minor chord comes in like the four minor.

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:31.880
[Guest]: That's like something that you wouldn't have heard, you know, a little while before.

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:35.040
[Guest]: So you can sense that sophistication coming in really quickly.

00:11:35.040 --> 00:11:40.760
[Guest]: I think also what happens is the moment an artist experiences some kind of mass success,

00:11:40.760 --> 00:11:46.720
[Guest]: there's all this kind of acceptance that comes in, you know, so you feel more, you're more

00:11:46.720 --> 00:11:50.920
[Guest]: likely to take risks, because you know that, you know, otherwise, always wondering, will

00:11:50.920 --> 00:11:51.920
[Guest]: people like it?

00:11:51.920 --> 00:11:56.080
[Guest]: But now they come to a point in popularity where like, everyone loves what they do.

00:11:56.080 --> 00:11:58.480
[Guest]: So it makes sense for them to take those risks.

00:11:58.480 --> 00:12:02.640
[Guest]: And you can see the acceleration is really quick.

00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:08.400
[Guest]: By the time they became popular, because by the time I think 63 was the first album.

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:13.320
[Guest]: Before that, they had spent years playing covers in Hamburg and the repertoire was vast.

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:17.960
[Guest]: They would have listened to like everything from jazz and you know, whatever top 40 and

00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:20.760
[Guest]: I was going in to the rock and roll and everything like that.

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:23.240
[Guest]: So huge range of influences already.

00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:24.880
[Guest]: And that's kind of already percolating.

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:30.720
[Guest]: And by the time the first album hits, you can see this, you know, from 63, please Mr.

00:12:30.720 --> 00:12:34.600
[Guest]: Postman, 66, Sargent Pepper comes along.

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:37.000
[Guest]: That's three years.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:38.000
[Guest]: That's ridiculous.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:46.840
[Unknown]: Yeah, one of the things that we started our conversation, Amit, with was, I had a theory

00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:53.120
[Unknown]: that if the discography of the Beatles was slightly flipped, and Sargent Pepper for some

00:12:53.120 --> 00:12:57.520
[Unknown]: magical reason was the first album, and then Please Please Me, etc. came later, that the

00:12:57.520 --> 00:13:01.000
[Unknown]: history of music would have been completely different because the Beatles wouldn't have

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.720
[Unknown]: had that initial fan base and then something experimental like Sargent Pepper wouldn't

00:13:04.720 --> 00:13:08.320
[Unknown]: have had a mass audience to be tested out on.

00:13:08.320 --> 00:13:11.760
[Unknown]: And that's something we debated and we'd love to know what you think about that.

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:13.520
[Guest]: Yeah, I think for sure.

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:18.440
[Guest]: Because even a guy like John Mayer, if you notice his career, the initial albums are

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:24.240
[Guest]: a little bit more poppy and you know, designed to get into the mainstream really quickly.

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:28.360
[Guest]: Once those two or three albums go by, and you become a household name, that's when you

00:13:28.360 --> 00:13:33.840
[Guest]: see, hey man, I'm going to take some risks and, you know, do something different.

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:38.120
[Guest]: And plus, what happens is then the people who are controlling the money supply are less

00:13:38.120 --> 00:13:39.120
[Guest]: likely to worry.

00:13:39.120 --> 00:13:44.360
[Guest]: They're saying, this guy knows what he's doing, let's let him do it, don't need to get involved.

00:13:44.360 --> 00:13:48.080
[Guest]: So then you have those abilities to do that, otherwise there's always someone saying, hey,

00:13:48.080 --> 00:13:51.120
[Guest]: make it more like this, or make it more like that, or maybe your pants should be blue,

00:13:51.120 --> 00:13:53.920
[Guest]: and your shoes should be green, you know, that sort of thing.

00:13:53.920 --> 00:13:56.600
[Guest]: And that kind of gets in the way of a certain creative flow.

00:13:56.600 --> 00:14:01.000
[Guest]: Because sometimes when too many people make those decisions, the art tends to suffer.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:05.760
[Unknown]: Yeah, I think that's a great business lesson itself over there for a company who's already

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:06.760
[Unknown]: popular or something.

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:11.640
[Unknown]: If they're launching something experimental, then it's likely that that will find acceptance

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:13.520
[Unknown]: with investors as well as audiences.

00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:15.960
[Unknown]: But that's just me extrapolating what you said.

00:14:15.960 --> 00:14:18.520
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I don't think it would work in a business context.

00:14:18.520 --> 00:14:23.960
[Amit Varma]: Because I think, you know, one day you're a startup, you innovate in some way, you're

00:14:23.960 --> 00:14:24.960
[Amit Varma]: a disruptor.

00:14:24.960 --> 00:14:27.720
[Amit Varma]: But once you become a big company, then you become set in your ways, your incentives are

00:14:27.720 --> 00:14:30.560
[Amit Varma]: for just keep on doing the same thing.

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:34.000
[Amit Varma]: But I guess I want to ask a question that in fact, I asked all the historians who come

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:35.400
[Amit Varma]: on the show.

00:14:35.400 --> 00:14:38.960
[Amit Varma]: And I think it's particularly apt when you're talking about the Beatles.

00:14:38.960 --> 00:14:42.800
[Amit Varma]: Now there's something, a gent named Thomas Carlyle had come up with something called

00:14:42.800 --> 00:14:44.760
[Amit Varma]: the great man theory of history.

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:46.760
[Amit Varma]: And there are really two schools of thought on this.

00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:51.220
[Amit Varma]: But Carlyle's great man theory of history really postulates that history is made by

00:14:51.220 --> 00:14:53.440
[Amit Varma]: great man at some point.

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:55.960
[Amit Varma]: And of course, back in those days, everything was a male gender.

00:14:55.960 --> 00:14:58.880
[Amit Varma]: So therefore, the great man and not the great person theory.

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:02.480
[Amit Varma]: But the idea being that there'll be a great person, they'll do something great and history

00:15:02.480 --> 00:15:03.480
[Amit Varma]: changes.

00:15:03.480 --> 00:15:06.960
[Amit Varma]: Whereas the counterpoint to that is that no, there are currents in history which are happening

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:07.960
[Amit Varma]: anyway.

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:10.160
[Amit Varma]: And things are going to go where they're going to go.

00:15:10.160 --> 00:15:12.820
[Amit Varma]: And people don't, individuals don't matter so much.

00:15:12.820 --> 00:15:15.880
[Amit Varma]: So in the context of the Beatles, how would you look at that?

00:15:15.880 --> 00:15:21.160
[Amit Varma]: Like, my sense is that music history would have been vastly different if say, if John

00:15:21.160 --> 00:15:26.120
[Amit Varma]: and Paul hadn't met, you know, you know, you can pick your sort of great man equivalent

00:15:26.120 --> 00:15:29.800
[Amit Varma]: of choice, you could pick Led Zeppelin, you could pick Dylan, depending on what you're

00:15:29.800 --> 00:15:31.200
[Amit Varma]: going to listen to.

00:15:31.200 --> 00:15:34.280
[Amit Varma]: So is that something you'd kind of tend to agree with?

00:15:34.280 --> 00:15:37.640
[Amit Varma]: Or would you say that there are currents which are going in a particular way, even if you

00:15:37.640 --> 00:15:41.560
[Amit Varma]: didn't have that specific group, music would have, you know, continued evolving in the

00:15:41.560 --> 00:15:42.960
[Amit Varma]: same kind of way?

00:15:42.960 --> 00:15:45.120
[Guest]: What's your sense?

00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:50.880
[Guest]: I think it's also down to the level of influence they had among other bands, you know, there

00:15:50.880 --> 00:15:53.760
[Guest]: was a lot of other bands that were very influenced by what they were doing.

00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:57.800
[Guest]: I mean, we're the first guys to actually start writing their own songs, if you look at it,

00:15:57.800 --> 00:16:01.160
[Guest]: because it was a lot of that, you know, A&R, we'll get the song from somebody, give it

00:16:01.160 --> 00:16:02.640
[Guest]: to the singer to sing.

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:03.640
[Guest]: And these guys come along.

00:16:03.640 --> 00:16:07.400
[Guest]: And there's also that class thing, which was broken down because they were these, you know,

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:08.400
[Guest]: Northern England people.

00:16:08.400 --> 00:16:12.940
[Guest]: So in that English sense, they kind of opened up the thing.

00:16:12.940 --> 00:16:17.120
[Guest]: And then the crossover to America, then that cross-pollination, which had been happening

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:19.440
[Guest]: is blown wide open, you know.

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:23.280
[Guest]: So in that sense, you can't discount like, you know, musically aside, if you're just

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:27.080
[Guest]: looking at historically, that would have definitely changed.

00:16:27.080 --> 00:16:32.560
[Guest]: There wouldn't be an Aerosmith without the Beatles, or a vast number of other bands like

00:16:32.560 --> 00:16:33.560
[Guest]: that.

00:16:33.560 --> 00:16:39.400
[Guest]: I mean, I don't think you'd have the opportunity for, let's say, what's like a not as famous

00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:42.320
[Guest]: British band, let's say Jets Hotel.

00:16:42.320 --> 00:16:46.840
[Guest]: Jets Hotel wouldn't have the ability to be popular in America unless that initial barrier

00:16:46.840 --> 00:16:48.520
[Guest]: had been broken down.

00:16:48.520 --> 00:16:49.520
[Guest]: And who did it?

00:16:49.520 --> 00:16:50.520
[Unknown]: It was them.

00:16:50.520 --> 00:16:51.520
[Unknown]: Interesting.

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:52.520
[Unknown]: So it's not just musically.

00:16:52.520 --> 00:16:55.920
[Unknown]: Another way of phrasing Amit's question, and this is something I often think about is,

00:16:55.920 --> 00:17:02.160
[Unknown]: which artist, if removed from rock history would have had the maximum ripple effect across?

00:17:02.160 --> 00:17:05.320
[Unknown]: And it's another way of phrasing the question that you asked is the great man theory.

00:17:05.320 --> 00:17:08.960
[Unknown]: But any name that springs to mind for you?

00:17:08.960 --> 00:17:09.960
[Guest]: Hendrix.

00:17:09.960 --> 00:17:10.960
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:17:10.960 --> 00:17:11.960
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:17:11.960 --> 00:17:12.960
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:17:12.960 --> 00:17:13.960
[Guest]: I mean, not just guitar players.

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:14.960
[Guest]: A lot of other musicians were.

00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:17.720
[Guest]: I mean, Miles Davis was very interested in what Hendrix was doing.

00:17:17.720 --> 00:17:19.720
[Amit Varma]: So that only goes to show.

00:17:19.720 --> 00:17:20.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:21.720
[Amit Varma]: Great.

00:17:21.720 --> 00:17:26.760
[Amit Varma]: So, so let's, let's start by, you know, where my shows often start, which is kind of your

00:17:26.760 --> 00:17:27.760
[Amit Varma]: personal history.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:31.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you were born in the right when the 70s were ending, you grew up in Dadar, tell

00:17:31.960 --> 00:17:35.280
[Amit Varma]: us a little bit about what your childhood was like, because, like, I'm a little older

00:17:35.280 --> 00:17:36.280
[Amit Varma]: than you.

00:17:36.280 --> 00:17:40.120
[Amit Varma]: And I remember back in those days, just, you know, you couldn't, the stuff people today

00:17:40.120 --> 00:17:44.000
[Amit Varma]: take for granted, like you can listen to any music in the world and all of that.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:45.400
[Amit Varma]: We couldn't take that shit for granted.

00:17:45.400 --> 00:17:48.960
[Amit Varma]: It was such a big deal and such an achievement to put a mixtape together.

00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:53.680
[Amit Varma]: For example, you discovered music by a band, you would have to scrounge high and dry for

00:17:53.680 --> 00:17:58.160
[Amit Varma]: some other album by them, even for information about, like, who are these guys and all of

00:17:58.160 --> 00:17:59.160
[Amit Varma]: that.

00:17:59.160 --> 00:18:04.720
[Amit Varma]: So tell us something about sort of the texture of your childhood growing up and, you know,

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:05.720
[Amit Varma]: what those years were like.

00:18:05.720 --> 00:18:12.520
[Guest]: So, I mean, I was, I was very lucky in that sense, because I was born into a musical family.

00:18:12.520 --> 00:18:17.680
[Guest]: So I was already surrounded by, you know, music, the act of creating it, the act of

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:20.000
[Guest]: listening to it, all of that.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:24.200
[Guest]: And the access to music, obviously, wasn't as good as it was now.

00:18:24.200 --> 00:18:27.220
[Guest]: But at least, you know, my, my dad had good taste.

00:18:27.220 --> 00:18:31.400
[Guest]: So a lot of, you know, his cassettes became like part of my education, like when I wanted

00:18:31.400 --> 00:18:34.160
[Guest]: to listen to Clapton, he gave me all the cream stuff.

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:36.720
[Guest]: He said, listen to that first, you know.

00:18:36.720 --> 00:18:37.800
[Guest]: So at least I had that.

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:41.720
[Guest]: And then I had uncles and my dad's friends, other musicians who would drop in, you know,

00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:46.400
[Guest]: and give some, like my uncle Loi, he, at the time I was a kid, he used to live in Delhi.

00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:49.640
[Guest]: So he used to come down once in a while and every time, like, he would come down, little

00:18:49.640 --> 00:18:54.280
[Guest]: one little nugget of yarn, you know, my first rock and roll riff or something like that,

00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:55.280
[Guest]: I would get from him.

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:58.240
[Guest]: When I was just one, we didn't have a TV at home.

00:18:58.240 --> 00:19:05.000
[Guest]: That came when I was like, say, four or five goes on black and white number and again,

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:09.840
[Guest]: you know, what TV was like at that time, there was nothing in the English sense, it was like

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:15.400
[Guest]: basically government messages and some, you know, in fact, I think my, my brother was

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:19.520
[Guest]: the one he started calling everyone to watch TV when the ads came on because the ads were

00:19:19.520 --> 00:19:20.520
[Guest]: in English.

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:23.320
[Guest]: Hey, the ads are on.

00:19:23.320 --> 00:19:25.640
[Guest]: And there was some cool jingle or something or the other.

00:19:25.640 --> 00:19:28.960
[Guest]: So at least that was culturally, you know, relevant.

00:19:28.960 --> 00:19:33.240
[Guest]: So I never really got into any of the, you know, Indian classical music or anything like

00:19:33.240 --> 00:19:34.240
[Guest]: that.

00:19:34.240 --> 00:19:37.920
[Guest]: In fact, it was almost like an imposition at times, like, can we please escape from

00:19:37.920 --> 00:19:40.120
[Guest]: this, give us something apart from this.

00:19:40.120 --> 00:19:45.240
[Guest]: And you know, that Sunday morning, He-Man used to come on, that was like one escape.

00:19:45.240 --> 00:19:51.120
[Guest]: Then there was another program, there's this German thing called Transtell, at least it

00:19:51.120 --> 00:19:56.240
[Guest]: was not in Hindi, so, you know, it was a little bit more understandable.

00:19:56.240 --> 00:19:57.240
[Guest]: And you know, things like that.

00:19:57.240 --> 00:20:00.080
[Guest]: And once in a while, something would come on, and then suddenly a world would light

00:20:00.080 --> 00:20:01.080
[Guest]: up.

00:20:01.080 --> 00:20:04.880
[Guest]: And I remember watching like, see that Eagles, hell freezes over, they put that was like,

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:09.320
[Guest]: you know, more towards the 90s or whatever, by then things had gotten a bit better.

00:20:09.320 --> 00:20:16.920
[Guest]: But just the, you know, the whole retrieval of information became like, every little nugget

00:20:16.920 --> 00:20:22.960
[Guest]: was, you know, treasured, and like how they do sugarcane juice, they remove every last

00:20:22.960 --> 00:20:25.920
[Guest]: bit of juice, so that became a little bit more valuable.

00:20:25.920 --> 00:20:29.880
[Guest]: Now the information is so widely available, even in fact, if I give you like the best

00:20:29.880 --> 00:20:32.800
[Guest]: advice in the world, there's a chance it will just get wasted.

00:20:32.800 --> 00:20:36.400
[Guest]: You know, someone will think I was just another person giving some gyaan, there's a chance

00:20:36.400 --> 00:20:37.400
[Guest]: like that.

00:20:37.400 --> 00:20:41.200
[Guest]: You know, so it's a very different world we live in today.

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:46.900
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, in fact, you know, one of your Black Shadows albums is called The Last Analog Generation.

00:20:46.900 --> 00:20:50.480
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you mentioned about how when your daughter was born, you kind of wanted

00:20:50.480 --> 00:20:55.220
[Amit Varma]: to document what has gone and we are the last analog generation in a sense.

00:20:55.220 --> 00:20:58.840
[Amit Varma]: So when you look at the way that she's growing up, for example, and you think of the way

00:20:58.840 --> 00:21:03.960
[Amit Varma]: that you grew up, what are the differences that you see in terms of how you're discovering

00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:08.040
[Amit Varma]: music, how you're experiencing music or anything else for that matter?

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:13.040
[Amit Varma]: Like not in terms of lamenting the good old days, or not in terms of passing a value judgment

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:20.000
[Amit Varma]: of one generation having a better time than the other, but just in terms of differences,

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:21.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, what have you noticed?

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:26.040
[Guest]: I mean, at this age, she's still getting a lot of the music from the parents, you know,

00:21:26.040 --> 00:21:30.600
[Guest]: so our tastes, you know, but now she is starting to discover like, I like certain things.

00:21:30.600 --> 00:21:36.000
[Guest]: So she'll make me make a playlist of her favorite songs that is then bhajaud ad infinitum in

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:37.000
[Guest]: the car.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:42.360
[Guest]: So, you know, we add her mercy, can we please not listen to that same song again?

00:21:42.360 --> 00:21:48.520
[Guest]: But apart from that, it's, I've noticed, like, as we get older, we get a little bit more

00:21:48.520 --> 00:21:53.200
[Guest]: judgmental about what is good and what is bad, where she doesn't have that, you know,

00:21:53.200 --> 00:21:57.200
[Guest]: if she likes it, she likes it, you know, she's not really analyzing it to that extent.

00:21:57.200 --> 00:21:58.660
[Guest]: It's got a good beat.

00:21:58.660 --> 00:21:59.720
[Guest]: That's the main thing.

00:21:59.720 --> 00:22:04.120
[Guest]: It's got a good melody, the chord changes are nice, notes, weird notes and stuff like

00:22:04.120 --> 00:22:05.120
[Guest]: that.

00:22:05.120 --> 00:22:06.120
[Guest]: It's all good.

00:22:06.120 --> 00:22:09.040
[Guest]: So I used to be the same way when I was a kid, you know, in that sense, humans are built

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:13.600
[Guest]: in similar ways, where it will change is when she gets a little bit older, and she wants

00:22:13.600 --> 00:22:18.040
[Guest]: to, you know, like one of my nieces, I think is around 14 or 15.

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:20.040
[Guest]: Oh, no, now she must be 16 or something.

00:22:20.040 --> 00:22:21.360
[Guest]: So she was listening to Thin Lizzy.

00:22:21.360 --> 00:22:26.320
[Guest]: I was like, oh, you like Thin Lizzy, you know, and I gave her a few recommendations and I

00:22:26.320 --> 00:22:29.600
[Guest]: was like, whatever, good uncle and everything.

00:22:29.600 --> 00:22:30.600
[Guest]: But it's cool.

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:35.040
[Guest]: I mean, I think the good music will still find an audience, you know, the ones who are

00:22:35.040 --> 00:22:36.480
[Guest]: ready to look for it.

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:40.960
[Guest]: For them, it's easier now than ever, you know, you just go to Spotify or whatever and say,

00:22:40.960 --> 00:22:46.000
[Guest]: give me your best of Thin Lizzy and otherwise I had to go to the shop and order the cassette

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:49.680
[Guest]: which took like a month to come, you know, that sort of thing.

00:22:49.680 --> 00:22:54.400
[Guest]: So, you know, I don't know, it's kind of interesting, because in a certain way, humans will always

00:22:54.400 --> 00:22:56.640
[Guest]: be built a certain way.

00:22:56.640 --> 00:23:04.040
[Guest]: And in ways the ease of access is going to definitely be a fully different way of doing

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:05.040
[Unknown]: things.

00:23:05.040 --> 00:23:08.040
[Unknown]: I actually wanted to ask a little later, but it makes so much sense asking it now, which

00:23:08.040 --> 00:23:12.640
[Unknown]: is we will have a conversation on form versus content and all that later.

00:23:12.640 --> 00:23:17.440
[Unknown]: But do you think that in some sense, what music itself is changing, like when you were

00:23:17.440 --> 00:23:22.320
[Unknown]: growing up, and when we were growing up, it was audio only.

00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:28.880
[Unknown]: And today, it's almost hard to separate out music from say, a music video or to a completely

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:32.840
[Unknown]: new generation, like your niece, it might be the associated TikTok meme or something

00:23:32.840 --> 00:23:33.840
[Unknown]: like that.

00:23:33.840 --> 00:23:39.680
[Unknown]: Do you think that has a bearing on the music itself that, oh, there's also an associated

00:23:39.680 --> 00:23:40.680
[Unknown]: music video?

00:23:40.680 --> 00:23:45.800
[Unknown]: Like I can't think of do I want to know without thinking of that, that that music, that iconic

00:23:45.800 --> 00:23:51.320
[Unknown]: music video, for instance, is that something you thought about?

00:23:51.320 --> 00:23:54.280
[Guest]: I think with every generation, there'll always be curious ones.

00:23:54.280 --> 00:23:57.320
[Guest]: And there'll always be ones will just follow the trend and listen to whatever's dished

00:23:57.320 --> 00:23:58.320
[Guest]: out to them.

00:23:58.320 --> 00:24:01.160
[Guest]: There'll be ones who are prepared to look and dig deeper.

00:24:01.160 --> 00:24:02.160
[Guest]: And those ones will find it.

00:24:02.160 --> 00:24:06.480
[Guest]: But I don't know, in terms of percentages, you know, how many of them will be one versus

00:24:06.480 --> 00:24:07.480
[Guest]: the other.

00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:11.200
[Guest]: You know, but there'll always be people I'm telling with every generation, there'll be

00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:15.240
[Guest]: someone who's listening to BB King or whatever, there'll be someone who's as long as it's

00:24:15.240 --> 00:24:16.240
[Guest]: there, it's accessible.

00:24:16.240 --> 00:24:19.920
[Guest]: For example, if his music has gone from all the servers or something like that, then it

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:21.840
[Guest]: may be a little bit tough.

00:24:21.840 --> 00:24:25.000
[Guest]: Then they'll have to go and dig out vinyls and find a vinyl player to play it and all

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:26.000
[Guest]: that kind of stuff.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:31.000
[Guest]: But as long as it's available, you know, and the ease of access also becomes a big part

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:35.800
[Guest]: of the thing, because if you notice like the ones whose videos are easily found on on YouTube,

00:24:35.800 --> 00:24:40.960
[Guest]: for example, will be, you know, getting across to younger listeners more easily than the

00:24:40.960 --> 00:24:41.960
[Unknown]: ones who don't.

00:24:41.960 --> 00:24:42.960
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:24:42.960 --> 00:24:47.720
[Unknown]: Mike, the question, though, I was actually getting it was is what we consider as music

00:24:47.720 --> 00:24:54.000
[Unknown]: is that changing from only audio to something that is audio plus visual and who knows when

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:58.280
[Unknown]: in the metaverse it might be audio plus visual plus how you're feeling and all that.

00:24:58.280 --> 00:24:59.520
[Guest]: That's really what I was getting to.

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:04.560
[Guest]: It's always been changing ever since MTV came out, you know, which was what, 1981, you know.

00:25:04.560 --> 00:25:05.560
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:25:05.560 --> 00:25:08.160
[Guest]: The moment it became visual, there was no turning back from that.

00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:14.200
[Guest]: And then it'll only go further from being a purely audio form, you know.

00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:15.200
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:25:15.200 --> 00:25:18.520
[Guest]: I mean, I'm still able to listen to music without any distractions.

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:21.760
[Guest]: Once in a while, maybe I'll pick up my phone and, you know, if a message comes on or something

00:25:21.760 --> 00:25:25.760
[Guest]: like which is why I tend to like disable notifications on all devices like fuck that.

00:25:25.760 --> 00:25:27.000
[Guest]: If I want to check it, I'll check it.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:29.480
[Guest]: Otherwise, don't tell me when to check, you know, that sort of thing.

00:25:29.480 --> 00:25:34.800
[Guest]: But, I mean, it's going to be different for different people.

00:25:34.800 --> 00:25:38.960
[Guest]: Different people will have the ability to devote their attention span to listening to

00:25:38.960 --> 00:25:41.800
[Guest]: an entire album, A Dark Side of the Moon, for example.

00:25:41.800 --> 00:25:45.280
[Guest]: And the first time you listen to it, it'll blow your mind, you know, but then who wants

00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:46.280
[Guest]: to listen to it?

00:25:46.280 --> 00:25:50.800
[Guest]: You have to see how many of them are there versus the ones who, you know, think money

00:25:50.800 --> 00:25:53.360
[Guest]: is something that you pay.

00:25:53.360 --> 00:25:54.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:25:54.360 --> 00:25:57.920
[Amit Varma]: Speaking of MTV, I actually worked there for a bit in the 90s.

00:25:57.920 --> 00:26:01.160
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, and the first video ever was Video Killed the Radio Star.

00:26:01.160 --> 00:26:06.160
[Amit Varma]: So maybe a more appropriate anthem would be Influencer Killed the Musician Star, which

00:26:06.160 --> 00:26:08.480
[Amit Varma]: might be kind of coming upon us.

00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:13.440
[Amit Varma]: My other question is that I agree with you when you say that in every generation, there'll

00:26:13.440 --> 00:26:17.860
[Amit Varma]: be kids who will want to go outside the beaten track in terms of whatever the mainstream

00:26:17.860 --> 00:26:22.400
[Amit Varma]: stuff is and discover their own music and their taste will take them wherever they do.

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:27.840
[Amit Varma]: But could it also be said that the notion of a mainstream has changed, if not dissolved?

00:26:27.840 --> 00:26:31.880
[Amit Varma]: Like Steve Van Zandt of the E Street Band, in an interview, he spoke about how rock was

00:26:31.880 --> 00:26:37.760
[Amit Varma]: mainstream for like, 30 years, from the Beatles or Ellen going electric to maybe Nirvana.

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:42.760
[Amit Varma]: And after that, everything kind of just splintered and there is no longer one mainstream and

00:26:42.760 --> 00:26:48.040
[Amit Varma]: that is a trend I see happening across everything else, not just music, like in terms of media,

00:26:48.040 --> 00:26:51.600
[Amit Varma]: you had a consensus on the truth, you had these mainstream outlets.

00:26:51.600 --> 00:26:57.400
[Amit Varma]: And now it's completely dispersed, you know, people get their sort of narratives from all

00:26:57.400 --> 00:27:00.680
[Amit Varma]: over the place, there is no more a consensus and truth.

00:27:00.680 --> 00:27:06.200
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, you know, just in terms of entertainment, would it be the case that tastes are much

00:27:06.200 --> 00:27:12.760
[Amit Varma]: more dispersed and fragmented, which of course, would have the negative impact that musicians,

00:27:12.760 --> 00:27:14.480
[Amit Varma]: it becomes harder to make money.

00:27:14.480 --> 00:27:18.320
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, you could say that it becomes easier to make money in a way because

00:27:18.320 --> 00:27:23.560
[Amit Varma]: a long tail is enabled, because many more people can form what Kevin Kelly called, you

00:27:23.560 --> 00:27:26.680
[Amit Varma]: know, thousand true fans, and you can reach out to them.

00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:29.720
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, these sort of conflicting thoughts kind of come to me.

00:27:29.720 --> 00:27:31.880
[Guest]: So what's, what's your sense of it?

00:27:31.880 --> 00:27:34.920
[Guest]: You ever noticed like, when we were kids, and there were only two channels, there's

00:27:34.920 --> 00:27:37.480
[Guest]: a bigger chance that everyone watched the same thing.

00:27:37.480 --> 00:27:41.480
[Guest]: Then when Star TV came, and, you know, then someone was watching this some, you know,

00:27:41.480 --> 00:27:48.200
[Guest]: that splintering has kept going on with technology as we get to the point.

00:27:48.200 --> 00:27:53.760
[Guest]: It also depends upon how easily influenced you are by your peer group as well.

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:57.560
[Guest]: You know, suddenly someone, I remember one friend, hey, look at this band from the States

00:27:57.560 --> 00:27:58.560
[Guest]: Nirvana.

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:00.360
[Guest]: Like, you know, suddenly everyone got into that.

00:28:00.360 --> 00:28:03.120
[Guest]: And that's how it kind of spread in that sense.

00:28:03.120 --> 00:28:08.220
[Guest]: So I mean, we're still social in that way, we're not kind of isolated from each other.

00:28:08.220 --> 00:28:13.360
[Guest]: So there's a chance of, you know, at least that kind of spread among, you know, like

00:28:13.360 --> 00:28:21.800
[Guest]: a social group, for example, with regards to reaching an audience.

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:25.840
[Guest]: I don't know, man, because the thing is, right now, everything is up in the air, first of

00:28:25.840 --> 00:28:31.960
[Guest]: all, because you're not competing for, you're competing for attention spans, basically,

00:28:31.960 --> 00:28:33.860
[Guest]: with everything else that's out there.

00:28:33.860 --> 00:28:35.520
[Guest]: Not just music.

00:28:35.520 --> 00:28:40.440
[Guest]: You're competing with video games, with, you know, sport, with everything else.

00:28:40.440 --> 00:28:43.360
[Guest]: Because the thing is around whatever you're interested in, you can just go and find so

00:28:43.360 --> 00:28:46.240
[Guest]: much content, there's no way you're going to get through it all.

00:28:46.240 --> 00:28:53.040
[Guest]: You know, if I suddenly get into Stratocaster Bridges, for example, I can find like a year's

00:28:53.040 --> 00:28:54.280
[Guest]: worth of content to watch.

00:28:54.280 --> 00:28:58.240
[Guest]: Now, I'm not that interested in it, I'm like somewhat interested, I'm just saying the fact

00:28:58.240 --> 00:29:03.120
[Guest]: that there's one year of content to watch about Stratocaster Bridges, whereas if I had

00:29:03.120 --> 00:29:09.440
[Guest]: to see a guitar on TV, I would feel happy.

00:29:09.440 --> 00:29:12.360
[Guest]: So I don't know, man, I think we just live in a strange world.

00:29:12.360 --> 00:29:15.520
[Guest]: It's kind of hard to predict and say, you know, this is what's going to happen.

00:29:15.520 --> 00:29:20.320
[Guest]: First of all, you don't even know the whole metaverse thing, how it's going to, you know,

00:29:20.320 --> 00:29:21.320
[Guest]: play out.

00:29:21.320 --> 00:29:23.480
[Guest]: For me personally, it scares the hell out of me.

00:29:23.480 --> 00:29:29.840
[Guest]: But then I feel like an old person who, when the internet came, like, what is this internet?

00:29:29.840 --> 00:29:34.240
[Guest]: So I mean, you kind of need to adapt and just keep an open mind.

00:29:34.240 --> 00:29:37.880
[Guest]: But obviously, if there's things that show that they're going to be harmful to us as

00:29:37.880 --> 00:29:44.080
[Guest]: a society, and as a planet or whatever, you know, it's a famous video of Bill Gates and

00:29:44.080 --> 00:29:49.480
[Amit Varma]: David Letterman, I think circa 96 or something and Letterman's making fun of him saying what

00:29:49.480 --> 00:29:53.760
[Amit Varma]: is this internet thing and all of that and Bill Gates is like, you can get sports update

00:29:53.760 --> 00:29:57.120
[Amit Varma]: and David Letterman is like, but I can turn on the radio for that.

00:29:57.120 --> 00:30:04.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, so I really hesitate to be negative about say, web three or, you know, any of

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:07.240
[Amit Varma]: these newfangled things I don't understand, because my assumption is maybe there's something

00:30:07.240 --> 00:30:12.480
[Amit Varma]: I don't get maybe we are the uncles, but just sort of going back to just following up on,

00:30:12.480 --> 00:30:16.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, what you just said, that, you know, when the three of us mentioned the Beatles,

00:30:16.960 --> 00:30:23.680
[Amit Varma]: it is immediately understood that we all know the Beatles that there is a common place in

00:30:23.680 --> 00:30:28.320
[Amit Varma]: our consciousness that the Beatles holds that in a sense, you know, Ted Joyer used a lovely

00:30:28.320 --> 00:30:33.080
[Amit Varma]: phrase where he said that music is like a kind of cloud memory that sort of connects

00:30:33.080 --> 00:30:34.080
[Amit Varma]: people in this manner.

00:30:34.080 --> 00:30:39.400
[Amit Varma]: And that's the thing that I wonder if the next generation will not have that one person's

00:30:39.400 --> 00:30:44.260
[Amit Varma]: Beatles won't be the other person's Beatles, because they've just gone on such incredibly

00:30:44.260 --> 00:30:45.260
[Amit Varma]: different tracks.

00:30:45.260 --> 00:30:49.840
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, when when I get into YouTube rabbit holes, you know, I have a regular account.

00:30:49.840 --> 00:30:53.640
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, I said that, okay, just to understand it a little better, I need to

00:30:53.640 --> 00:30:58.080
[Amit Varma]: understand what the Hindutva right wing rabbit holes are like those extreme guys.

00:30:58.080 --> 00:31:00.280
[Amit Varma]: But I didn't want it to mess up my algorithm.

00:31:00.280 --> 00:31:04.080
[Amit Varma]: So I incognito window, a different Google account.

00:31:04.080 --> 00:31:09.040
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is that now, those are two completely different YouTubes, those two different YouTubes

00:31:09.040 --> 00:31:13.360
[Amit Varma]: that I see on my regular account, and my incognito account have no relation to each other.

00:31:13.360 --> 00:31:18.000
[Amit Varma]: And I think that's analogous of the experience that different young people have today, where

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:21.840
[Amit Varma]: they're not actually watching a common stream, where there is no Beatles as such.

00:31:21.840 --> 00:31:25.860
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I remember Jonathan Haidt once said that you might think that kids today would

00:31:25.860 --> 00:31:30.280
[Amit Varma]: understand the past much better, because everything all of history, it's available to them.

00:31:30.280 --> 00:31:34.560
[Amit Varma]: But his point was that everybody is watching content that was created in the last three

00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:36.240
[Amit Varma]: days, you know.

00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:42.880
[Amit Varma]: So we are constantly sort of in this chakra view, as it were, where content keeps coming,

00:31:42.880 --> 00:31:46.360
[Amit Varma]: we keep watching, but there's no space for sitting back and reflection.

00:31:46.360 --> 00:31:48.160
[Amit Varma]: Those common connections aren't there.

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:50.800
[Amit Varma]: So a bit of a ramble, but any thoughts?

00:31:50.800 --> 00:31:56.880
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, it, I mean, we should be actually listening to what these right wing people

00:31:56.880 --> 00:32:00.280
[Guest]: are on about just so we understand that they're not crazy.

00:32:00.280 --> 00:32:03.600
[Guest]: There's obviously something that's, that's going on in their heads.

00:32:03.600 --> 00:32:08.040
[Guest]: And the only way to reach some kind of a conciliation, because at the end, we're all humans, we have

00:32:08.040 --> 00:32:12.280
[Guest]: to share the same planet, there's no point, like, spewing hate, whichever side of the

00:32:12.280 --> 00:32:16.680
[Guest]: battle or whatever you're on, the very fact that there's become such a, you know, a huge

00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:22.240
[Guest]: divide between us as a society is like, really alarming, you know, everywhere you go, every

00:32:22.240 --> 00:32:24.440
[Guest]: country, you kind of find like that kind of conflict.

00:32:24.440 --> 00:32:30.920
[Guest]: And if these algorithms are only fueling that further, because no one is getting to see

00:32:30.920 --> 00:32:36.280
[Guest]: the other point of view, that whole us and them happens, you know, you, you guys suck,

00:32:36.280 --> 00:32:37.280
[Guest]: you guys suck.

00:32:37.280 --> 00:32:41.160
[Guest]: I mean, like, both sides have got some, you know, bad things about it, that you can take

00:32:41.160 --> 00:32:42.160
[Guest]: each side too far.

00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:47.280
[Guest]: If you can go like, there are crazy people in the left wing as well, you know, so I guess

00:32:47.280 --> 00:32:51.720
[Guest]: at the point where we can somewhat understand what each other has to say, okay, I get like,

00:32:51.720 --> 00:32:57.000
[Guest]: you don't like what this does or whatever, but at least let's, you know, eat what we

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:01.840
[Guest]: want to eat, wear what we want to wear, do what we, without harming, basically, the,

00:33:01.840 --> 00:33:05.880
[Guest]: every religion should just scrap all their books and put one rule, don't be an asshole.

00:33:05.880 --> 00:33:06.880
[Guest]: That's it.

00:33:06.880 --> 00:33:10.400
[Guest]: For now, I think this is the only message the world needs, don't be an asshole.

00:33:10.400 --> 00:33:14.240
[Guest]: You know, in our own lives, we find the times where we are an asshole.

00:33:14.240 --> 00:33:19.840
[Guest]: So like, let's not be assholes for a little while, till things get a bit better.

00:33:19.840 --> 00:33:22.040
[Amit Varma]: You could form a new religion around that.

00:33:22.040 --> 00:33:24.040
[Unknown]: Yeah, man, just don't be an asshole.

00:33:24.040 --> 00:33:25.040
[Unknown]: That's it.

00:33:25.040 --> 00:33:27.040
[Unknown]: There were two trains of thought running in my head.

00:33:27.040 --> 00:33:32.160
[Unknown]: One, you said that most of the content that we consume right now happened in the last

00:33:32.160 --> 00:33:33.160
[Unknown]: three days.

00:33:33.160 --> 00:33:37.960
[Unknown]: And there's another article related to music that both of us read, which is new music is,

00:33:37.960 --> 00:33:39.920
[Unknown]: old music is killing new music.

00:33:39.920 --> 00:33:44.000
[Unknown]: And Warren, I'm guessing you saw that as well, because Rick Beato did a video on that too.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:49.520
[Unknown]: And one of the astonishing facts over there was increasingly people are listening to older

00:33:49.520 --> 00:33:50.520
[Unknown]: music.

00:33:50.520 --> 00:33:55.320
[Unknown]: And I have struggled to reconcile my head around these two facts at the same time.

00:33:55.320 --> 00:33:58.000
[Unknown]: Maybe there is no answer over here, but I just wanted to know what you thought about

00:33:58.000 --> 00:33:59.000
[Unknown]: that.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:01.080
[Unknown]: Because people are listening to older music.

00:34:01.080 --> 00:34:05.360
[Unknown]: Another video that Rick Beato had done was actually he had compared the following that

00:34:05.360 --> 00:34:08.320
[Unknown]: new artists had along with older artists.

00:34:08.320 --> 00:34:12.640
[Unknown]: And it was quite surprising because some of the legacy artists like Queen, for instance,

00:34:12.640 --> 00:34:17.240
[Unknown]: had a lot of subscribers and were very relevant to even his son's generation, for example.

00:34:17.240 --> 00:34:22.160
[Unknown]: Just wanted to know what you thought about that, that on one hand, you have, okay, there's

00:34:22.160 --> 00:34:25.880
[Unknown]: so much content being created, and we're consuming everything that's being created, a lot of

00:34:25.880 --> 00:34:28.360
[Unknown]: the stuff that we're consuming happened in the last three days.

00:34:28.360 --> 00:34:33.520
[Unknown]: And at the same time, a lot of the legacy content is also being consumed, be it books,

00:34:33.520 --> 00:34:35.720
[Unknown]: be it music, be it films even.

00:34:35.720 --> 00:34:38.160
[Unknown]: So yeah, I just wanted to get your take on that.

00:34:38.160 --> 00:34:43.160
[Guest]: Basically, the algorithms work like this, things become more popular, as they become

00:34:43.160 --> 00:34:44.160
[Guest]: more popular.

00:34:44.160 --> 00:34:45.160
[Guest]: You know what I mean?

00:34:45.160 --> 00:34:46.760
[Guest]: Yeah, that's how it works.

00:34:46.760 --> 00:34:51.680
[Guest]: So now the Queen thing, for example, I traced it to that movie, which was hugely popular.

00:34:51.680 --> 00:34:54.320
[Guest]: You know, that kind of drove a huge spike in listeners.

00:34:54.320 --> 00:34:57.720
[Guest]: And then because of that, more people got to listen to it.

00:34:57.720 --> 00:35:01.160
[Guest]: So the more people listen to it, the more people get to listen to it.

00:35:01.160 --> 00:35:02.160
[Guest]: You know what I mean?

00:35:02.160 --> 00:35:03.640
[Guest]: That's just how it works.

00:35:03.640 --> 00:35:06.800
[Guest]: With the Beatles now, this get back thing just came out.

00:35:06.800 --> 00:35:12.280
[Guest]: So again, I'm just looking at musicians my age as well, more people are talking about

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:13.280
[Guest]: it.

00:35:13.280 --> 00:35:17.080
[Guest]: So it was kind of like, yeah, everyone knows what the Beatles is, right, and how this like

00:35:17.080 --> 00:35:21.400
[Guest]: kids also are, you know, being, you know, faced with that, you know, this is what's

00:35:21.400 --> 00:35:22.400
[Guest]: coming out.

00:35:22.400 --> 00:35:23.400
[Guest]: And it becomes popular.

00:35:23.400 --> 00:35:24.400
[Guest]: So people talk about it.

00:35:24.400 --> 00:35:25.920
[Guest]: So you want to go in and check it out.

00:35:25.920 --> 00:35:26.920
[Unknown]: Yeah, that's interesting.

00:35:26.920 --> 00:35:30.800
[Unknown]: This is kind of like stuff from the past is being repurposed in various ways.

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:32.280
[Unknown]: And then that drives spikes.

00:35:32.280 --> 00:35:36.200
[Unknown]: There's this interesting thing that happened a couple of years back, the TikTok Fleetwood

00:35:36.200 --> 00:35:37.200
[Unknown]: Mac thing.

00:35:37.200 --> 00:35:38.360
[Unknown]: I don't know if you guys remember this.

00:35:38.360 --> 00:35:41.960
[Guest]: So the guy drinking that, yeah, on the skateboard.

00:35:41.960 --> 00:35:45.960
[Unknown]: Yeah, so for those who don't know what this is about, especially since we can't see TikTok

00:35:45.960 --> 00:35:52.000
[Unknown]: here in India, there was a video of a guy, it wasn't a content creator and influencer

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:53.000
[Unknown]: or anything like that.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:55.680
[Unknown]: He was drinking a juice called Ocean Spray.

00:35:55.680 --> 00:35:58.080
[Unknown]: And he was skateboarding down his road.

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:02.600
[Unknown]: And he was humming along to Dreams, I think it was by Fleetwood Mac, and he was just humming

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:03.600
[Unknown]: it out.

00:36:03.600 --> 00:36:08.240
[Unknown]: And for no reason at all that managed to go viral, it became a meme of his own, Mick Fleetwood.

00:36:08.240 --> 00:36:11.760
[Unknown]: And I think Stevie Nicks also did their own versions of this.

00:36:11.760 --> 00:36:13.440
[Unknown]: And this led to Ocean Spray.

00:36:13.440 --> 00:36:17.480
[Unknown]: It was not a branded campaign by them or anything, but it ended up becoming a huge thing for

00:36:17.480 --> 00:36:18.640
[Unknown]: the brand.

00:36:18.640 --> 00:36:24.080
[Unknown]: And the song entered the Billboard Top 100 after what 30-40 years.

00:36:24.080 --> 00:36:26.160
[Unknown]: I guess that's an example of what you're talking about.

00:36:26.160 --> 00:36:30.760
[Unknown]: It is some random accident somewhere or a planned cultural event like a Queen movie

00:36:30.760 --> 00:36:35.280
[Unknown]: or a Beatles documentary that brings a lot of these old things back and makes them relevant

00:36:35.280 --> 00:36:40.200
[Unknown]: again for a younger audience as well as oldies like us who just want to relive some of that.

00:36:40.200 --> 00:36:42.120
[Unknown]: So I guess there's something over there.

00:36:42.120 --> 00:36:46.880
[Guest]: Yeah, because I guess when I was a kid, I was listening to the Beatles while the other

00:36:46.880 --> 00:36:50.080
[Guest]: kids in my class were listening to Guns N' Roses.

00:36:50.080 --> 00:36:52.760
[Guest]: Because I remember one girl telling me, why are you listening to this old fashioned music?

00:36:52.760 --> 00:36:57.880
[Guest]: I said, like, you know, this is like, what I want to listen to.

00:36:57.880 --> 00:37:01.600
[Guest]: And then I learned sweet child of mine on the guitar just to like, you know, shut her

00:37:01.600 --> 00:37:03.800
[Unknown]: up.

00:37:03.800 --> 00:37:07.640
[Unknown]: You remind me of that TikToker who had again, it goes back to TikTok again, you remember

00:37:07.640 --> 00:37:11.520
[Unknown]: that Metallica girl from last year?

00:37:11.520 --> 00:37:15.600
[Unknown]: She is an R&B singer and hip hopper or something and she was wearing a Metallica t-shirt and

00:37:15.600 --> 00:37:20.560
[Unknown]: metal fans being metal fans, like a hip hop person wearing a Metallica thing, bet you

00:37:20.560 --> 00:37:22.240
[Unknown]: don't even know three Metallica songs.

00:37:22.240 --> 00:37:26.400
[Unknown]: And she went on her next video and said, I can, instead of naming them, I'd rather just

00:37:26.400 --> 00:37:27.400
[Unknown]: play them for you on the guitar.

00:37:27.400 --> 00:37:31.200
[Unknown]: And she shredded her way through Master of Puppets, the solo of one and a couple of others

00:37:31.200 --> 00:37:32.200
[Unknown]: as well.

00:37:32.200 --> 00:37:33.200
[Amit Varma]: So yeah.

00:37:33.200 --> 00:37:38.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I was speaking of that phenomenon, I mean, and even before this, I remember a few

00:37:38.240 --> 00:37:41.920
[Amit Varma]: years back, forget TikTok, there was a TV commercial, I think a Volkswagen with Nick

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:43.440
[Amit Varma]: Drake's Pink Moon.

00:37:43.440 --> 00:37:46.680
[Amit Varma]: And Nick Drake suddenly became a big for a short while again, which is great, because

00:37:46.680 --> 00:37:50.720
[Amit Varma]: I love the guy though, that's not perhaps his favorite song of mine.

00:37:50.720 --> 00:37:54.080
[Amit Varma]: But you know, what you said about what is popular, you know, lead that that sort of

00:37:54.080 --> 00:37:56.920
[Amit Varma]: vicious circle that starts reminds me of this experiment.

00:37:56.920 --> 00:38:01.520
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if I'll be able to, if I remember the details well enough, but the whole idea

00:38:01.520 --> 00:38:07.760
[Amit Varma]: of the experiment was that these guys gave an app with a few 1000 songs to a couple of

00:38:07.760 --> 00:38:10.560
[Amit Varma]: 100 kids, but they programmed those apps.

00:38:10.560 --> 00:38:14.680
[Amit Varma]: So it would randomly show which you know, which were the 10 most played ones and which

00:38:14.680 --> 00:38:16.080
[Amit Varma]: were the most popular.

00:38:16.080 --> 00:38:20.680
[Amit Varma]: So all of them had different top 10 lists in their apps, you know, like not 300 different,

00:38:20.680 --> 00:38:22.920
[Amit Varma]: but maybe 30 different 10 people each.

00:38:22.920 --> 00:38:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, that's exactly what happened, what Warren said, the stuff that was already

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:28.160
[Amit Varma]: on the charts got listened to more.

00:38:28.160 --> 00:38:30.360
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, it kind of spiraled.

00:38:30.360 --> 00:38:36.280
[Amit Varma]: And you had completely separate trajectories for the music in, you know, for each of the

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:41.080
[Amit Varma]: control groups, which is kind of fascinating, because that also sort of short tells you

00:38:41.080 --> 00:38:46.080
[Amit Varma]: a little bit about just the role of sheer dumb luck, that if you kind of happen to somehow

00:38:46.080 --> 00:38:50.520
[Amit Varma]: make it, then you continue making it like that whole Billy Joel story about how Piano

00:38:50.520 --> 00:38:52.640
[Amit Varma]: Man came out, and then it was going nowhere.

00:38:52.640 --> 00:38:58.360
[Amit Varma]: And his label was just, you know, had given up on him and, you know, and then this one

00:38:58.360 --> 00:39:02.400
[Amit Varma]: guy who was passionate about it started taking it around to all the radio stations, and somebody

00:39:02.400 --> 00:39:03.560
[Amit Varma]: gave it a play.

00:39:03.560 --> 00:39:07.080
[Amit Varma]: And after it was dead, it is revived, and Billy Joel becomes Billy Joel.

00:39:07.080 --> 00:39:13.240
[Unknown]: But yeah, but arguably, luck has played a role throughout history right now, our context

00:39:13.240 --> 00:39:15.640
[Unknown]: for that is Spotify algorithms.

00:39:15.640 --> 00:39:17.320
[Unknown]: Back in the day, it might have been something else.

00:39:17.320 --> 00:39:23.320
[Unknown]: What if George had sorry, what if Paul had never met john for whatever reason that day?

00:39:23.320 --> 00:39:27.000
[Unknown]: So yeah, I guess we can all these are what ifs experiments except now instead of meeting

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:32.680
[Unknown]: in a place now it's, did you discover this on tik tok or something like that?

00:39:32.680 --> 00:39:35.560
[Guest]: I've got a killer idea for a movie, by the way.

00:39:35.560 --> 00:39:41.680
[Guest]: So there's this band from the 70s, like relatively popular band from the 70s.

00:39:41.680 --> 00:39:46.960
[Guest]: And they're in their tour bus and the tour bus hit some kind of weird wormhole and they

00:39:46.960 --> 00:39:52.280
[Guest]: get transported to, you know, I don't know what COVID times were at least present day.

00:39:52.280 --> 00:39:59.960
[Guest]: And they have to suddenly deal with this thing called social media.

00:39:59.960 --> 00:40:03.560
[Guest]: And and also streaming services and everything, everything is like totally different.

00:40:03.560 --> 00:40:05.760
[Guest]: So like how they deal with that.

00:40:05.760 --> 00:40:12.800
[Guest]: And my idea was for these like macho metal guys to meet a band of young girls who then

00:40:12.800 --> 00:40:15.400
[Guest]: shows them how to do this.

00:40:15.400 --> 00:40:18.520
[Unknown]: Yeah, actually, that actually sounds pretty interesting.

00:40:18.520 --> 00:40:22.320
[Unknown]: And that was another thing that Amit and I actually discovered, he asked me a very fascinating

00:40:22.320 --> 00:40:23.320
[Unknown]: question.

00:40:23.320 --> 00:40:25.040
[Unknown]: And I'd love to know what your take on this would be.

00:40:25.040 --> 00:40:28.680
[Unknown]: Suppose Watters and Gilmore actually form Pink Floyd today.

00:40:28.680 --> 00:40:29.920
[Unknown]: How would things be different?

00:40:29.920 --> 00:40:33.080
[Guest]: Man, there's no Rick, right?

00:40:33.080 --> 00:40:39.920
[Guest]: I was like the secret weapon, anyway, yeah, being a purist aside.

00:40:39.920 --> 00:40:40.920
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:40:40.920 --> 00:40:42.080
[Guest]: I think they'd still be able to make good music.

00:40:42.080 --> 00:40:43.520
[Guest]: I wouldn't put it past them.

00:40:43.520 --> 00:40:46.120
[Guest]: You know, it just depends on what time and place they are.

00:40:46.120 --> 00:40:51.000
[Guest]: Because musicians are always, you know, always changing, like there's not there's not one

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:56.120
[Guest]: particular mindset, there's always 150 things we could be doing, it just depends what appeals

00:40:56.120 --> 00:41:00.120
[Guest]: at that particular time, suddenly, the wind changes, and they decide, okay, it's a good

00:41:00.120 --> 00:41:02.440
[Guest]: idea to work together, then you've got it.

00:41:02.440 --> 00:41:03.440
[Guest]: And if not, then not.

00:41:03.440 --> 00:41:09.640
[Amit Varma]: No, I think I think our speculation really was that, because like, if they were young

00:41:09.640 --> 00:41:13.560
[Amit Varma]: today and growing up today, they the palette of music they would listen to would be completely

00:41:13.560 --> 00:41:14.560
[Amit Varma]: different.

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:17.880
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, who knows what direction they would go in.

00:41:17.880 --> 00:41:22.480
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, you know, to return to the subject of your sort of evolving years, there is also

00:41:22.480 --> 00:41:25.080
[Amit Varma]: the counterfactual that if you weren't born in the family you were born in, where your

00:41:25.080 --> 00:41:29.080
[Amit Varma]: father is a bass guitarist, and your uncle is a lawyer and all of that, that if you weren't

00:41:29.080 --> 00:41:33.640
[Amit Varma]: exposed to that kind of music, if you were, you know, in a South Indian family, listening

00:41:33.640 --> 00:41:38.280
[Amit Varma]: to Carnatic, or if you were, you know, somewhere else listening only to Bollywood in a village

00:41:38.280 --> 00:41:41.640
[Amit Varma]: in Bihar, totally different directions, different counterfactuals.

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:46.600
[Amit Varma]: But tell me a little bit about, you know, then how you got sort of turned on to playing

00:41:46.600 --> 00:41:51.720
[Amit Varma]: music, what your other early influences were like, I remember you talking about how your

00:41:51.720 --> 00:41:55.160
[Amit Varma]: dad when he first showed you chords on the guitar, he showed you A minor and E, which

00:41:55.160 --> 00:41:58.960
[Amit Varma]: aren't really the typical sort of standard ones.

00:41:58.960 --> 00:42:04.440
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about, you know, that phase of your life where you're into music,

00:42:04.440 --> 00:42:09.000
[Amit Varma]: you're discovering music, you know, beyond the Beatles, you know, who else were the people

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:13.160
[Amit Varma]: you kind of fell in love with, and how did that sort of start evolving from this?

00:42:13.160 --> 00:42:18.840
[Guest]: So let's get to when the Beatles, rather the only Beatles phase was ending.

00:42:18.840 --> 00:42:20.200
[Guest]: So that was around 13.

00:42:20.200 --> 00:42:22.920
[Guest]: Now, the hormones have started to kick in.

00:42:22.920 --> 00:42:27.800
[Guest]: And by this time, I kind of started catching up with what the rest of the, you know, peer

00:42:27.800 --> 00:42:29.080
[Guest]: group was listening to.

00:42:29.080 --> 00:42:33.020
[Guest]: So I think Guns N' Roses had done Live and Let Die.

00:42:33.020 --> 00:42:35.560
[Guest]: So I say, oh, they've covered Paul McCartney, they can't be that bad.

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:36.560
[Guest]: Let me check it out.

00:42:36.560 --> 00:42:38.040
[Guest]: So I got that Illusion One album.

00:42:38.040 --> 00:42:41.880
[Guest]: That was the first one I actually listened to, in entirety, I'd listened to a couple

00:42:41.880 --> 00:42:45.420
[Guest]: of songs from Appetite, but this was like the first album listen.

00:42:45.420 --> 00:42:50.160
[Guest]: So I found it really enjoyable, November in came very lovely melodies, great guitar solos,

00:42:50.160 --> 00:42:52.800
[Guest]: I was like, yeah, this is some cool stuff.

00:42:52.800 --> 00:42:56.520
[Guest]: And then we had started seeing their videos also on Star TV around the same time.

00:42:56.520 --> 00:43:00.640
[Guest]: So it kind of, you know, everyone's Oh, Guns N' Roses, Guns N' Roses became a thing.

00:43:00.640 --> 00:43:02.640
[Guest]: So that was around 13.

00:43:02.640 --> 00:43:08.240
[Guest]: Then for some reason, I got a Kira and I started tracing back further, like, where are these

00:43:08.240 --> 00:43:09.240
[Guest]: guys coming from?

00:43:09.240 --> 00:43:10.840
[Guest]: And I got into Aerosmith.

00:43:10.840 --> 00:43:14.880
[Guest]: And then Led Zeppelin hit in a huge way, I think that was around, say, 15 or something

00:43:14.880 --> 00:43:15.880
[Guest]: like that.

00:43:15.880 --> 00:43:17.980
[Guest]: I got that Led Zeppelin 4 album.

00:43:17.980 --> 00:43:21.680
[Guest]: And then the next thing you know, I'm on one huge rabbit hole, as you tend to and then

00:43:21.680 --> 00:43:26.180
[Guest]: all my lunch money is going into buying cassettes, you know, that sort of thing.

00:43:26.180 --> 00:43:30.840
[Guest]: And during this time, the guitar became more of a social connection as well, because I

00:43:30.840 --> 00:43:34.720
[Guest]: had a friend, Johan, who I've known since I was a child, because our dads knew each

00:43:34.720 --> 00:43:35.720
[Guest]: other.

00:43:35.720 --> 00:43:39.640
[Guest]: Dads were musicians, but both were bass players, so they never played in the same band.

00:43:39.640 --> 00:43:43.320
[Guest]: So luckily for us, Johan played bass and I played guitar.

00:43:43.320 --> 00:43:45.960
[Guest]: In fact, actually, I started on bass when I was a kid.

00:43:45.960 --> 00:43:50.040
[Guest]: But my dad said, listen, you're probably going to get a lot better at music.

00:43:50.040 --> 00:43:55.000
[Guest]: If you learn to play guitar, it's more like harmony and everything, more open.

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:59.840
[Guest]: You can still play bass, but you know, don't forget to play guitar as well.

00:43:59.840 --> 00:44:02.680
[Guest]: So luckily around that time, I was playing guitar, he was playing bass, we started jamming

00:44:02.680 --> 00:44:03.680
[Guest]: together.

00:44:03.680 --> 00:44:07.320
[Guest]: And I used to go to his house, you know, we had just gotten out of school.

00:44:07.320 --> 00:44:10.360
[Guest]: He's one year older than me, both of us in the same school.

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:13.800
[Guest]: So we had gotten out of school and I used to go to his house to jam.

00:44:13.800 --> 00:44:17.520
[Guest]: He used to have this little drum machine that his dad had given him.

00:44:17.520 --> 00:44:19.720
[Guest]: So he used to program a beat on that.

00:44:19.720 --> 00:44:23.200
[Guest]: And he would play and both of us around the same time started listening to a lot of music

00:44:23.200 --> 00:44:27.000
[Guest]: together, like cream and a lot of classic rock.

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:30.400
[Guest]: You know, we had this one MCA Records compilation.

00:44:30.400 --> 00:44:36.080
[Guest]: So there was Lynyrd Skynyrd, Freebird, and a whole bunch of songs like Born to be Wild

00:44:36.080 --> 00:44:37.080
[Guest]: and all that kind of thing.

00:44:37.080 --> 00:44:39.040
[Guest]: I still remember to this day.

00:44:39.040 --> 00:44:43.680
[Guest]: So we started listening to music together, started trading cassettes and that kind of

00:44:43.680 --> 00:44:44.680
[Guest]: stuff.

00:44:44.680 --> 00:44:48.920
[Guest]: I remember one day we were sitting and jamming and he was playing bass along with the drum

00:44:48.920 --> 00:44:49.920
[Guest]: machine and I was playing guitar.

00:44:49.920 --> 00:44:52.440
[Guest]: I was so like absorbed in what I was playing.

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:57.280
[Guest]: I woke up and I was like, I opened my eyes and I went to talk to him and he had left

00:44:57.280 --> 00:44:58.280
[Guest]: the room.

00:44:58.280 --> 00:45:00.400
[Guest]: He had programmed the bass line as well in that machine and he had left.

00:45:00.400 --> 00:45:04.280
[Guest]: I was in an empty room with the guitar.

00:45:04.280 --> 00:45:09.400
[Guest]: So we had a lot of these like nice formative, you know, like just playing with other musicians

00:45:09.400 --> 00:45:10.480
[Guest]: that became a big thing.

00:45:10.480 --> 00:45:16.280
[Guest]: And then he had these next door neighbors, Rajiv and Bobby, who then I later on got into

00:45:16.280 --> 00:45:17.640
[Guest]: a band with them.

00:45:17.640 --> 00:45:23.760
[Guest]: But they had a kind of a jam thing where it wasn't really like a band where we went and

00:45:23.760 --> 00:45:24.760
[Guest]: played gigs and stuff.

00:45:24.760 --> 00:45:27.280
[Guest]: We just get together and play music.

00:45:27.280 --> 00:45:33.160
[Guest]: So this kind of went along for like around a year.

00:45:33.160 --> 00:45:38.280
[Guest]: And then Sid Cooter, who was another childhood friend, but he had never lived in Bombay.

00:45:38.280 --> 00:45:42.040
[Guest]: His dad was always, you know, traveling outside the city.

00:45:42.040 --> 00:45:44.640
[Guest]: He came back to Bombay after like many years.

00:45:44.640 --> 00:45:49.520
[Guest]: So my mom kind of, you know, made sure because he lived down the road, you know, go be friends,

00:45:49.520 --> 00:45:50.520
[Guest]: you know how moms are.

00:45:50.520 --> 00:45:56.520
[Guest]: I remember when she said, you can't go jam unless you take him with you as well.

00:45:56.520 --> 00:45:59.880
[Guest]: So I had to go and call him and he came with his bright green guitar and everything.

00:45:59.880 --> 00:46:01.520
[Guest]: And he was louder than everyone else.

00:46:01.520 --> 00:46:04.120
[Guest]: I remember that.

00:46:04.120 --> 00:46:06.960
[Guest]: So then that kind of became a thing.

00:46:06.960 --> 00:46:10.800
[Guest]: And then Sid, Johan and me got into a band together called Vicious Circle.

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:16.000
[Guest]: And the whole deal with the band was we couldn't play anything after 1980.

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:17.520
[Guest]: That was a cut off.

00:46:17.520 --> 00:46:20.520
[Guest]: So anything after 1980 was not on the set list.

00:46:20.520 --> 00:46:23.680
[Guest]: So it kind of gave us some kind of a direction, you know.

00:46:23.680 --> 00:46:28.800
[Guest]: So we played everything from Deep Purple, Zep, the usual classic rock stuff.

00:46:28.800 --> 00:46:34.680
[Guest]: And the whole thing was Sid was playing drums and singing.

00:46:34.680 --> 00:46:37.800
[Guest]: So we played our first gig and he was behind the drums.

00:46:37.800 --> 00:46:41.760
[Guest]: And everyone said, you guys are lip syncing, there's no singer.

00:46:41.760 --> 00:46:43.400
[Guest]: So he got really bugged about that.

00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:47.600
[Guest]: He said, I'm never going to be, you know, doing this behind the drums singing again.

00:46:47.600 --> 00:46:48.600
[Guest]: We need to get a single.

00:46:48.600 --> 00:46:49.600
[Guest]: So he got a single.

00:46:49.600 --> 00:46:50.600
[Guest]: This guy called Sean Gomes.

00:46:50.600 --> 00:46:54.560
[Guest]: And he was a big Dire Straits and U2 fan.

00:46:54.560 --> 00:47:00.360
[Guest]: So some of that stuff also was incorporated into U2 kind of just about got in because

00:47:00.360 --> 00:47:04.960
[Guest]: like there was like one or two songs that were before 1980.

00:47:04.960 --> 00:47:07.920
[Guest]: So or, you know, 1980 itself.

00:47:07.920 --> 00:47:13.160
[Guest]: So that became like, like the first proper band where we actually got together and started

00:47:13.160 --> 00:47:14.880
[Guest]: practicing and all that kind of stuff.

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:16.200
[Guest]: And we actually got pretty tight.

00:47:16.200 --> 00:47:19.320
[Guest]: I remember we used to play Stormbringer and at the end of it, like, we used to look at

00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:21.680
[Guest]: each other like, wow, did we actually pull that off?

00:47:21.680 --> 00:47:24.600
[Guest]: And you know, it was like, not bad at all.

00:47:24.600 --> 00:47:28.800
[Guest]: We did our first gig at Razz and I remember the first time Sid told me, let's play a gig

00:47:28.800 --> 00:47:29.800
[Guest]: at Razz.

00:47:29.800 --> 00:47:30.800
[Guest]: I was like, what?

00:47:30.800 --> 00:47:31.800
[Guest]: Are you kidding?

00:47:31.800 --> 00:47:32.800
[Guest]: We'll never get to play there.

00:47:32.800 --> 00:47:37.120
[Guest]: So I was a very realistic guy, like, you know, there's no way I'm going to get to a point

00:47:37.120 --> 00:47:40.680
[Guest]: where we're playing at, you know, a proper place where people pay money to come and watch

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:42.080
[Guest]: you.

00:47:42.080 --> 00:47:43.480
[Guest]: So that happened.

00:47:43.480 --> 00:47:47.000
[Guest]: And just after that, that became like, you know, something that we worked and worked

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:48.000
[Guest]: towards.

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:51.320
[Guest]: And we did pretty well at that gig, all our friends came and watched everyone had a good

00:47:51.320 --> 00:47:52.320
[Guest]: time.

00:47:52.320 --> 00:47:55.740
[Guest]: We actually made a little bit of money or whatever, which we spent on food.

00:47:55.740 --> 00:48:00.540
[Guest]: So just after that gig, Johan left to study in the States.

00:48:00.540 --> 00:48:04.840
[Guest]: So now like back to square one, Sid and me were like, what do we do?

00:48:04.840 --> 00:48:06.380
[Guest]: So he had the right idea.

00:48:06.380 --> 00:48:11.400
[Guest]: The next door neighbors, they have a drum kit, let's call them.

00:48:11.400 --> 00:48:16.000
[Guest]: So that became, you know, what became Zero.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:21.200
[Guest]: And during this time in between, you know, the two bands, Sid and I started writing music

00:48:21.200 --> 00:48:23.640
[Guest]: together and we found it quite effortless.

00:48:23.640 --> 00:48:26.480
[Guest]: Like I would come up with a chord progression, he would sing something on top of it.

00:48:26.480 --> 00:48:29.840
[Guest]: Hey, we've got a song, you know, and we weren't really precious about it.

00:48:29.840 --> 00:48:33.160
[Guest]: That's the thing, when you're that age, you don't think too much about it, just do it.

00:48:33.160 --> 00:48:36.520
[Guest]: You know, you worry about, you worry later about what's going to happen with this song

00:48:36.520 --> 00:48:38.080
[Guest]: and everything like that.

00:48:38.080 --> 00:48:43.800
[Guest]: So I think we had written Not My Kind of Girl, a song called Dear Jesus, which not too many

00:48:43.800 --> 00:48:44.800
[Guest]: people have heard.

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:48.240
[Guest]: And a couple of other songs like that, and they were mainly like, you know, chill out

00:48:48.240 --> 00:48:49.240
[Guest]: music.

00:48:49.240 --> 00:48:53.600
[Guest]: No, it wasn't like, you know, loud, heavy rock and stuff like that.

00:48:53.600 --> 00:48:59.000
[Guest]: So when we finally got together as Zero, we tried playing covers, we sucked.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:02.880
[Guest]: And then it was like, if we play our own songs, nobody knows how these songs are supposed

00:49:02.880 --> 00:49:03.880
[Guest]: to go.

00:49:03.880 --> 00:49:06.000
[Guest]: So we can kind of get away with it.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:07.160
[Guest]: That was the whole, you know, idea.

00:49:07.160 --> 00:49:13.920
[Guest]: It was a spite from the judging eyes of people who are well versed in the cover music.

00:49:13.920 --> 00:49:18.280
[Guest]: And at that time, I think there was like a slight trend because you had bands like Indiscreet

00:49:18.280 --> 00:49:23.520
[Guest]: and Pentagram, who are starting to, you know, play significantly their own music as opposed

00:49:23.520 --> 00:49:27.200
[Guest]: to the usual thing is like you play 10 songs and then just at the end, hey, this is one

00:49:27.200 --> 00:49:30.360
[Guest]: of ours, slip it in, that kind of a thing.

00:49:30.360 --> 00:49:34.880
[Guest]: So suddenly it was like, you know, and it took a while for the audiences also to, you

00:49:34.880 --> 00:49:37.400
[Guest]: know, to accept that.

00:49:37.400 --> 00:49:41.240
[Guest]: Otherwise, first, they would give you a lot of shit initially, like, why aren't you playing

00:49:41.240 --> 00:49:45.240
[Guest]: the music that we want to hear, you know, it's like, give it a chance.

00:49:45.240 --> 00:49:49.800
[Guest]: And the good thing, I guess, is our songs had very identifiable choruses.

00:49:49.800 --> 00:49:54.240
[Guest]: Because I think I said this before, if we didn't remember it, then the song was gone.

00:49:54.240 --> 00:49:56.880
[Guest]: So we had to kind of design it in a way so we could remember it.

00:49:56.880 --> 00:50:02.260
[Guest]: So then because of that, other people found it easy to remember as well.

00:50:02.260 --> 00:50:04.840
[Guest]: So that kind of, you know, opened up a few doors.

00:50:04.840 --> 00:50:09.600
[Guest]: And then, I guess, from that, around that time is when Chuck probably started listening

00:50:09.600 --> 00:50:14.920
[Guest]: to Zero, he can fill you in on the rest.

00:50:14.920 --> 00:50:17.760
[Amit Varma]: So I have a question about the learning process.

00:50:17.760 --> 00:50:22.960
[Amit Varma]: Like, one of the questions like I teach a writing course online, and one of the issues

00:50:22.960 --> 00:50:26.760
[Amit Varma]: that some of my students will sometimes have is that, listen, I've written something, but

00:50:26.760 --> 00:50:27.760
[Amit Varma]: it sucks.

00:50:27.760 --> 00:50:28.760
[Amit Varma]: What do I do?

00:50:28.760 --> 00:50:32.680
[Amit Varma]: Now, part of the time, they are, of course, being too self critical and overthinking it.

00:50:32.680 --> 00:50:34.960
[Amit Varma]: But part of the time, they're right, it sucks.

00:50:34.960 --> 00:50:37.760
[Amit Varma]: And the way I look at it is that that is not a reason to stop.

00:50:37.760 --> 00:50:42.680
[Amit Varma]: That is a reason to continue, because you only become better through endless iteration.

00:50:42.680 --> 00:50:46.720
[Amit Varma]: And all it means when you've done something and you think it sucks, is that your judgment

00:50:46.720 --> 00:50:49.320
[Amit Varma]: is better than your ability right now.

00:50:49.320 --> 00:50:51.280
[Amit Varma]: And it's a good thing your judgment is good.

00:50:51.280 --> 00:50:54.920
[Amit Varma]: But if you just continue working at it, your ability will catch up with your judgment sooner

00:50:54.920 --> 00:50:57.400
[Guest]: or later, it's just a question of putting in the work.

00:50:57.400 --> 00:51:00.400
[Guest]: Unless your judgment keeps getting better.

00:51:00.400 --> 00:51:01.400
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:51:01.400 --> 00:51:02.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:51:02.400 --> 00:51:08.040
[Amit Varma]: So, I mean, it's a lifelong catching up process, I guess.

00:51:08.040 --> 00:51:13.000
[Amit Varma]: But so when you're learning, you know, you've got all these influences, I'm guessing from

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:14.000
[Amit Varma]: all over the place.

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:19.800
[Amit Varma]: You also mentioned how you were turned on to the Allman Brothers and to the 70s bands

00:51:19.800 --> 00:51:20.800
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

00:51:20.800 --> 00:51:24.640
[Amit Varma]: So when you're learning, you've got all these heroes, you want to play like this.

00:51:24.640 --> 00:51:30.200
[Amit Varma]: What was that process like, you know, in terms of what you're able to do and what you want

00:51:30.200 --> 00:51:34.000
[Amit Varma]: to do, but you're unable to do right now, but you know, you want to do it.

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:35.320
[Amit Varma]: What was that learning process like?

00:51:35.320 --> 00:51:37.200
[Amit Varma]: How do you keep doing it?

00:51:37.200 --> 00:51:41.960
[Amit Varma]: Or is it just this youthful thing that you're just so enthusiastic, you just keep on going?

00:51:41.960 --> 00:51:47.880
[Amit Varma]: Because in this, I think also there is sort of a lesson for younger people who I think

00:51:47.880 --> 00:51:49.400
[Amit Varma]: sometimes can give up too soon.

00:51:49.400 --> 00:51:52.080
[Amit Varma]: And that's dangerous.

00:51:52.080 --> 00:51:58.760
[Guest]: I think you need to find one thing that you can kind of do well, that is going to serve

00:51:58.760 --> 00:52:01.440
[Guest]: as an inspiration to keep continuing.

00:52:01.440 --> 00:52:08.880
[Guest]: Like I was pretty good at, like, hearing inside my head, a melody, and then being able to

00:52:08.880 --> 00:52:10.600
[Guest]: quickly find it on the fretboard.

00:52:10.600 --> 00:52:14.960
[Guest]: I don't know, kind of, you know, it was a thing, I guess, a gift or whatever.

00:52:14.960 --> 00:52:19.760
[Guest]: But I still had to work on it, you know, which is like today I made a lesson like 10 things

00:52:19.760 --> 00:52:23.320
[Guest]: I wish I knew about playing guitar on YouTube.

00:52:23.320 --> 00:52:26.640
[Guest]: One of the things I said is work on your strengths as well as your weaknesses.

00:52:26.640 --> 00:52:30.360
[Guest]: Don't forget the strengths, because you have to keep honing that as well for it to get

00:52:30.360 --> 00:52:31.360
[Guest]: better.

00:52:31.360 --> 00:52:34.320
[Guest]: If it's something that you can do, just learn how to do it better.

00:52:34.320 --> 00:52:37.440
[Guest]: And then automatically, which goes without saying, work on the stuff that you can't do

00:52:37.440 --> 00:52:38.840
[Guest]: as well to get better on that.

00:52:38.840 --> 00:52:44.380
[Guest]: But the things that you can do well, should, you know, kind of pull out the inspiration

00:52:44.380 --> 00:52:48.160
[Guest]: into doing the things that you can't do well, at least that's my advice.

00:52:48.160 --> 00:52:55.600
[Guest]: Because it's got to be some amount of natural, you know, not amount to say skill, but ability

00:52:55.600 --> 00:52:58.120
[Guest]: that comes into play that serves as inspiration.

00:52:58.120 --> 00:53:00.040
[Guest]: Otherwise, why would you want to do it, you know?

00:53:00.040 --> 00:53:03.360
[Guest]: If you're going to cook and like you've been cooking for two years, and every meal is a

00:53:03.360 --> 00:53:10.240
[Guest]: botched job, you don't want to actually, you know, cook anymore unless you are starving.

00:53:10.240 --> 00:53:15.760
[Guest]: But if you like, say, after a few meals, it gets better, you know, like you notice a little

00:53:15.760 --> 00:53:20.000
[Guest]: bit of improvement that becomes like an inspiration to say, hang on, I should just keep on doing

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:21.000
[Guest]: that.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:24.120
[Guest]: And that's, at least for me, that's always what it's, you know, I just need to keep getting

00:53:24.120 --> 00:53:28.240
[Guest]: better at whatever it is that I'm doing.

00:53:28.240 --> 00:53:34.800
[Unknown]: A question that I'll ask over here is, when you shifted from doing covers to writing your

00:53:34.800 --> 00:53:38.600
[Unknown]: own songs, how did that change your playing style?

00:53:38.600 --> 00:53:41.880
[Unknown]: Was it around this time that you realized that you had the strength of being able to

00:53:41.880 --> 00:53:46.280
[Unknown]: translate your own melodies that you had in your head onto guitar?

00:53:46.280 --> 00:53:50.040
[Unknown]: So I was just curious to see how that how that transition from doing Deep Purple covers

00:53:50.040 --> 00:53:55.360
[Unknown]: to writing Not My Kind of Girl, how that how that came about, how that affected your own

00:53:55.360 --> 00:53:56.360
[Unknown]: playing style?

00:53:56.360 --> 00:54:03.160
[Guest]: Well, at the time, we actually had to learn guitar, I mean, Deep Purple songs, I've already

00:54:03.160 --> 00:54:04.940
[Guest]: kind of written Not My Kind of Girl.

00:54:04.940 --> 00:54:09.760
[Guest]: So it wasn't really, you know, suddenly, it flipped over, there was always this parallel

00:54:09.760 --> 00:54:14.040
[Guest]: thing happening, you were learning other people's music, as well as working on your own.

00:54:14.040 --> 00:54:17.320
[Guest]: The good thing about your own music, like I said, there was no preconceived notion about

00:54:17.320 --> 00:54:20.800
[Guest]: how something should be what, like something to live up to.

00:54:20.800 --> 00:54:25.080
[Guest]: So whatever you did, at least as long as you put yourself into it, and you were able to

00:54:25.080 --> 00:54:27.400
[Guest]: listen back to it without cringing.

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:32.720
[Guest]: That became like the goal, you know, I put, like, whatever I'm hearing into this.

00:54:32.720 --> 00:54:37.320
[Guest]: So at least I feel honest doing it, you know, I'm not trying to be something that I'm not

00:54:37.320 --> 00:54:39.700
[Guest]: in that sense.

00:54:39.700 --> 00:54:44.600
[Guest]: On the other hand, it's still, you know, something that I've done, but I need to make sure it's

00:54:44.600 --> 00:54:50.480
[Guest]: at a certain level, you know, just so I can, because now I can listen back to some stuff.

00:54:50.480 --> 00:54:55.520
[Guest]: And some stuff is just like, no, let's, let's not listen to that anymore.

00:54:55.520 --> 00:55:00.720
[Amit Varma]: Tell us about sort of the early days of Zero, like one of the things you mentioned is that

00:55:00.720 --> 00:55:05.560
[Amit Varma]: you started as a five person act, you, I think, went to a mood indigo at IIT Povai and you

00:55:05.560 --> 00:55:08.700
[Amit Varma]: completely bombed and the next time one of you didn't show up.

00:55:08.700 --> 00:55:12.560
[Amit Varma]: And you realized that, hey, it's much tighter, everything is kind of falling into place.

00:55:12.560 --> 00:55:13.560
[Amit Varma]: This is better.

00:55:13.560 --> 00:55:16.760
[Amit Varma]: There was less to go wrong, less to go wrong.

00:55:16.760 --> 00:55:17.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:55:17.760 --> 00:55:20.080
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about your evolution as a band.

00:55:20.080 --> 00:55:23.880
[Amit Varma]: And especially what I'm interested in is, who were the other local bands you looked

00:55:23.880 --> 00:55:26.400
[Amit Varma]: at at that time as models?

00:55:26.400 --> 00:55:30.440
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, when you start off, you look at all the guys around you, which I guess

00:55:30.440 --> 00:55:35.440
[Amit Varma]: in that era would be your Indus Creed, Parikrama, Pentagram, so on and so forth.

00:55:35.440 --> 00:55:40.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, who are the guys you're looking at as possible models, you know, what is that

00:55:40.440 --> 00:55:44.240
[Amit Varma]: journey like also towards finding your own sound like you were pretty much I think the

00:55:44.240 --> 00:55:48.840
[Amit Varma]: first band that I can remember, which would only play originals, nothing else at all.

00:55:48.840 --> 00:55:52.240
[Amit Varma]: So where did that kind of conviction come from?

00:55:52.240 --> 00:55:57.800
[Guest]: I guess when we found people were able to recall the songs when they came back for the

00:55:57.800 --> 00:56:01.160
[Guest]: next gig, sometimes they would start singing the choruses.

00:56:01.160 --> 00:56:08.960
[Guest]: That was like, oh, you know, a nice little validation or whatever, whatever you're doing.

00:56:08.960 --> 00:56:12.320
[Guest]: But I mean, bands like Pentagram was still starting to play their own stuff.

00:56:12.320 --> 00:56:17.920
[Guest]: Because I've watched Pentagram go from like a large cover oriented set and very quickly

00:56:17.920 --> 00:56:21.720
[Guest]: start throwing their own material in by the time that first album came out and stuff like

00:56:21.720 --> 00:56:23.700
[Guest]: that from then onwards.

00:56:23.700 --> 00:56:27.880
[Guest]: So that also was, you know, like a peer group thing, like, okay, it's fine to do that.

00:56:27.880 --> 00:56:32.000
[Guest]: And even if you get gullies, let it be, they'll come back the next time.

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:36.160
[Guest]: And then it'll be a little bit better, you know, that sort of thing.

00:56:36.160 --> 00:56:40.920
[Guest]: By the time we had played IIT Modindigo for the third time, I think this was the year

00:56:40.920 --> 00:56:42.360
[Guest]: 2000.

00:56:42.360 --> 00:56:46.080
[Guest]: That was the year we decided like, okay, let's not put one single cover on the setlist, it

00:56:46.080 --> 00:56:47.720
[Guest]: has to be only our own music.

00:56:47.720 --> 00:56:51.600
[Guest]: And you know, that was it as an identity, as this is who we are as a band that has to

00:56:51.600 --> 00:56:53.600
[Guest]: be established.

00:56:53.600 --> 00:56:59.560
[Guest]: And again, the added bonus is the judges wouldn't be able to know when you made a mistake.

00:56:59.560 --> 00:57:03.440
[Guest]: As long as you were able to disguise that and not let it be a train wreck.

00:57:03.440 --> 00:57:06.720
[Guest]: One little thing like if you miss the note, you know, that like, it will become less easy

00:57:06.720 --> 00:57:07.720
[Guest]: for people to notice.

00:57:07.720 --> 00:57:14.120
[Guest]: I remember the first time we played PSP was at that IIT Modindigo gig.

00:57:14.120 --> 00:57:16.480
[Guest]: And Rajeev had just come back from the States.

00:57:16.480 --> 00:57:19.540
[Guest]: And we had to teach him PSP in one evening.

00:57:19.540 --> 00:57:22.800
[Guest]: And then when we're going on stage, the groove starts.

00:57:22.800 --> 00:57:25.520
[Guest]: And then he comes running to me, how does the song start?

00:57:25.520 --> 00:57:28.440
[Guest]: I don't know who asked him, he wrote that bit.

00:57:28.440 --> 00:57:32.640
[Guest]: So he was running to Sid and said how, like, I knew the melody, I didn't know the lyrics.

00:57:32.640 --> 00:57:35.240
[Guest]: So Sid knew the lyrics and he sang it to him in his ear.

00:57:35.240 --> 00:57:40.320
[Guest]: And all this while, no one suspects a thing is up, it is just driving that groove through

00:57:40.320 --> 00:57:43.000
[Guest]: and everything's like pretty tight at that point.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:46.520
[Guest]: And then finally goes to the front of the stage and like he sings it like he owns it,

00:57:46.520 --> 00:57:47.840
[Guest]: you know, at that point.

00:57:47.840 --> 00:57:53.600
[Guest]: So at least there was by then that ability to kind of take these little, you know, pitfalls

00:57:53.600 --> 00:58:00.160
[Guest]: or mishaps and not care about it still like, you know, we are the guys on this on the stage.

00:58:00.160 --> 00:58:05.840
[Guest]: Yeah, so, so that particular gig went really well then because we won best band, best guitarist

00:58:05.840 --> 00:58:07.640
[Guest]: and you know, all those prizes.

00:58:07.640 --> 00:58:12.640
[Guest]: I remember like standing with my money in cash, it was 7,500 rupees, the most money

00:58:12.640 --> 00:58:14.600
[Guest]: I'd ever seen from a gig.

00:58:14.600 --> 00:58:18.320
[Guest]: And I gave all of it to my friend who had come back from the UK and bought me this thing

00:58:18.320 --> 00:58:24.240
[Guest]: called the Ebo, which then went on to the studio recording of PSP.

00:58:24.240 --> 00:58:28.440
[Guest]: But that Ebo was bought with my IIT Bodendigul winnings.

00:58:28.440 --> 00:58:33.480
[Amit Varma]: Okay, kindly explain title of PSP 12 inches.

00:58:33.480 --> 00:58:38.520
[Guest]: It's nothing really, it's just become a lot of a thing because the song became, you know,

00:58:38.520 --> 00:58:39.520
[Guest]: relatively well known.

00:58:39.520 --> 00:58:43.360
[Guest]: The whole idea was, I'll tell you how this song started.

00:58:43.360 --> 00:58:51.320
[Guest]: So, I came into practice and this was for Strawberry Fields, NLS, Rajiv was in the States.

00:58:51.320 --> 00:58:58.920
[Guest]: So we had Gareth from Split, another Bombay band, they, you know, sorry, he came for practice,

00:58:58.920 --> 00:58:59.920
[Guest]: but he was late.

00:58:59.920 --> 00:59:03.760
[Guest]: So when I walked in, Sid and Bobby had been waiting there for like a little while.

00:59:03.760 --> 00:59:07.440
[Guest]: And they had started playing that and that grew.

00:59:07.440 --> 00:59:11.300
[Guest]: And then I plugged in my guitar and then as is customary with bands, you start making

00:59:11.300 --> 00:59:13.680
[Guest]: some noise along with what the other guys are playing.

00:59:13.680 --> 00:59:18.320
[Guest]: And you know, it kind of after a while it fizzled out, but they had one nice chorus

00:59:18.320 --> 00:59:20.440
[Guest]: just standing by, standing by, which they kept shouting.

00:59:20.440 --> 00:59:24.640
[Guest]: I thought it was a little annoying at first, but then I kind of said, it's got a thing

00:59:24.640 --> 00:59:25.640
[Guest]: to it.

00:59:25.640 --> 00:59:26.680
[Guest]: So this was cool.

00:59:26.680 --> 00:59:30.640
[Guest]: But then we didn't finish that song in time for NLS.

00:59:30.640 --> 00:59:35.280
[Guest]: Then once Rajiv came back, this was like two months later, I think October to December.

00:59:35.280 --> 00:59:37.920
[Guest]: Rajiv came back and then Mudai happened.

00:59:37.920 --> 00:59:41.440
[Guest]: And then we needed one more song to flush out the setlist of only originals.

00:59:41.440 --> 00:59:46.440
[Guest]: So then the idea was like, let's pull out that standing by song and finish it.

00:59:46.440 --> 00:59:47.440
[Guest]: So we quickly finished it.

00:59:47.440 --> 00:59:51.640
[Guest]: I went home, wrote that middle, that bridge part and everything, all the little ambient

00:59:51.640 --> 00:59:52.640
[Guest]: section and everything.

00:59:52.640 --> 00:59:58.200
[Guest]: The song was done, put it together, it was ready for Mudai, you know, that sort of thing.

00:59:58.200 --> 01:00:03.440
[Guest]: So the chorus was standing by, standing by, so then it became BSB.

01:00:03.440 --> 01:00:08.480
[Guest]: And then they said, it sounds like a pizza, and then they changed it to PSP when I told

01:00:08.480 --> 01:00:12.840
[Guest]: them that when I play the score, it's my pawn shakes, and then they became PSP pawn shaking

01:00:12.840 --> 01:00:15.240
[Guest]: pawns instead of by standing by.

01:00:15.240 --> 01:00:25.880
[Guest]: And then because it sounded like a pizza, that 12 inches at the end, like it's one of

01:00:25.880 --> 01:00:29.200
[Guest]: those random events, which just became a thing, you know, I guess.

01:00:29.200 --> 01:00:30.200
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:00:30.200 --> 01:00:32.240
[Unknown]: And the song obviously took a life of its own after that.

01:00:32.240 --> 01:00:38.200
[Unknown]: You know, what you're telling us about the Rajiv going around on stage asking people

01:00:38.200 --> 01:00:40.880
[Unknown]: for the lyrics sort of thing.

01:00:40.880 --> 01:00:45.640
[Unknown]: It's such a zero thing, because I remember, so one of the things I admired about the band

01:00:45.640 --> 01:00:50.320
[Unknown]: in its later days, when you guys used to get together for those one off gigs, is that Rajiv

01:00:50.320 --> 01:00:53.720
[Unknown]: would go off on one of his tangents talking about something random, and then the three

01:00:53.720 --> 01:00:57.920
[Unknown]: of you would be very bored and just look to pass the time.

01:00:57.920 --> 01:01:01.320
[Unknown]: One of you would come up with something, either you would play a little riff or Sid would

01:01:01.320 --> 01:01:02.680
[Unknown]: play a little groove.

01:01:02.680 --> 01:01:08.040
[Unknown]: And then before you know it, Rajiv is still talking about some nonsense, you know, or

01:01:08.040 --> 01:01:09.040
[Unknown]: whatever.

01:01:09.040 --> 01:01:12.480
[Unknown]: And the three of you are back there playing something legit.

01:01:12.480 --> 01:01:16.680
[Unknown]: And I'm being in the audience, I can say this, everybody around me is like, is this an actual

01:01:16.680 --> 01:01:17.680
[Unknown]: song?

01:01:17.680 --> 01:01:20.000
[Unknown]: Are they actually is this a lead up to an actual song performance?

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:21.880
[Unknown]: And then you will smile or something.

01:01:21.880 --> 01:01:25.560
[Unknown]: And you'll say, Okay, enough of this nonsense, and let's get to actually playing something.

01:01:25.560 --> 01:01:26.560
[Unknown]: And everybody's like, why did you do that?

01:01:26.560 --> 01:01:27.560
[Unknown]: Why do that KLPD?

01:01:27.560 --> 01:01:28.560
[Unknown]: Like, that sounded great.

01:01:28.560 --> 01:01:29.560
[Unknown]: Why did you stop?

01:01:29.560 --> 01:01:31.200
[Unknown]: Why did you not continue this?

01:01:31.200 --> 01:01:34.520
[Unknown]: So yeah, so the reason I said that, so that is from 2000.

01:01:34.520 --> 01:01:39.320
[Unknown]: From that random incident to 2015 or 16, when the last time you guys played was, I guess

01:01:39.320 --> 01:01:44.440
[Unknown]: that tightness and band chemistry really didn't change all that much, did it?

01:01:44.440 --> 01:01:46.160
[Guest]: No, it never really does.

01:01:46.160 --> 01:01:51.960
[Guest]: Because even when we last played at NH7, I remember flying in from Singapore, and you

01:01:51.960 --> 01:01:53.800
[Guest]: know, it was a series of connecting flights.

01:01:53.800 --> 01:01:58.000
[Guest]: And I finally got there five minutes before we were due to start the gig.

01:01:58.000 --> 01:01:59.800
[Guest]: And they had soundchecked without me.

01:01:59.800 --> 01:02:03.920
[Guest]: So I came in, just dumped my thing plugged in, and one, two, three, gajang, literally,

01:02:03.920 --> 01:02:08.480
[Guest]: that was like it what it was like it may have been, I may have had a second to just go and

01:02:08.480 --> 01:02:11.680
[Guest]: wipe my face, you know, all the sweat and start playing.

01:02:11.680 --> 01:02:13.240
[Guest]: But that's what it felt like.

01:02:13.240 --> 01:02:17.320
[Guest]: And it never really, you know, felt weird or anything like that.

01:02:17.320 --> 01:02:20.960
[Guest]: It's just like, you get back into it quickly, as long as the other other guys know the song

01:02:20.960 --> 01:02:21.960
[Guest]: goes.

01:02:21.960 --> 01:02:22.960
[Guest]: Yeah, we're good to go.

01:02:22.960 --> 01:02:28.000
[Guest]: So certain things get written into your read only memory never to be erased.

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:33.600
[Guest]: I think like, you can wake me up in the morning, go to guitar and start playing Lucy, you know,

01:02:33.600 --> 01:02:37.120
[Guest]: we can just start the gig in in autopilot.

01:02:37.120 --> 01:02:41.400
[Guest]: And somewhere in the middle of the gig, you kind of take stock of you know, what's what's

01:02:41.400 --> 01:02:42.680
[Guest]: going on in that sense.

01:02:42.680 --> 01:02:43.680
[Guest]: So that's a pretty cool thing.

01:02:43.680 --> 01:02:48.920
[Guest]: You can just get back with these guys and just plug in and make music.

01:02:48.920 --> 01:02:53.080
[Amit Varma]: And back in those days, when Zero was taking off, and you know, then Hook comes out, which

01:02:53.080 --> 01:02:57.080
[Amit Varma]: was the second album, and you've become really popular on the local scene.

01:02:57.080 --> 01:03:01.240
[Amit Varma]: What was your conception of where this band is going?

01:03:01.240 --> 01:03:04.320
[Amit Varma]: Initially, you're a bunch of guys who just enjoy jamming together.

01:03:04.320 --> 01:03:05.320
[Amit Varma]: You kind of do that.

01:03:05.320 --> 01:03:08.160
[Amit Varma]: You say, let's make a band, you go you form a band, then you write these originals, you

01:03:08.160 --> 01:03:10.960
[Amit Varma]: do one album, you do a second album.

01:03:10.960 --> 01:03:14.840
[Amit Varma]: Was there, you know, in your young minds thought that, hey, we should we want to break through

01:03:14.840 --> 01:03:15.840
[Amit Varma]: internationally?

01:03:15.840 --> 01:03:21.200
[Amit Varma]: Or was there in your mind that gradual acceptance that hey, no, this is kind of the limit of

01:03:21.200 --> 01:03:23.040
[Amit Varma]: what the scene is?

01:03:23.040 --> 01:03:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Just take me through that journey of thinking about what is this band's place in the world?

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:29.000
[Guest]: What's happening?

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:32.680
[Guest]: I mean, for us, it like the whole thing was we had certain goals.

01:03:32.680 --> 01:03:36.640
[Guest]: Like the first goal was play Mood Indigo.

01:03:36.640 --> 01:03:38.120
[Guest]: We played Mood Indigo.

01:03:38.120 --> 01:03:40.880
[Guest]: Then we wanted to play Rang Bhavan and we played Rang Bhavan.

01:03:40.880 --> 01:03:44.320
[Guest]: Then we wanted to win Mood Indigo, then we won Mood Indigo, then we won Great Indian

01:03:44.320 --> 01:03:45.320
[Guest]: Rock.

01:03:45.320 --> 01:03:49.880
[Guest]: And after that, we said, you know, I think we've like done a fair amount on this competition

01:03:49.880 --> 01:03:50.880
[Guest]: thing.

01:03:50.880 --> 01:03:53.200
[Guest]: So we decided not to like take part in any of these.

01:03:53.200 --> 01:03:57.160
[Guest]: So we became one of those, you know, pro bands at the college, you know, they would call

01:03:57.160 --> 01:03:58.840
[Guest]: us to play and that sort of thing.

01:03:58.840 --> 01:04:04.640
[Guest]: And after a while, I realized that this is kind of as high as you can get in this particular,

01:04:04.640 --> 01:04:06.280
[Guest]: you know, pecking order.

01:04:06.280 --> 01:04:10.080
[Guest]: And in order for us to break abroad at that point, first of all, we don't have the money

01:04:10.080 --> 01:04:12.920
[Guest]: or financial backing to actually support a tour at that time.

01:04:12.920 --> 01:04:17.480
[Guest]: It was like frightfully expensive, which it probably still is in that sense.

01:04:17.480 --> 01:04:21.880
[Guest]: But we've won a few competitions and then, you know, there was this thing about sending

01:04:21.880 --> 01:04:24.200
[Guest]: us overseas to some country and everything.

01:04:24.200 --> 01:04:27.760
[Guest]: But then there was always this thing that was communicated to us that you need to have

01:04:27.760 --> 01:04:29.580
[Guest]: the Indian element.

01:04:29.580 --> 01:04:32.960
[Guest]: So we had made many jokes about this whole Indian element.

01:04:32.960 --> 01:04:33.960
[Guest]: What is the Indian element?

01:04:33.960 --> 01:04:34.960
[Guest]: Like we are zeros.

01:04:34.960 --> 01:04:36.240
[Guest]: Zero is an Indian invention.

01:04:36.240 --> 01:04:38.720
[Guest]: So you know, that's the Indian element.

01:04:38.720 --> 01:04:39.720
[Guest]: Is that enough for you?

01:04:39.720 --> 01:04:40.720
[Guest]: What do you want?

01:04:40.720 --> 01:04:41.720
[Guest]: Do you want us to wear lungis?

01:04:41.720 --> 01:04:42.720
[Guest]: What do you want us to do?

01:04:42.720 --> 01:04:49.640
[Guest]: So, you know, and at that time, I think also slowly, maybe after that time came the acceptance

01:04:49.640 --> 01:04:53.240
[Guest]: that you can still show your Indianness in your music and still be authentic.

01:04:53.240 --> 01:04:57.400
[Guest]: You won't like consider selling out just because you put some tabla on your music.

01:04:57.400 --> 01:05:01.000
[Guest]: And the whole thing is to get it to fuse effortlessly.

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:02.320
[Guest]: If it does, great.

01:05:02.320 --> 01:05:06.280
[Guest]: And if it doesn't, in a band like Zero, it never seemed like, you know, it was it was

01:05:06.280 --> 01:05:07.280
[Guest]: needed.

01:05:07.280 --> 01:05:08.320
[Guest]: We just play what we want to play.

01:05:08.320 --> 01:05:12.160
[Guest]: And the fact that we lived in India was Indian enough for us, you know, we didn't found the

01:05:12.160 --> 01:05:13.920
[Guest]: need to add.

01:05:13.920 --> 01:05:17.680
[Guest]: And then as you grow older, obviously, with Blackstar Blues, those influences start creeping

01:05:17.680 --> 01:05:23.360
[Guest]: in your sitar, the Tanpura drone in the Renaissance Mission and stuff like that.

01:05:23.360 --> 01:05:26.520
[Guest]: It goes together, you know, pretty well in that sense.

01:05:26.520 --> 01:05:30.200
[Guest]: So there was also a little bit of that sense like, OK, I think, you know, it's kind of

01:05:30.200 --> 01:05:33.320
[Guest]: got to as good as it's going to get.

01:05:33.320 --> 01:05:38.400
[Guest]: And at that time, my parents had moved to New Zealand around 2003.

01:05:38.400 --> 01:05:42.520
[Guest]: And there was this, you know, are you going to come, are you going to stay there?

01:05:42.520 --> 01:05:48.240
[Guest]: That you know, parents, they wanted me to obviously move along with them as well.

01:05:48.240 --> 01:05:53.480
[Guest]: So for around one or two years after they left, it was like a huge party scene.

01:05:53.480 --> 01:05:57.320
[Guest]: But then I also started kind of, you know, feeling the wind down, like, there has to

01:05:57.320 --> 01:05:59.260
[Guest]: be more to life than this.

01:05:59.260 --> 01:06:03.840
[Guest]: So then for me, it was like, OK, let's go there and see what that's all about.

01:06:03.840 --> 01:06:09.560
[Guest]: And then I went and I actually found a system that somewhat works, everything was like a

01:06:09.560 --> 01:06:12.080
[Guest]: polar opposite of what you're used to in India.

01:06:12.080 --> 01:06:17.240
[Guest]: India is like too many people there, there's not enough people, you know, there's very

01:06:17.240 --> 01:06:20.080
[Guest]: long lines, you know, there's not very long lines.

01:06:20.080 --> 01:06:21.080
[Guest]: So that's what I'm saying.

01:06:21.080 --> 01:06:23.900
[Guest]: I mean, you start noticing the contrast and everything like that.

01:06:23.900 --> 01:06:27.720
[Guest]: So then it became like, OK, maybe I should stay here for a while.

01:06:27.720 --> 01:06:35.400
[Guest]: And after a series of very, shall we say, fortunate events, I ended up getting my New

01:06:35.400 --> 01:06:40.040
[Guest]: Zealand residency because the thing was, I had to reach out before I was 25.

01:06:40.040 --> 01:06:44.940
[Guest]: And I landed here on my 25th birthday, cutting it close.

01:06:44.940 --> 01:06:47.040
[Guest]: So anyway, finally, I got it.

01:06:47.040 --> 01:06:51.220
[Guest]: And that was a sign like after all this, you know, chakkar and everything, maybe I should

01:06:51.220 --> 01:06:52.880
[Guest]: stay here for a little bit.

01:06:52.880 --> 01:06:57.200
[Guest]: So I did a six month thing back in India where I packed up all my stuff because I'd come

01:06:57.200 --> 01:07:02.080
[Guest]: in initially on a tourist visa, tourist visa, as you do, went back, packed up all my stuff.

01:07:02.080 --> 01:07:07.320
[Guest]: And 2005 is when I was like, chalo, I'm going there.

01:07:07.320 --> 01:07:09.600
[Guest]: You guys won't see me for a very long time.

01:07:09.600 --> 01:07:15.760
[Guest]: So it wasn't such like a, what do you call it, like a whole drama thing, like, you know,

01:07:15.760 --> 01:07:19.480
[Guest]: I'm going, I'm leaving the band and all that kind of thing was like, no, listen, I've got

01:07:19.480 --> 01:07:21.080
[Guest]: to go and live in another country for a while.

01:07:21.080 --> 01:07:26.560
[Guest]: So, you know, you guys carry on and we'll see, you know, where things go.

01:07:26.560 --> 01:07:29.640
[Guest]: And I think I came back for a holiday in 2006.

01:07:29.640 --> 01:07:34.760
[Guest]: We played at one of the great Indian rock set, Pragati Maidana is one of the headlining

01:07:34.760 --> 01:07:36.320
[Guest]: bands and everything like that.

01:07:36.320 --> 01:07:39.840
[Guest]: So that was cool as and when, you know, there was no thing like, okay, now it's ended and

01:07:39.840 --> 01:07:41.280
[Guest]: now we're reuniting or anything.

01:07:41.280 --> 01:07:43.640
[Guest]: It's just like, no, we're in the same city.

01:07:43.640 --> 01:07:44.640
[Guest]: We play.

01:07:44.640 --> 01:07:45.640
[Guest]: We're not in the same city.

01:07:45.640 --> 01:07:46.640
[Guest]: We don't play.

01:07:46.640 --> 01:07:47.640
[Guest]: It's as simple as that.

01:07:47.640 --> 01:07:54.120
[Guest]: So that's kind of the whole thing with Zero, the way it currently is, at least now.

01:07:54.120 --> 01:07:58.680
[Amit Varma]: And how are you kind of collaborating, you know, what you were doing as a musician?

01:07:58.680 --> 01:08:02.440
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, at one point you decided to be serious, you've spoken about how you

01:08:02.440 --> 01:08:06.920
[Amit Varma]: were doing engineering, decided it wasn't for you, left that, you're a full time musician,

01:08:06.920 --> 01:08:11.360
[Amit Varma]: your families were supportive of that and all of that, then Zero happens, presumably

01:08:11.360 --> 01:08:15.600
[Amit Varma]: you've got some ambitions for that, but you do as well as you can as a band.

01:08:15.600 --> 01:08:19.520
[Amit Varma]: And the next thing you're in New Zealand, there's a completely new ecosystem.

01:08:19.520 --> 01:08:23.680
[Amit Varma]: You don't know anybody there, I'm guessing it's like, totally different.

01:08:23.680 --> 01:08:28.280
[Amit Varma]: What are you thinking of in terms of, you know, the next 20-30 years of your life?

01:08:28.280 --> 01:08:30.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I know no one really plans like that.

01:08:30.400 --> 01:08:32.040
[Amit Varma]: But were there moments of worry?

01:08:32.040 --> 01:08:35.820
[Amit Varma]: Were there moments where you wondered if you'd made the right decision in terms of going

01:08:35.820 --> 01:08:36.820
[Amit Varma]: to New Zealand?

01:08:36.820 --> 01:08:39.720
[Amit Varma]: Obviously not in terms of music, because, or did you have second thoughts about that

01:08:39.720 --> 01:08:40.720
[Guest]: as well?

01:08:40.720 --> 01:08:43.600
[Guest]: No, it was just like, I need to try something new.

01:08:43.600 --> 01:08:46.960
[Guest]: You know, when you come to that point in your life, you know, like things are starting to

01:08:46.960 --> 01:08:51.100
[Guest]: feel like samey and very old and, you know, stagnant in that sense.

01:08:51.100 --> 01:08:57.160
[Guest]: So you have to kind of do something different to get to a different place in your life.

01:08:57.160 --> 01:08:59.920
[Guest]: So in that sense, it felt like the right thing.

01:08:59.920 --> 01:09:04.180
[Guest]: And, you know, like a young kid who's never really been outside India, suddenly everything

01:09:04.180 --> 01:09:09.500
[Guest]: was like, you know, wide open, I was like, well, you can actually listen to the sound

01:09:09.500 --> 01:09:12.080
[Guest]: of your guitar notes decaying into silence.

01:09:12.080 --> 01:09:15.680
[Guest]: That was a new thing for me, I could hear the note decaying, right?

01:09:15.680 --> 01:09:19.960
[Guest]: Because in India, obviously, where I live in Bombay, noisy part of the city, it decays

01:09:19.960 --> 01:09:23.720
[Guest]: and then the autos take over.

01:09:23.720 --> 01:09:27.520
[Guest]: So you know, all these little bits of discovery were pretty cool.

01:09:27.520 --> 01:09:32.240
[Guest]: And my parents had this garage where my brother and me pooled our resources together and we

01:09:32.240 --> 01:09:34.800
[Guest]: set up a little studio.

01:09:34.800 --> 01:09:39.000
[Guest]: And I was putting down a few ideas and he said, you know, I've gotten pretty good at

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:42.280
[Guest]: programming drums, let me have a crack at it.

01:09:42.280 --> 01:09:46.780
[Guest]: So then he turned out some spectacular drum tracks, I was like, hang on, this is a cool

01:09:46.780 --> 01:09:51.440
[Guest]: opportunity for me to flush out all the unfinished ideas, because there were always these ideas

01:09:51.440 --> 01:09:57.120
[Guest]: which were like, you know, in a half completed state throughout the zero thing.

01:09:57.120 --> 01:10:02.240
[Guest]: Once in a while, the band guys would like get me to finish it like spittly for Christmas

01:10:02.240 --> 01:10:04.600
[Guest]: in July and put it on an album.

01:10:04.600 --> 01:10:08.320
[Guest]: But those were like the precursor Black Swan Blues tracks.

01:10:08.320 --> 01:10:11.600
[Guest]: So then there were tracks like Anubha Sky and Soar the Sky and everything like that,

01:10:11.600 --> 01:10:15.660
[Guest]: which were, you know, incomplete.

01:10:15.660 --> 01:10:19.120
[Guest]: Because of this sudden, you know, josh, you get that, oh, suddenly it's sounding really

01:10:19.120 --> 01:10:22.560
[Guest]: good with this guy programming the drums, it became really easy.

01:10:22.560 --> 01:10:24.200
[Guest]: So then that flow got established.

01:10:24.200 --> 01:10:26.800
[Guest]: So I think I recorded that entire album in three weeks.

01:10:26.800 --> 01:10:31.360
[Guest]: It sounds nuts right now, at my current state of, you know, work.

01:10:31.360 --> 01:10:33.800
[Guest]: But in three weeks, I kind of had it wrapped up.

01:10:33.800 --> 01:10:41.460
[Guest]: But it was still so fresh that I didn't have the detachedness from it to mix it properly.

01:10:41.460 --> 01:10:43.700
[Guest]: The mixes never sounded, you know, good.

01:10:43.700 --> 01:10:48.280
[Guest]: So that process took me like a year and something to finish the mixes.

01:10:48.280 --> 01:10:51.500
[Guest]: And then finally it was at a point, okay, I can put this out.

01:10:51.500 --> 01:10:56.400
[Guest]: And then once it went out and people liked it, then it became, you know, by the time

01:10:56.400 --> 01:11:02.160
[Guest]: the second album came around, enough people had liked it, where like Mithi by College

01:11:02.160 --> 01:11:07.560
[Guest]: wanted to fly me down to play a gig that became the first Black Swan Blues gig in 2009.

01:11:07.560 --> 01:11:12.240
[Guest]: So there was like a two year period of that, you know, just putting out stuff and seeing

01:11:12.240 --> 01:11:13.240
[Guest]: what happens.

01:11:13.240 --> 01:11:14.720
[Guest]: And then I think I put it out for free.

01:11:14.720 --> 01:11:19.280
[Guest]: I had my website where it was a download link.

01:11:19.280 --> 01:11:26.000
[Guest]: And then, you know, enough people heard it and they liked it and that's how things go.

01:11:26.000 --> 01:11:30.920
[Amit Varma]: And I'm intrigued by one aspect of your development, you know, which has a sort of dual part to

01:11:30.920 --> 01:11:31.920
[Amit Varma]: it.

01:11:31.920 --> 01:11:36.680
[Amit Varma]: One is that you said in an interview once that the first thing you noticed about Auckland

01:11:36.680 --> 01:11:40.680
[Amit Varma]: was that it was a lot quieter than Mumbai and the silence opened up your ears in a new

01:11:40.680 --> 01:11:41.680
[Amit Varma]: way.

01:11:41.680 --> 01:11:44.160
[Amit Varma]: You began to listen to music differently.

01:11:44.160 --> 01:11:45.160
[Amit Varma]: And that's one thing.

01:11:45.160 --> 01:11:49.120
[Amit Varma]: But the other thing is also I think something that inevitably happens with us as we grow

01:11:49.120 --> 01:11:55.600
[Amit Varma]: older, where we kind of learn to take a step back and relax just a little bit and maybe

01:11:55.600 --> 01:11:59.320
[Amit Varma]: get more comfortable in our skins and so on and so forth.

01:11:59.320 --> 01:12:02.680
[Amit Varma]: Like you've done an interview with Chuck, I think around the time of the second Black

01:12:02.680 --> 01:12:05.840
[Amit Varma]: Strat Blues album where he asked you what you don't do well.

01:12:05.840 --> 01:12:09.560
[Amit Varma]: And I think you said that sometimes I still overplay, you know, and listening to your

01:12:09.560 --> 01:12:13.920
[Amit Varma]: later albums and even those earlier albums, there's just a lot of restraint, a lot of

01:12:13.920 --> 01:12:14.920
[Amit Varma]: chilling.

01:12:14.920 --> 01:12:19.960
[Amit Varma]: And eventually, I guess, over time, you reach the stage where you become more and more comfortable

01:12:19.960 --> 01:12:25.360
[Amit Varma]: in your own skin, where you're no longer worried about, you know, what you want to sound like.

01:12:25.360 --> 01:12:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Am I living up to my own expectations?

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:30.160
[Amit Varma]: Or am I living up to the expectations of others?

01:12:30.160 --> 01:12:34.200
[Amit Varma]: Or, you know, all of that and you and you just get comfortable and you just let the

01:12:34.200 --> 01:12:36.720
[Amit Varma]: music kind of take over like, brief digression.

01:12:36.720 --> 01:12:41.120
[Amit Varma]: I remember my friend Prem Panicker once was doing a writing workshop for my students and

01:12:41.120 --> 01:12:45.440
[Amit Varma]: he told told me this great story about a writer and I forget which writer it was, but this

01:12:45.440 --> 01:12:47.880
[Amit Varma]: writer was asked about his writing process.

01:12:47.880 --> 01:12:51.880
[Amit Varma]: And he said, Okay, I get into the room, and I sit with my typewriter, and I close the

01:12:51.880 --> 01:12:53.520
[Amit Varma]: door and then I'm alone in the room.

01:12:53.520 --> 01:12:57.920
[Amit Varma]: So the whoever was interviewing the guy asked him that, is that when you start writing and

01:12:57.920 --> 01:13:02.440
[Amit Varma]: he said no, because there are still even though I'm alone in the room, I can still sense all

01:13:02.440 --> 01:13:06.400
[Amit Varma]: these other people around me whom I want to impress or their expectations of me and so

01:13:06.400 --> 01:13:07.400
[Amit Varma]: on.

01:13:07.400 --> 01:13:09.260
[Amit Varma]: So I wait until they've all left.

01:13:09.260 --> 01:13:12.400
[Amit Varma]: So then this person asked, Oh, so that's when you stop writing.

01:13:12.400 --> 01:13:16.520
[Amit Varma]: And the guy said, No, that's not when I start writing, because there is still one person

01:13:16.520 --> 01:13:17.520
[Amit Varma]: in the room.

01:13:17.520 --> 01:13:18.520
[Amit Varma]: And that's me.

01:13:18.520 --> 01:13:19.520
[Amit Varma]: And I wait for that person to leave.

01:13:19.520 --> 01:13:20.960
[Amit Varma]: And then the story takes over.

01:13:20.960 --> 01:13:21.960
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:13:21.960 --> 01:13:23.960
[Amit Varma]: And I found it very resonant.

01:13:23.960 --> 01:13:28.040
[Amit Varma]: Like when you somewhere else in another interview, you spoke about Ode to a Sunny Day and how

01:13:28.040 --> 01:13:29.520
[Amit Varma]: that came about.

01:13:29.520 --> 01:13:34.200
[Amit Varma]: And how at the end of it, you were kind of surprised at my God, I wrote this, you know,

01:13:34.200 --> 01:13:37.640
[Amit Varma]: similar to when, you know, Paul McCartney got yesterday in a dream, and he woke up and

01:13:37.640 --> 01:13:38.640
[Amit Varma]: he played it.

01:13:38.640 --> 01:13:40.700
[Amit Varma]: And he said that, you know, have you heard this before?

01:13:40.700 --> 01:13:43.440
[Amit Varma]: Because he couldn't believe he had written it, it kind of came.

01:13:43.440 --> 01:13:48.700
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about this, that have you become comfortable in your own skin?

01:13:48.700 --> 01:13:50.440
[Amit Varma]: What was that process like?

01:13:50.440 --> 01:13:54.640
[Amit Varma]: You told Chuck in that interview more than a decade ago that you sometimes you overplayed,

01:13:54.640 --> 01:13:56.520
[Amit Varma]: do you still do that?

01:13:56.520 --> 01:13:58.120
[Amit Varma]: What was the journey like?

01:13:58.120 --> 01:14:03.280
[Guest]: I mean, for me, the best music comes when when you become a conduit, or an antenna,

01:14:03.280 --> 01:14:08.440
[Guest]: you're just able to channel something or a feeling or whatever just goes through you.

01:14:08.440 --> 01:14:13.520
[Guest]: And as little of your own ego is applied to the process as possible.

01:14:13.520 --> 01:14:16.840
[Guest]: There are certain things you obviously do well, and the certain things that you're kind

01:14:16.840 --> 01:14:19.500
[Guest]: of more inclined to do than other things.

01:14:19.500 --> 01:14:21.320
[Guest]: So that kind of shapes it.

01:14:21.320 --> 01:14:28.360
[Guest]: But as long as I'm honest to the song, you know, and not trying to bend it against its

01:14:28.360 --> 01:14:33.080
[Guest]: will, because you can do that to a piece of music, you can kind of push it too far into

01:14:33.080 --> 01:14:35.160
[Guest]: something it's not intended to be.

01:14:35.160 --> 01:14:41.360
[Guest]: So I guess I grew a little better at knowing when I was doing that, and then just back

01:14:41.360 --> 01:14:43.000
[Guest]: off a little bit.

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:48.760
[Guest]: And the ability to take time and let something percolate in your subconscious for a while,

01:14:48.760 --> 01:14:49.760
[Guest]: is pretty awesome.

01:14:49.760 --> 01:14:53.520
[Guest]: Because now you're able to open a QA session, for example, and do a whole bunch of stuff

01:14:53.520 --> 01:14:56.320
[Guest]: in one day, like say, do six hours of work.

01:14:56.320 --> 01:14:59.600
[Guest]: And then you don't listen to it for like three weeks, and then you come back to it.

01:14:59.600 --> 01:15:03.320
[Guest]: And then you have a little bit of a clear insight about that, take that out, that doesn't

01:15:03.320 --> 01:15:04.680
[Guest]: work, you know, that sort of thing.

01:15:04.680 --> 01:15:08.160
[Guest]: Because when you get into a flow, you tend to like, throw as much of it, you know, into

01:15:08.160 --> 01:15:09.160
[Guest]: it as possible.

01:15:09.160 --> 01:15:14.240
[Guest]: And then you come back another day, and then that second person has to strip away the excess

01:15:14.240 --> 01:15:19.360
[Guest]: and kind of find what that little vein of gold inside the rock is.

01:15:19.360 --> 01:15:24.560
[Guest]: And then shine that out a bit and tend to, you know, make that the centerpiece of it.

01:15:24.560 --> 01:15:28.280
[Guest]: So it could be a melody, it could be a chord progression, it could be a drum groove, it

01:15:28.280 --> 01:15:29.960
[Guest]: could be a bassline, whatever it is.

01:15:29.960 --> 01:15:34.480
[Guest]: And then different types of songs, there's different things that can do that.

01:15:34.480 --> 01:15:38.640
[Guest]: My main goal is to kind of keep myself interested in the process.

01:15:38.640 --> 01:15:44.840
[Guest]: And to start the process, I try to find an idea which has what I call legs.

01:15:44.840 --> 01:15:50.080
[Guest]: The idea is legs, it inspires me to do more to get it out.

01:15:50.080 --> 01:15:53.840
[Guest]: And sometimes I can do too much, but I can always kind of come back to it, as long as

01:15:53.840 --> 01:15:57.720
[Guest]: you know, things are not, you know, set in stone.

01:15:57.720 --> 01:16:02.200
[Guest]: The idea of collaboration also is pretty awesome with me, because the idea of handing something

01:16:02.200 --> 01:16:06.360
[Guest]: over to something like, say, a drum groove, why the hell would I want to think of a drum

01:16:06.360 --> 01:16:12.120
[Guest]: groove when I've got someone like Jay or Cole, who would, you know, and also now I have like,

01:16:12.120 --> 01:16:15.680
[Guest]: say, the ability to say, okay, this song is better if Jay plays it, or this song is better

01:16:15.680 --> 01:16:19.760
[Guest]: if Cole plays it, that sort of thing on this last current album, which I found awesome.

01:16:19.760 --> 01:16:26.040
[Guest]: It was like, otherwise, what you tend to do is you tend to shape the songs into what the

01:16:26.040 --> 01:16:30.560
[Guest]: band itself is, you know, it's like, you know, you've got a certain cast, and then this is

01:16:30.560 --> 01:16:35.000
[Guest]: the kind of material that is, this is the kind of material which is going to be best

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:36.000
[Guest]: for them.

01:16:36.000 --> 01:16:40.120
[Guest]: Like with Zero, I would write in a very different way to what I would do in Black Swan Blues,

01:16:40.120 --> 01:16:42.640
[Guest]: just because the members were different.

01:16:42.640 --> 01:16:47.880
[Guest]: So once you get used to delegating that and handing things over, while still retaining

01:16:47.880 --> 01:16:53.640
[Guest]: the overall picture, the big picture of things, it's pretty awesome in that sense, because

01:16:53.640 --> 01:16:57.640
[Guest]: then the whole idea is also just freeing yourself of all these hang ups, you know, what is this

01:16:57.640 --> 01:16:58.640
[Guest]: one going to think?

01:16:58.640 --> 01:16:59.640
[Guest]: What is that one going to think?

01:16:59.640 --> 01:17:04.200
[Guest]: Right now, I'm at a point where as long as I play honestly, and I play in tune and in

01:17:04.200 --> 01:17:11.640
[Guest]: time, as you would expect, the idea would get across, you know, so I don't really want

01:17:11.640 --> 01:17:17.200
[Guest]: to fluff it up by putting too much into it, just to show what I can do.

01:17:17.200 --> 01:17:20.240
[Guest]: At this point, it's like, people know what I can do.

01:17:20.240 --> 01:17:23.840
[Guest]: So, you know, I'd rather do what's best for the song.

01:17:23.840 --> 01:17:28.000
[Unknown]: It almost seems to me like there are two parts to you.

01:17:28.000 --> 01:17:31.760
[Unknown]: And I'm not saying the pre-Zero, the essence Zero guitarist and the Black Swan Blues guitarist,

01:17:31.760 --> 01:17:34.200
[Unknown]: but when you what you described right now was kind of fascinating.

01:17:34.200 --> 01:17:37.520
[Unknown]: It's like, there's a creator and there's an editor almost, right?

01:17:37.520 --> 01:17:41.200
[Unknown]: Like there's a creator part where you create and then you come back, look at it with fresh

01:17:41.200 --> 01:17:42.200
[Unknown]: eyes.

01:17:42.200 --> 01:17:43.200
[Unknown]: Do you have like a different process?

01:17:43.200 --> 01:17:47.840
[Unknown]: Or like, what are the things that you do to get into the respective grooves are there,

01:17:47.840 --> 01:17:53.840
[Unknown]: you know, is, or when do you know that you need to, how do you know when to step out

01:17:53.840 --> 01:18:00.000
[Unknown]: of the creator mode and step into the editor mode, for example?

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:04.720
[Guest]: I mean, you can't really hand off on one to the other, because there's still a little

01:18:04.720 --> 01:18:09.040
[Guest]: bit of that creator thing that has to inform the editor part as well.

01:18:09.040 --> 01:18:13.480
[Guest]: Because sometimes you can again get too clever with the editing as well.

01:18:13.480 --> 01:18:17.080
[Guest]: So sometimes, you know, don't polish that too much.

01:18:17.080 --> 01:18:21.200
[Guest]: It's better left, you know, in a slightly raw state.

01:18:21.200 --> 01:18:23.520
[Guest]: That's kind of what was giving the thing its charm.

01:18:23.520 --> 01:18:29.920
[Guest]: So you have to be very sensitive to the aesthetic or the vibe or whatever you want to call it.

01:18:29.920 --> 01:18:32.920
[Guest]: You know, there's obviously going to be a subjective thing, because I'll hear things

01:18:32.920 --> 01:18:36.680
[Guest]: differently than, you know, a different person who's equally proficient.

01:18:36.680 --> 01:18:39.780
[Guest]: It's not a question of proficiency, it's just a question of taste.

01:18:39.780 --> 01:18:43.000
[Guest]: So very often, there's no right or wrong, there's just different things.

01:18:43.000 --> 01:18:46.960
[Guest]: And at the end of the day, it comes down to what makes you happy at that point of time,

01:18:46.960 --> 01:18:51.360
[Guest]: because what makes you happy yesterday may not be what makes you happy today.

01:18:51.360 --> 01:18:55.400
[Guest]: Just also depends on how you're feeling, you know, what the humidity is like, what the

01:18:55.400 --> 01:18:59.280
[Guest]: temperature is like, all that kind of changes the way you perceive a piece of music.

01:18:59.280 --> 01:19:05.780
[Guest]: I think the passage of time kind of helps me, at least, if I'm able to have enough time.

01:19:05.780 --> 01:19:08.520
[Guest]: Because when people ask me, when is the next album going to be out?

01:19:08.520 --> 01:19:09.520
[Guest]: I said, when it's ready.

01:19:09.520 --> 01:19:11.320
[Guest]: I don't know when it's going to be ready.

01:19:11.320 --> 01:19:15.240
[Guest]: And there's no one putting a gun to my head saying it needs to be out once so and so date.

01:19:15.240 --> 01:19:21.280
[Guest]: So then, you know, why have an imaginary gun, you know, just wait till it's done.

01:19:21.280 --> 01:19:25.560
[Guest]: But then also, I guess, the deadline kind of helps with the procrastination.

01:19:25.560 --> 01:19:30.200
[Guest]: So sometimes you have to set yourself a deadline after you have it done by this date, you know,

01:19:30.200 --> 01:19:31.200
[Guest]: that sort of thing.

01:19:31.200 --> 01:19:36.440
[Guest]: Like this previous album, I uploaded it to streaming services eight times.

01:19:36.440 --> 01:19:39.560
[Guest]: Every time I'd upload it, I'd hear it in the car, I was like, I'm going to change that,

01:19:39.560 --> 01:19:40.980
[Guest]: you know, and pull it back down.

01:19:40.980 --> 01:19:46.960
[Guest]: And this eight times happened in a week, you know, and by the time it came to the last

01:19:46.960 --> 01:19:48.720
[Guest]: upload, it was cutting it really fine.

01:19:48.720 --> 01:19:51.720
[Guest]: And they were saying like, no, it won't be out by that day.

01:19:51.720 --> 01:19:54.320
[Guest]: If you don't upload it today, that sort of thing.

01:19:54.320 --> 01:19:56.760
[Guest]: So it was like, okay, it's done.

01:19:56.760 --> 01:19:58.480
[Guest]: Let's pull it out and see what happens.

01:19:58.480 --> 01:20:05.040
[Guest]: So it's also it's ready when you when you have to let go, keep on editing.

01:20:05.040 --> 01:20:08.480
[Guest]: That's also the thing is, like, in the early days, you had studio time, you had this much

01:20:08.480 --> 01:20:11.440
[Guest]: to your time, you have to go, you have to finish the thing and get out like there's

01:20:11.440 --> 01:20:15.960
[Guest]: a whole story of Led Zeppelin recording presence in like a very short span of time, because

01:20:15.960 --> 01:20:18.840
[Guest]: the Rolling Stones were coming in and they had to finish.

01:20:18.840 --> 01:20:22.000
[Guest]: And he did all his guitar overdubs in one night, which is amazing if you listen to that

01:20:22.000 --> 01:20:25.880
[Guest]: album and think all the guitar parts on the album were done in one night.

01:20:25.880 --> 01:20:32.400
[Guest]: So similarly, like, you know, having a deadline can kind of push you but I like to have a

01:20:32.400 --> 01:20:39.120
[Guest]: reasonable, you know, window to, to move things around and see how things work.

01:20:39.120 --> 01:20:43.260
[Amit Varma]: And what you said about stopping the editor inside you from polishing something too much

01:20:43.260 --> 01:20:45.880
[Amit Varma]: reminds me of this quote by a guy called William Maxwell.

01:20:45.880 --> 01:20:50.240
[Amit Varma]: He was an editor at the New Yorker for about 40 years, and a great writer himself wrote

01:20:50.240 --> 01:20:51.240
[Amit Varma]: some crazy books.

01:20:51.240 --> 01:20:55.760
[Amit Varma]: And once he was asked about what he looks for in the writing that people sent to him.

01:20:55.760 --> 01:20:59.200
[Amit Varma]: And he said, I don't look for style, I look for the breadth of life, you know, and he

01:20:59.200 --> 01:21:03.400
[Amit Varma]: said this was something that he had learned to do over time, that it's not just about

01:21:03.400 --> 01:21:05.600
[Amit Varma]: immaculate craft and all of those things.

01:21:05.600 --> 01:21:09.120
[Amit Varma]: It's about, you know, where is that kind of moment of magic?

01:21:09.120 --> 01:21:12.960
[Amit Varma]: One thing I want to ask you about, which I've always wondered about in the context of both

01:21:12.960 --> 01:21:18.840
[Amit Varma]: music and cinema, is the anxiety of avoiding cliche.

01:21:18.840 --> 01:21:23.040
[Amit Varma]: For example, in writing, it's really common advice that you want to avoid cliches.

01:21:23.040 --> 01:21:26.960
[Amit Varma]: Martin Amis, even his book of collective criticism is called the war against cliche.

01:21:26.960 --> 01:21:30.400
[Amit Varma]: Now, in cinema and music, it seems a little harder than that.

01:21:30.400 --> 01:21:35.680
[Amit Varma]: Because where do you distinguish between, say, cliche and convention and trope, like

01:21:35.680 --> 01:21:39.440
[Amit Varma]: in a film, you know, if you have an establishing scene, you'll have a wide shot, then you'll

01:21:39.440 --> 01:21:41.160
[Amit Varma]: go in, is it cliche?

01:21:41.160 --> 01:21:42.160
[Amit Varma]: Is it convention?

01:21:42.160 --> 01:21:45.160
[Amit Varma]: Is it just friendly to the audience to do it in a familiar way?

01:21:45.160 --> 01:21:50.240
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, when you're playing music, I would imagine that there'll be tons of tropes, which

01:21:50.240 --> 01:21:54.120
[Amit Varma]: are say common to blues or common to a particular kind of vibe that you're doing, you know,

01:21:54.120 --> 01:21:57.880
[Amit Varma]: if there's a certain kind of melody, you'll mix it in a certain kind of way or whatever.

01:21:57.880 --> 01:22:00.680
[Amit Varma]: And some things can even become your own cliches.

01:22:00.680 --> 01:22:06.720
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, is that something that you worried about at any point the anxiety that, you know,

01:22:06.720 --> 01:22:10.720
[Amit Varma]: am I really doing something new that where does one draw that line?

01:22:10.720 --> 01:22:12.200
[Guest]: Stuff you've thought about?

01:22:12.200 --> 01:22:15.440
[Guest]: There's always anxiety.

01:22:15.440 --> 01:22:22.400
[Guest]: The whole imposter syndrome looms large, you know, but you kind of have to kind of almost

01:22:22.400 --> 01:22:26.600
[Guest]: be your own psychologist and tell yourself, no, I do this well, just relax.

01:22:26.600 --> 01:22:27.600
[Guest]: I'll do it.

01:22:27.600 --> 01:22:28.840
[Guest]: You know, I know how to do this.

01:22:28.840 --> 01:22:29.840
[Guest]: Just let me do it.

01:22:29.840 --> 01:22:33.320
[Guest]: So that part of you, you know, has to be silenced.

01:22:33.320 --> 01:22:35.440
[Guest]: The one which is always like, no, it's wrong.

01:22:35.440 --> 01:22:36.440
[Guest]: No, it's wrong.

01:22:36.440 --> 01:22:37.440
[Guest]: No, it's wrong.

01:22:37.440 --> 01:22:40.320
[Guest]: Like, okay, you chill for a little while, just do it.

01:22:40.320 --> 01:22:45.880
[Guest]: And you can kind of feel when you have an honest reaction to your own music, to something

01:22:45.880 --> 01:22:47.400
[Guest]: that you make.

01:22:47.400 --> 01:22:55.480
[Guest]: And whether it is cliche or not, if the reaction you feel is tangibly genuine, then I don't

01:22:55.480 --> 01:22:56.640
[Guest]: worry about it so much.

01:22:56.640 --> 01:23:01.920
[Guest]: Because sometimes you can do a certain thing, which everyone has done, but you can do it

01:23:01.920 --> 01:23:04.320
[Guest]: in a way which is sometimes it's like a parody.

01:23:04.320 --> 01:23:08.720
[Guest]: Like I played it ironically, you know, something like that, like in zero, I would throw in

01:23:08.720 --> 01:23:13.600
[Guest]: like heaps of these little things, these little phrases, like if you listen to the solo on

01:23:13.600 --> 01:23:20.720
[Guest]: found, there's a lick from Santana from Europa, and there's one in the IA guitar parts sound

01:23:20.720 --> 01:23:24.820
[Guest]: like Led Zeppelin, your time is going to come, you know, just the I would just throw these

01:23:24.820 --> 01:23:27.320
[Guest]: things in to see like who would notice.

01:23:27.320 --> 01:23:32.360
[Guest]: And then sometimes after 20 years, someone would come and say, hey, that's amazing.

01:23:32.360 --> 01:23:33.360
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:23:33.360 --> 01:23:36.840
[Unknown]: And you and you were notable for doing this in live performances as well.

01:23:36.840 --> 01:23:38.560
[Guest]: Like live was a totally different thing.

01:23:38.560 --> 01:23:41.680
[Guest]: It was like, you know, because at least on a recording, it's committing something to

01:23:41.680 --> 01:23:42.680
[Guest]: posterity live.

01:23:42.680 --> 01:23:46.200
[Guest]: At least then when no one was recording shit on their cell phones, you could do what the

01:23:46.200 --> 01:23:47.200
[Guest]: hell you wanted.

01:23:47.200 --> 01:23:57.120
[Guest]: I remember playing the solo from Metallica song, fade to black, in comfortably numb.

01:23:57.120 --> 01:24:01.040
[Unknown]: And which go very well together, by the way, there's actually a video where a guy superimpose

01:24:01.040 --> 01:24:02.040
[Unknown]: one over there.

01:24:02.040 --> 01:24:06.040
[Unknown]: No, you were you would also do phrases from tujhe dekha toh yeh jana sanam inside IA and

01:24:06.040 --> 01:24:07.040
[Unknown]: things like that.

01:24:07.040 --> 01:24:08.040
[Guest]: Yeah, it's great.

01:24:08.040 --> 01:24:11.600
[Guest]: That that came about at some gig where people would ask us to play Bollywood.

01:24:11.600 --> 01:24:14.960
[Guest]: I was like, this is all I know.

01:24:14.960 --> 01:24:16.160
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:24:16.160 --> 01:24:19.200
[Amit Varma]: Let's take a quick commercial break and on the other side of the break, let's continue

01:24:19.200 --> 01:24:22.400
[Amit Varma]: with your journey.

01:24:22.400 --> 01:24:25.440
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer, but never quite gotten down to it?

01:24:25.440 --> 01:24:26.880
[Amit Varma]: Well, I'd love to help you.

01:24:26.880 --> 01:24:31.760
[Amit Varma]: Since April 2020, I've taught 20 cohorts of my online course, the art of clear writing.

01:24:31.760 --> 01:24:34.920
[Amit Varma]: An online community has now sprung up of all my past students.

01:24:34.920 --> 01:24:39.200
[Amit Varma]: We have workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students and vibrant community

01:24:39.200 --> 01:24:40.200
[Amit Varma]: interaction.

01:24:40.200 --> 01:24:44.560
[Amit Varma]: The course itself, through four webinars spread over four weekends, I share all I know about

01:24:44.560 --> 01:24:46.560
[Amit Varma]: the craft and practice of clear writing.

01:24:46.560 --> 01:24:50.520
[Amit Varma]: There are many exercises, much interaction, a lovely and lively community at the end of

01:24:50.520 --> 01:24:51.520
[Amit Varma]: it.

01:24:51.520 --> 01:24:55.600
[Amit Varma]: The course cost rupees 10,000 plus GST or about 150 dollars and is a monthly thing.

01:24:55.600 --> 01:25:00.480
[Amit Varma]: So if you're interested, head on over to register at IndiaUncut.com slash clear writing.

01:25:00.480 --> 01:25:03.280
[Amit Varma]: That's IndiaUncut.com slash clear writing.

01:25:03.280 --> 01:25:08.080
[Amit Varma]: Being a good writer doesn't require God given talent, just the willingness to work hard

01:25:08.080 --> 01:25:11.640
[Amit Varma]: and a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills.

01:25:11.640 --> 01:25:13.600
[Amit Varma]: I can help you.

01:25:13.600 --> 01:25:14.840
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

01:25:14.840 --> 01:25:17.800
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Warren Mendonza and Chuck Gopal.

01:25:17.800 --> 01:25:23.920
[Amit Varma]: I often wonder, should one say Deepak, should one say Chuck, but we'll just say Chuck.

01:25:23.920 --> 01:25:25.880
[Amit Varma]: Let's continue talking about Black Strat Blues.

01:25:25.880 --> 01:25:29.520
[Amit Varma]: Like we have a whole bunch of albums and they're all pretty different, like the noticeable

01:25:29.520 --> 01:25:33.120
[Amit Varma]: difference between Nights in Shining Karma and your second album, which was called the

01:25:33.120 --> 01:25:36.520
[Amit Varma]: new album, though one could argue all subsequent albums are newer.

01:25:36.520 --> 01:25:40.080
[Amit Varma]: You know, like you yourself said somewhere else that in that first album, the guitar

01:25:40.080 --> 01:25:41.080
[Amit Varma]: is a hero.

01:25:41.080 --> 01:25:45.120
[Amit Varma]: And you spoke about your process of kind of putting it together, you know, your brother's

01:25:45.120 --> 01:25:48.160
[Amit Varma]: laying down the drum tracks and you're just playing everything else.

01:25:48.160 --> 01:25:51.920
[Amit Varma]: But by the second album, you're building soundscapes.

01:25:51.920 --> 01:25:54.040
[Amit Varma]: The guitar is no longer the prominent thing.

01:25:54.040 --> 01:25:56.520
[Amit Varma]: There's this whole vibe that's kind of happening.

01:25:56.520 --> 01:25:59.960
[Amit Varma]: And through later albums, other interesting things happen.

01:25:59.960 --> 01:26:03.960
[Amit Varma]: There are these Indian influences like the Tanpura drone and so on or the tabla or whatever

01:26:03.960 --> 01:26:06.280
[Amit Varma]: coming in at different points in time.

01:26:06.280 --> 01:26:12.160
[Amit Varma]: So what was your evolution during these years of the Black Strat Blues, where it begins

01:26:12.160 --> 01:26:15.200
[Amit Varma]: as a kind of a solo project, but then it becomes something more.

01:26:15.200 --> 01:26:20.000
[Amit Varma]: So kind of take me through that process of, you know, your evolution as a musician and

01:26:20.000 --> 01:26:22.280
[Amit Varma]: of Black Strat Blues as well at the same time.

01:26:22.280 --> 01:26:23.280
[Guest]: Right.

01:26:23.280 --> 01:26:27.840
[Guest]: So the first album was pretty much my brother and me, like I said, by the time the second

01:26:27.840 --> 01:26:30.920
[Guest]: album happened, I had met a few other people.

01:26:30.920 --> 01:26:37.560
[Guest]: So the first guy I met was, who still is one of my dearest friends here, a guy called Cole

01:26:37.560 --> 01:26:38.560
[Guest]: Goodley.

01:26:38.560 --> 01:26:42.440
[Guest]: So I'd gone to watch him at a gig.

01:26:42.440 --> 01:26:44.880
[Guest]: Actually let me backtrack before that.

01:26:44.880 --> 01:26:48.120
[Guest]: When I first moved here, I needed to get a job right away.

01:26:48.120 --> 01:26:55.160
[Guest]: So it was at a local government organization and I met another friend of mine called Emma.

01:26:55.160 --> 01:26:59.080
[Guest]: Now Emma had some songs which I thought were really cool.

01:26:59.080 --> 01:27:02.720
[Guest]: So I said, let me help you put an album together.

01:27:02.720 --> 01:27:04.560
[Guest]: So we started recording.

01:27:04.560 --> 01:27:09.560
[Guest]: Then Emma said, I need drums on one song, but it has to be like a certain style.

01:27:09.560 --> 01:27:13.720
[Guest]: So we had gone to watch this gig and we came across this drummer, Cole Goodley.

01:27:13.720 --> 01:27:16.400
[Guest]: We said, this is the perfect guy for that song.

01:27:16.400 --> 01:27:22.840
[Guest]: So at that time, I was working at a recording studio, I'd quit the day job and I was able

01:27:22.840 --> 01:27:23.840
[Guest]: to use downtime.

01:27:23.840 --> 01:27:28.280
[Guest]: The studio owner was a very sweet guy, so he said, you can use it whenever you want.

01:27:28.280 --> 01:27:30.360
[Guest]: So we used the downtime to record Cole.

01:27:30.360 --> 01:27:36.240
[Guest]: So Cole came over to the studio to record on Emma's song and he did his takes very quickly.

01:27:36.240 --> 01:27:39.420
[Guest]: I think he had what he wanted, give us a few options.

01:27:39.420 --> 01:27:41.680
[Guest]: That was done in an hour and a half.

01:27:41.680 --> 01:27:43.960
[Guest]: And then we had the rest of the evening.

01:27:43.960 --> 01:27:48.120
[Guest]: So then before he started putting his drums away, he started playing something.

01:27:48.120 --> 01:27:51.880
[Guest]: And then he went into Akili's Last Stand, which is like one of my favorite Zeppelin

01:27:51.880 --> 01:27:52.880
[Guest]: songs.

01:27:52.880 --> 01:27:54.200
[Guest]: It's like, dude, just give me a second.

01:27:54.200 --> 01:27:58.360
[Guest]: And I quickly grabbed the Les Paul, which was lying there, plugged it into the Marshall

01:27:58.360 --> 01:27:59.480
[Guest]: and we started playing.

01:27:59.480 --> 01:28:02.200
[Guest]: And then it went on from that to like, oh, do you know this?

01:28:02.200 --> 01:28:03.200
[Guest]: You know that?

01:28:03.200 --> 01:28:07.240
[Guest]: You know, and suddenly we found a whole bunch of common influences and a lifelong friend

01:28:07.240 --> 01:28:09.400
[Guest]: was made in one evening.

01:28:09.400 --> 01:28:13.280
[Guest]: So he said, hey, I'll play on your stuff if you want.

01:28:13.280 --> 01:28:15.800
[Guest]: And I was playing in some demos and everything.

01:28:15.800 --> 01:28:21.200
[Guest]: So he was like a huge contributor on that album, because I still think without his playing,

01:28:21.200 --> 01:28:25.880
[Guest]: the music would never be, you know, I wouldn't say as good or whatever, just wouldn't have

01:28:25.880 --> 01:28:28.840
[Guest]: been that, you know, whatever it is that you hear.

01:28:28.840 --> 01:28:33.080
[Guest]: Because like on a song like Ode to a Sunny Day, he understood exactly what was required.

01:28:33.080 --> 01:28:38.600
[Guest]: If you listen to that original album version, I still think it's probably like the definitive

01:28:38.600 --> 01:28:39.600
[Guest]: version of that.

01:28:39.600 --> 01:28:43.240
[Guest]: Some people like the live one on Gearhouse and everything like that.

01:28:43.240 --> 01:28:48.160
[Guest]: But he brought a lot to the music, whatever he played on it, just, you know, when he heard

01:28:48.160 --> 01:28:51.480
[Guest]: Happy Billy song, he knew instantly I was doing a manic depression on that.

01:28:51.480 --> 01:28:53.360
[Guest]: So he just did the whole Mitch Mitchell thing.

01:28:53.360 --> 01:28:57.960
[Guest]: And he was very good at channeling those, you know, influences like I do on guitar,

01:28:57.960 --> 01:29:01.440
[Guest]: you know, channel a Hendrix or whoever, but still kind of make it your own.

01:29:01.440 --> 01:29:04.320
[Guest]: So he was able to do that same thing on drums, which was awesome.

01:29:04.320 --> 01:29:06.960
[Guest]: It didn't sound like, you know, it was a Hendrix song.

01:29:06.960 --> 01:29:11.440
[Guest]: It sounded like someone who understood Hendrix, but played what had to be played to make that

01:29:11.440 --> 01:29:12.960
[Guest]: thing come to life.

01:29:12.960 --> 01:29:18.080
[Guest]: Similarly with Ode to a Rainy Day, he heard that and he picked up his sticks to start

01:29:18.080 --> 01:29:19.080
[Guest]: the take.

01:29:19.080 --> 01:29:24.240
[Guest]: And he said, right, I'll do my very best Nick Mason on this, you know, and listen to it.

01:29:24.240 --> 01:29:27.400
[Guest]: And he would like sometimes stop and start and everything, but he kind of did all the

01:29:27.400 --> 01:29:31.040
[Guest]: drums for that album in one day, which is kind of, you know, pretty amazing.

01:29:31.040 --> 01:29:32.720
[Guest]: It's all, it's all done in one day.

01:29:32.720 --> 01:29:36.680
[Guest]: And after he left, I still had some time before it like got too late.

01:29:36.680 --> 01:29:40.240
[Guest]: And I remember I was so like inspired by what we had just recorded, and I finished Happy

01:29:40.240 --> 01:29:41.760
[Guest]: Billy that same evening.

01:29:41.760 --> 01:29:45.680
[Guest]: Can you imagine like you spend a whole day recording drums and you still have some energy

01:29:45.680 --> 01:29:49.880
[Guest]: to put down all the guitar parts, you know, whatever.

01:29:49.880 --> 01:29:54.560
[Guest]: So in that sense, the whole collaborative energy brought like a totally different thing

01:29:54.560 --> 01:29:56.480
[Guest]: to the music.

01:29:56.480 --> 01:29:59.520
[Guest]: And by the time of the second album, I had been living here for a while.

01:29:59.520 --> 01:30:06.280
[Guest]: So I kind of become accustomed to, you know, a little bit of a slower pace of life.

01:30:06.280 --> 01:30:10.200
[Guest]: Once the third album comes on, that becomes like another change altogether, because by

01:30:10.200 --> 01:30:11.840
[Guest]: then I'd moved back to India.

01:30:11.840 --> 01:30:16.680
[Guest]: If you notice, between the second and the third album, there's a good six years gap.

01:30:16.680 --> 01:30:21.500
[Guest]: So that was me getting accustomed back into, you know, being a professional musician back

01:30:21.500 --> 01:30:23.600
[Guest]: in India and everything like that.

01:30:23.600 --> 01:30:28.560
[Guest]: So then by the time the third album came about, I had met Adi.

01:30:28.560 --> 01:30:33.440
[Guest]: In fact, Adi and me had played together long back at a gig where his band and my band had

01:30:33.440 --> 01:30:34.440
[Guest]: played together.

01:30:34.440 --> 01:30:39.480
[Guest]: And then the vocal, Mike Blue, it was on a boat, the vocal PA Blue, so it became an instrumental

01:30:39.480 --> 01:30:40.480
[Guest]: jam.

01:30:40.480 --> 01:30:41.480
[Guest]: So that there's a picture of that.

01:30:41.480 --> 01:30:44.920
[Guest]: I think I can share it with you later if you want.

01:30:44.920 --> 01:30:48.600
[Guest]: And so we knew each other and everything, but we never really played together as such.

01:30:48.600 --> 01:30:53.440
[Guest]: And then we had to play together at Ehsan and Roy's Coke Studio.

01:30:53.440 --> 01:30:56.360
[Guest]: So that was the first time we spent a lot of time, because in between rehearsals and

01:30:56.360 --> 01:30:57.360
[Guest]: we were just sitting and jamming.

01:30:57.360 --> 01:31:02.000
[Guest]: I think at one point there was Prakash Sondake on pedal steel, who knows the whole dark side

01:31:02.000 --> 01:31:04.400
[Guest]: of the moon, you know, all the steel parts.

01:31:04.400 --> 01:31:07.760
[Guest]: And then Ehsan and Adi and I think Debu was playing drums.

01:31:07.760 --> 01:31:13.200
[Guest]: So like between rehearsals for that episode, we were only playing Pink Floyd, it was hilarious.

01:31:13.200 --> 01:31:17.560
[Guest]: So Adi and me started getting along at that point.

01:31:17.560 --> 01:31:22.480
[Guest]: And Jai, who had played on the very first Blackstar Blues tour, but had never recorded

01:31:22.480 --> 01:31:28.840
[Guest]: on any of the albums, but I figured Jai and Adi would be a good, you know, team together.

01:31:28.840 --> 01:31:33.720
[Guest]: Because Jai is the guy who will push with serious energy, but Adi is the guy who will

01:31:33.720 --> 01:31:35.440
[Guest]: hold things back and ground it.

01:31:35.440 --> 01:31:39.640
[Guest]: So you have a perfect blend of those two, you know, because if you have both guys pushing

01:31:39.640 --> 01:31:44.480
[Guest]: at the same time, it can blow out of control, you know, the car will just go off the track.

01:31:44.480 --> 01:31:48.720
[Guest]: So one guy is holding it back and, you know, guiding things.

01:31:48.720 --> 01:31:50.200
[Guest]: So that became a trio.

01:31:50.200 --> 01:31:54.280
[Guest]: And then as a trio, we recorded the third album.

01:31:54.280 --> 01:31:59.080
[Guest]: And I think we had also worked a fair bit with Karsh.

01:31:59.080 --> 01:32:03.960
[Guest]: So Karsh and Jai had split drum duties on that third album.

01:32:03.960 --> 01:32:07.680
[Guest]: Then the following year, I'd met Bevan on Clinton's Coke Studio.

01:32:07.680 --> 01:32:12.520
[Guest]: So two Blackstar Blues band members came from Coke Studio.

01:32:12.520 --> 01:32:15.920
[Guest]: So Bevan, I used to drive with him for Clinton's rehearsals, and I was playing him like all

01:32:15.920 --> 01:32:18.200
[Guest]: the third album stuff and everything.

01:32:18.200 --> 01:32:22.060
[Guest]: So he turns to me and he said, if you ever need a keyboard player, just let me know.

01:32:22.060 --> 01:32:26.480
[Guest]: And I was shocked because like Bevan is like a seriously skilled musician and to play with

01:32:26.480 --> 01:32:30.560
[Guest]: us jokers, like rock band jokers, I was like, you will play with us?

01:32:30.560 --> 01:32:32.660
[Guest]: And he said, yeah, I'll play with you.

01:32:32.660 --> 01:32:37.480
[Guest]: So at that point, it became like, you know, everything just fell into place and you could

01:32:37.480 --> 01:32:38.480
[Guest]: kind of sense it.

01:32:38.480 --> 01:32:43.760
[Guest]: And then that's when that last analog generation happened, which I think is probably after

01:32:43.760 --> 01:32:44.760
[Guest]: the second album.

01:32:44.760 --> 01:32:47.840
[Guest]: That's like my favorite one till now.

01:32:47.840 --> 01:32:53.520
[Guest]: So that point, it became a band and then a lot of live gigs happened as well.

01:32:53.520 --> 01:32:57.400
[Guest]: So that kind of solidified the lineup.

01:32:57.400 --> 01:33:02.080
[Guest]: And then I put out an album called When It's Time When I knew it was going to be time for

01:33:02.080 --> 01:33:05.600
[Guest]: that to to wind up and make the move back.

01:33:05.600 --> 01:33:09.360
[Guest]: Because at that time, when my kid was born, it was like, OK, you kind of have to stop

01:33:09.360 --> 01:33:10.600
[Guest]: thinking about yourself.

01:33:10.600 --> 01:33:15.200
[Guest]: And then there's another person that you have to consider making plans and everything.

01:33:15.200 --> 01:33:22.160
[Guest]: So at that point, it just became pretty evident that if a child is a New Zealand citizen,

01:33:22.160 --> 01:33:25.560
[Guest]: she should probably grow up in New Zealand.

01:33:25.560 --> 01:33:30.560
[Guest]: So at that point, it was a bit hard, you know, because we had kind of done so many killer

01:33:30.560 --> 01:33:32.720
[Guest]: gigs and everything together.

01:33:32.720 --> 01:33:37.600
[Guest]: But again, it was kind of almost like a hop back to the zero thing, where like, you know,

01:33:37.600 --> 01:33:41.880
[Guest]: the band had solidified really nicely, but then you have to just say, you know, then

01:33:41.880 --> 01:33:46.280
[Guest]: it was because of me that I moved and now it was because of her.

01:33:46.280 --> 01:33:56.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'm also, you know, another sort of area I want to explore is what the other influences

01:33:56.160 --> 01:33:59.360
[Amit Varma]: around you, how that shaped your music, like in one of your interviews, you speak about

01:33:59.360 --> 01:34:04.800
[Amit Varma]: how, you know, during Ganpati, you used to hear that drumbeat and later you hear the

01:34:04.800 --> 01:34:09.320
[Amit Varma]: same beat in Black Sabbath and you feel that there's sort of a commonality there.

01:34:09.320 --> 01:34:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And in another interview, at one point, you said this quote that stuck with me, where

01:34:15.000 --> 01:34:19.280
[Amit Varma]: you said, quote, I have an unproven theory that all forms of folk music are intertwined

01:34:19.280 --> 01:34:22.560
[Amit Varma]: down to the pentatonic scale that exists in all cultures.

01:34:22.560 --> 01:34:26.400
[Amit Varma]: After having worked with many Indian classical musicians, it's pretty easy to spot parallel

01:34:26.400 --> 01:34:29.840
[Amit Varma]: threads to the music, and this makes collaboration a possibility.

01:34:29.840 --> 01:34:34.120
[Amit Varma]: For me personally, it's a common areas found in rhythm percussion that are the most appealing,

01:34:34.120 --> 01:34:39.080
[Amit Varma]: stop quote, like, you know, the Ganpati beat and Black Sabbath, perhaps, and equally, you've

01:34:39.080 --> 01:34:42.840
[Amit Varma]: been a sessions player in a lot of film recordings and all of that.

01:34:42.840 --> 01:34:47.600
[Amit Varma]: I think you've done a couple of Dance Masti albums, you've been Amit Trivedi's live guitarist,

01:34:47.600 --> 01:34:52.560
[Amit Varma]: you've performed with, you know, Ehsan Loy, Rehman, all of these guys.

01:34:52.560 --> 01:34:58.520
[Amit Varma]: So you're not just any kind of blues musician, you've got a much wider array of influences

01:34:58.520 --> 01:35:03.280
[Amit Varma]: and most people like I often tell people that anyone in India is by default luckier than

01:35:03.280 --> 01:35:06.920
[Amit Varma]: the rest of the world in at least one way, which is that we are multilingual, you know,

01:35:06.920 --> 01:35:10.760
[Amit Varma]: in Europe, people will speak one language, we speak three, four languages, there's so

01:35:10.760 --> 01:35:12.720
[Amit Varma]: much else coming in from there.

01:35:12.720 --> 01:35:18.580
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, in a musical sense, you've got that same sort of good fortune, not of

01:35:18.580 --> 01:35:21.880
[Amit Varma]: just being surrounded by different kinds of music, but being able to listen to them and

01:35:21.880 --> 01:35:23.560
[Amit Varma]: find these commonalities.

01:35:23.560 --> 01:35:28.240
[Amit Varma]: So expand on this a little bit, tell me about, you know, what are these sort of different

01:35:28.240 --> 01:35:29.240
[Amit Varma]: common elements?

01:35:29.240 --> 01:35:31.640
[Amit Varma]: How has it shaped your music and so on?

01:35:31.640 --> 01:35:36.000
[Guest]: Well, the the pentatonic scale is definitely there in every culture, you can hear that

01:35:36.000 --> 01:35:41.560
[Guest]: there's a nice video that Bobby McFerrin shows, where he kind of has a theory that it's part

01:35:41.560 --> 01:35:45.400
[Guest]: of our DNA, the pentatonic scale is part of our human DNA.

01:35:45.400 --> 01:35:47.640
[Guest]: So that's worth checking out.

01:35:47.640 --> 01:35:53.400
[Guest]: The 6-8 groove, you can hear that in every single culture, African, Celtic, you know,

01:35:53.400 --> 01:35:57.480
[Guest]: American, Indian, tribal stuff, Asian music, you'll hear it.

01:35:57.480 --> 01:36:01.440
[Guest]: I mean, everywhere you go, you'll find that 6-8, it has to come, and that's kind of one

01:36:01.440 --> 01:36:02.440
[Guest]: of my favorite grooves.

01:36:02.440 --> 01:36:07.240
[Guest]: So you listen to a song like Focus 3, for example, that's kind of where I exploited

01:36:07.240 --> 01:36:13.360
[Guest]: that whole thing, which is like a visarjan kind of groove, but it's also like a blues

01:36:13.360 --> 01:36:17.800
[Guest]: shuffle that, you know, that 6-8 thing as well.

01:36:17.800 --> 01:36:22.320
[Guest]: So I love that, you know, for me, it's like finding something that's that's pretty universal,

01:36:22.320 --> 01:36:26.120
[Guest]: you know, which again, you know, most people would be able to relate.

01:36:26.120 --> 01:36:29.400
[Guest]: And then the fact that it's instrumental means there's no lyrics.

01:36:29.400 --> 01:36:35.160
[Guest]: So technically, it shouldn't prevent from anyone who listens to any kind of language

01:36:35.160 --> 01:36:39.400
[Guest]: to not be able to get it.

01:36:39.400 --> 01:36:44.640
[Guest]: But in terms of relating to other musicians, I think you kind of have to keep your ears

01:36:44.640 --> 01:36:49.080
[Guest]: open, because there's obviously some things they'll do in some particular raag, which,

01:36:49.080 --> 01:36:52.040
[Guest]: you know, I'll have no idea, then I'll have to kind of ask them like, what exactly is

01:36:52.040 --> 01:36:53.040
[Guest]: going on?

01:36:53.040 --> 01:36:57.400
[Guest]: And once you, there are only 12 notes, but how you use those 12 notes, infinite, you

01:36:57.400 --> 01:37:01.360
[Guest]: know, combinations, and then you have to listen to things like microtonal inflections, you

01:37:01.360 --> 01:37:02.920
[Guest]: know, how they bend into that note.

01:37:02.920 --> 01:37:07.640
[Guest]: There's another nice video, Derek Trucks talking about Indian music and how it's common, like

01:37:07.640 --> 01:37:11.240
[Guest]: the microtones, to gospel music in America.

01:37:11.240 --> 01:37:12.240
[Guest]: So that's worth checking out.

01:37:12.240 --> 01:37:15.360
[Guest]: I can send you a link.

01:37:15.360 --> 01:37:18.840
[Guest]: But every time I find something like that, it just makes me feel like warm and fuzzy

01:37:18.840 --> 01:37:25.040
[Guest]: inside, you know, like there's something common among us all as humans, which doesn't matter

01:37:25.040 --> 01:37:29.480
[Guest]: where you were born, you still can, you know, I mean, there's, I mean, have you gone to

01:37:29.480 --> 01:37:36.680
[Guest]: a place where nobody likes Bob Marley, go to any beach town, there's some form of that

01:37:36.680 --> 01:37:38.640
[Guest]: music which is playing.

01:37:38.640 --> 01:37:45.180
[Guest]: So I don't know, I just think the ability of, you know, the whole genre thing is basically

01:37:45.180 --> 01:37:46.720
[Guest]: a marketing construct.

01:37:46.720 --> 01:37:50.200
[Guest]: It's basically people want to sell things in certain boxes.

01:37:50.200 --> 01:37:55.360
[Guest]: So it has to be, I mean, would you call Led Zeppelin a reggae band just because they had

01:37:55.360 --> 01:37:56.360
[Guest]: a reggae song?

01:37:56.360 --> 01:38:00.640
[Guest]: No, they were just Led Zeppelin, you know, I mean, you could say they were a rock band.

01:38:00.640 --> 01:38:03.400
[Guest]: So similarly, I wouldn't really consider myself a blues musician.

01:38:03.400 --> 01:38:08.680
[Guest]: I think I have like a lifetime to live as a blues musician to be classified as one.

01:38:08.680 --> 01:38:09.680
[Guest]: I love the blues.

01:38:09.680 --> 01:38:10.680
[Guest]: I love where it comes from.

01:38:10.680 --> 01:38:12.120
[Guest]: I love also expanding it.

01:38:12.120 --> 01:38:16.020
[Guest]: I think like early cream, they did cool things with the blues, where they would like taking

01:38:16.020 --> 01:38:20.740
[Guest]: traditional forms and kind of, you know, making it a little bit more of its time.

01:38:20.740 --> 01:38:25.400
[Guest]: So I like artists who do that, who take from traditional forms and are able to, you know,

01:38:25.400 --> 01:38:31.520
[Guest]: do something different with it, where you can retain, you know, where it's coming from,

01:38:31.520 --> 01:38:33.920
[Guest]: but you know, it's not that, where it's coming from.

01:38:33.920 --> 01:38:34.920
[Guest]: It's something else.

01:38:34.920 --> 01:38:39.640
[Unknown]: You know, one of the questions that I wanted to ask was, so you spoke about how you're

01:38:39.640 --> 01:38:44.080
[Unknown]: a fan of artists who take something with an existing genre and add on to it.

01:38:44.080 --> 01:38:45.520
[Unknown]: And that's really how music evolves, right?

01:38:45.520 --> 01:38:48.360
[Unknown]: So have you seen any of that happen recently?

01:38:48.360 --> 01:38:54.840
[Unknown]: Like, for example, you can argue that rock is now, rock and heavy metal are now traditional

01:38:54.840 --> 01:39:00.240
[Unknown]: forms of music in some sense, like how the blues and early rock and beat music was.

01:39:00.240 --> 01:39:04.080
[Unknown]: I've come across some artists doing fascinating things, like an artist I came across recently

01:39:04.080 --> 01:39:08.920
[Unknown]: is called Carpenter Brute, who takes traditional heavy metal and adds a lot of influences from

01:39:08.920 --> 01:39:09.920
[Unknown]: electronic music.

01:39:09.920 --> 01:39:10.920
[Unknown]: So it's basically just him.

01:39:10.920 --> 01:39:13.820
[Unknown]: It's basically a metal DJ on stage.

01:39:13.820 --> 01:39:18.280
[Unknown]: And while I may not be a complete fan of things like that, I think that pushes music in different

01:39:18.280 --> 01:39:21.200
[Unknown]: directions, even if it makes some people slightly uncomfortable.

01:39:21.200 --> 01:39:25.300
[Unknown]: I saw this at a metal fest, so it obviously alienated the audience a fair bit.

01:39:25.300 --> 01:39:27.040
[Unknown]: Have you come across any examples like this?

01:39:27.040 --> 01:39:31.080
[Unknown]: And like, just generally, where do you think music, especially the types that we love so

01:39:31.080 --> 01:39:32.720
[Unknown]: much, where could it go?

01:39:32.720 --> 01:39:38.200
[Unknown]: Do you see like more of a role of traditional scales and instruments, for example, around

01:39:38.200 --> 01:39:39.200
[Unknown]: the world?

01:39:39.200 --> 01:39:44.720
[Unknown]: I've come across music like I was just telling Amit before our recording, I came across something

01:39:44.720 --> 01:39:49.920
[Unknown]: called Torek guitar, which is North African psychedelic guitar.

01:39:49.920 --> 01:39:55.640
[Unknown]: And you would love this absolutely with artists like Umdu Mukhtar, if I've got the pronunciation

01:39:55.640 --> 01:40:04.560
[Unknown]: right, who play a very Hendrix like fuzz sound, but with what is unmistakably Arabic influence

01:40:04.560 --> 01:40:10.160
[Unknown]: or that or North African influence of sorts or like Tinariwen.

01:40:10.160 --> 01:40:11.280
[Unknown]: Have you come across any like this?

01:40:11.280 --> 01:40:12.720
[Unknown]: And what do you think about stuff like this?

01:40:12.720 --> 01:40:18.000
[Unknown]: Like, where do you think at least the music that we like rock and metal could go?

01:40:18.000 --> 01:40:23.280
[Guest]: For me, like if, like, for example, if I hear a bit of Hendrix, I'm immediately drawn in

01:40:23.280 --> 01:40:29.880
[Guest]: because that's like such a, you know, like if you're ever in doubt about what to play

01:40:29.880 --> 01:40:36.360
[Guest]: on guitar, do a journey, it'll work for most, you know, that's, that's also like one of

01:40:36.360 --> 01:40:39.600
[Guest]: the things that you like, I know certain things will work, you know.

01:40:39.600 --> 01:40:42.360
[Guest]: So like you said, like, it sounds a bit like that Hendrix fuzz thing.

01:40:42.360 --> 01:40:46.080
[Guest]: That's kind of like a universal sound now, you know, like any guitar player across the

01:40:46.080 --> 01:40:48.600
[Guest]: world knows what, what Hendrix sounds like.

01:40:48.600 --> 01:40:53.640
[Guest]: There's a really nice band from Sweden called Dungeon.

01:40:53.640 --> 01:40:54.640
[Guest]: So it's spelled D-U-N-G-E-N.

01:40:54.640 --> 01:41:00.400
[Guest]: They sing in Swedish, but it doesn't really matter because the music is amazing.

01:41:00.400 --> 01:41:05.160
[Guest]: Guitar player is like a little bit of a, you know, you can hear the Hendrix influence,

01:41:05.160 --> 01:41:07.900
[Guest]: but he's also like totally his own guy.

01:41:07.900 --> 01:41:11.240
[Guest]: So that's another thing which, you know, you can take the similar sound like that Hendrix

01:41:11.240 --> 01:41:15.220
[Guest]: fuzzed out like relic guitar sound and do different things with it.

01:41:15.220 --> 01:41:22.960
[Guest]: So I would recommend checking out, there's one album called Ta Det Lunt, L-U-G-N-T.

01:41:22.960 --> 01:41:24.960
[Guest]: So that's, I think that's their second or third album.

01:41:24.960 --> 01:41:26.860
[Guest]: And there's one album called Four.

01:41:26.860 --> 01:41:34.160
[Guest]: If you listen to that Four album, there's one killer song called Mina Damar Ok Fasana.

01:41:34.160 --> 01:41:37.400
[Guest]: I'm pronouncing it horribly, but whatever you can from my, you know, you can kind of

01:41:37.400 --> 01:41:38.600
[Guest]: get the spelling.

01:41:38.600 --> 01:41:43.660
[Guest]: So this song, you can hear that fuzz guitar thing, but it almost sounds like Arabic or

01:41:43.660 --> 01:41:50.160
[Guest]: Indian in a slightly Bollywood way, it goes something like that.

01:41:50.160 --> 01:41:55.260
[Guest]: And the groove is man, like this fat ass, like something like that, you know?

01:41:55.260 --> 01:42:00.320
[Guest]: So then, you know, you can, you can, you're like different influences, but it's coming

01:42:00.320 --> 01:42:05.800
[Guest]: together in such a unique way, which just sounds like that and nothing else.

01:42:05.800 --> 01:42:10.140
[Guest]: You know, again, which brings you back, like you, you're a little bit of the commonality

01:42:10.140 --> 01:42:13.440
[Guest]: in it, but it's something totally different, which you've never heard before.

01:42:13.440 --> 01:42:17.840
[Guest]: And that like, is what I live for.

01:42:17.840 --> 01:42:21.200
[Guest]: Have you ever heard of this guy called Josh Fix, by any chance?

01:42:21.200 --> 01:42:22.200
[Guest]: Josh Fix?

01:42:22.200 --> 01:42:23.200
[Guest]: No, I haven't.

01:42:23.200 --> 01:42:27.880
[Guest]: So this guy, I think he came out in 2004 or 5.

01:42:27.880 --> 01:42:33.920
[Guest]: And he had this album called, I'll send you the name later.

01:42:33.920 --> 01:42:39.580
[Guest]: But it sounded like Queen, Elton John, you know, that kind of thing, piano driven rock,

01:42:39.580 --> 01:42:41.360
[Guest]: but the production is immaculate.

01:42:41.360 --> 01:42:43.520
[Guest]: Like you can't help but not like it.

01:42:43.520 --> 01:42:47.480
[Guest]: And he found quite a few fans in like, say, Steve Lukather, you know, like, you know,

01:42:47.480 --> 01:42:48.840
[Guest]: prominent musicians.

01:42:48.840 --> 01:42:52.800
[Guest]: And then he had an EP after that with the most killer name, This Town Is Starting To

01:42:52.800 --> 01:42:55.320
[Guest]: Make Me Angry.

01:42:55.320 --> 01:42:59.100
[Guest]: So two, like one great album, one amazing EP.

01:42:59.100 --> 01:43:02.080
[Guest]: And then you never heard of him again, you know, he just disappeared.

01:43:02.080 --> 01:43:04.400
[Guest]: And I guess he kind of grew disillusioned or whatever.

01:43:04.400 --> 01:43:06.940
[Guest]: And that's only something I'm speculating.

01:43:06.940 --> 01:43:12.160
[Guest]: But with an artist like that, you can again, you know, where he's coming from very clearly.

01:43:12.160 --> 01:43:16.200
[Guest]: But again, it's so uniquely him, like just the way things are put together.

01:43:16.200 --> 01:43:21.760
[Guest]: So that can be a facet of your originality, the way you put things together, from styles

01:43:21.760 --> 01:43:22.760
[Guest]: that have come from you.

01:43:22.760 --> 01:43:27.500
[Guest]: So you can take things that are very, like, you know, almost universal in a way, but combine

01:43:27.500 --> 01:43:31.560
[Guest]: them in a certain way, which, you know, I guess people have been doing that in every

01:43:31.560 --> 01:43:37.400
[Guest]: genre for the last 20 years.

01:43:37.400 --> 01:43:41.440
[Amit Varma]: So I want to get back to a question that we touched upon right at the start, which is,

01:43:41.440 --> 01:43:46.020
[Amit Varma]: you know, the question of form and content, how they affect each other, like, you know,

01:43:46.020 --> 01:43:50.860
[Amit Varma]: every form that we kind of have came because of a physical reason, you could only fit so

01:43:50.860 --> 01:43:52.680
[Amit Varma]: many minutes of music on an LP.

01:43:52.680 --> 01:43:57.080
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, that's your album length, or a radio will typically, you know, they'll

01:43:57.080 --> 01:43:58.760
[Amit Varma]: play a three minute this thing.

01:43:58.760 --> 01:44:00.760
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, that becomes kind of a standard.

01:44:00.760 --> 01:44:05.200
[Amit Varma]: Today, you will find bands optimizing for the first 30 seconds on Spotify, because you

01:44:05.200 --> 01:44:09.480
[Amit Varma]: got to make the guy finish 30 seconds, you know, when advanced mics first came about

01:44:09.480 --> 01:44:14.840
[Amit Varma]: in the 1920s, people started singing differently, Bing Crosby could whisper into the mic, and,

01:44:14.840 --> 01:44:19.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, didn't have to sort of throw his voice today, you know, record labels will

01:44:19.800 --> 01:44:24.480
[Amit Varma]: ask artists to have that 15 second catchy bit, which you know, TikTok or reels can pick

01:44:24.480 --> 01:44:25.480
[Amit Varma]: up.

01:44:25.480 --> 01:44:31.680
[Amit Varma]: But what has happened is that we somehow as creators, and I'm talking across everything,

01:44:31.680 --> 01:44:36.240
[Amit Varma]: not just music, we get stuck in old formats, writers will only think of 800 word pieces

01:44:36.240 --> 01:44:41.600
[Amit Varma]: or 100,000 word books, or filmmakers will think in terms of like a 24 minute TV episode

01:44:41.600 --> 01:44:45.080
[Amit Varma]: or a 90 minute Hollywood film, and so on and so forth.

01:44:45.080 --> 01:44:49.840
[Amit Varma]: But one, in many fields, those formats don't matter anymore, the reasons why they came

01:44:49.840 --> 01:44:53.920
[Amit Varma]: about in the first place are, they don't matter, they've gone.

01:44:53.920 --> 01:44:59.640
[Amit Varma]: And in music, you've got new imperatives, like sort of the one that we discussed.

01:44:59.640 --> 01:45:04.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, what has happened is that many of these formats have become cliches, or formulas,

01:45:04.920 --> 01:45:10.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, so I got this video on YouTube, where this guy was analyzing the formula for

01:45:10.080 --> 01:45:15.480
[Amit Varma]: a perfect pop song, which was 114.2 beats per minute, 3 minutes 59 seconds long, moderately

01:45:15.480 --> 01:45:19.200
[Amit Varma]: danceable in the key of C major, and so on and so forth.

01:45:19.200 --> 01:45:22.920
[Amit Varma]: There's another video that breaks down what Max Martin does, you know, where your chorus

01:45:22.920 --> 01:45:27.240
[Amit Varma]: will start between 40 seconds to a minute, your lyrics will be below fourth grade reading

01:45:27.240 --> 01:45:32.120
[Amit Varma]: level, simple harmonic structures, short, unique intros, because many people are, you

01:45:32.120 --> 01:45:36.320
[Amit Varma]: know, kind of, if you're playing, if you're a DJ changing tracks on a loud this thing,

01:45:36.320 --> 01:45:40.540
[Amit Varma]: the intro has to be catchy for people to stay on the dance floor, and so on and so forth.

01:45:40.540 --> 01:45:45.100
[Amit Varma]: So all these formulas have evolved, and they've evolved because of one commercial imperatives,

01:45:45.100 --> 01:45:48.560
[Amit Varma]: because obviously labels will look at what is successful and just want to repeat that

01:45:48.560 --> 01:45:50.200
[Amit Varma]: and that becomes a formula.

01:45:50.200 --> 01:45:53.420
[Amit Varma]: Two, it's because you've gotten used to a particular kind of form.

01:45:53.420 --> 01:45:56.960
[Amit Varma]: So you think, oh, every song has to be three minutes or four minutes or whatever that so

01:45:56.960 --> 01:45:58.720
[Amit Varma]: called optimal length is.

01:45:58.720 --> 01:46:03.080
[Amit Varma]: And three, because of the way our brains are wired, as you said, all our brains are wired

01:46:03.080 --> 01:46:04.800
[Amit Varma]: in the same kind of way.

01:46:04.800 --> 01:46:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Something will sound musical to us, something else will not sound musical to us.

01:46:08.480 --> 01:46:12.540
[Amit Varma]: So in some senses, you're kind of catering to how our brains are wired, and you kind

01:46:12.540 --> 01:46:15.920
[Amit Varma]: of therefore slip into those same old grooves.

01:46:15.920 --> 01:46:22.120
[Amit Varma]: So what is your sort of thinking about this, because, you know, one of the things you mentioned

01:46:22.120 --> 01:46:26.080
[Amit Varma]: that Auckland allowed you to do, for example, just going there, and maybe it's just a part

01:46:26.080 --> 01:46:31.400
[Amit Varma]: of maturity of any artist or any person is that you're able to sit back and re examine

01:46:31.400 --> 01:46:35.220
[Amit Varma]: all of this, and you know, your role in all of this and all of that.

01:46:35.220 --> 01:46:41.440
[Amit Varma]: So what do you think about all of these things that, you know, Chuck in an old piece had,

01:46:41.440 --> 01:46:46.960
[Amit Varma]: in fact, written about your stuff very, I'll quote Chuck now, there's something in his

01:46:46.960 --> 01:46:51.520
[Amit Varma]: compositions that move from familiar intro, to slow part where people can soak it in and

01:46:51.520 --> 01:46:55.600
[Amit Varma]: notice how good the other musicians are, to faster part when the pace picks up to epic

01:46:55.600 --> 01:47:00.120
[Amit Varma]: ending when everyone goes berserk, fuck how good is everyone in this band that just works

01:47:00.120 --> 01:47:01.400
[Amit Varma]: with any audience.

01:47:01.400 --> 01:47:04.020
[Amit Varma]: And he continued elaborating on that.

01:47:04.020 --> 01:47:05.400
[Amit Varma]: So what is your sense of that?

01:47:05.400 --> 01:47:09.160
[Amit Varma]: Because I guess when you start without even thinking about it without even thinking, oh,

01:47:09.160 --> 01:47:13.000
[Amit Varma]: this is a formula, this is what I need to do, you just gravitate to that.

01:47:13.000 --> 01:47:17.040
[Amit Varma]: But then later on, you've tried many different things in different structures.

01:47:17.040 --> 01:47:20.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about how you sort of think about all of this.

01:47:20.000 --> 01:47:25.160
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, for every song that fits that, that formula, there's also another one that

01:47:25.160 --> 01:47:29.800
[Guest]: doesn't, you know, so it just depends upon, you know, which are the ones that you latch

01:47:29.800 --> 01:47:31.120
[Guest]: on to.

01:47:31.120 --> 01:47:35.160
[Guest]: The thing is, also, you have to keep in mind, are you making music for mass consumption?

01:47:35.160 --> 01:47:37.720
[Guest]: Are you doing it for your own gratification?

01:47:37.720 --> 01:47:41.720
[Guest]: I do it currently, because I want to make myself happy.

01:47:41.720 --> 01:47:48.640
[Guest]: Now, the moment the commercial consideration comes into mind, I may have to change the

01:47:48.640 --> 01:47:50.080
[Guest]: way I do it.

01:47:50.080 --> 01:47:55.400
[Guest]: At this point, at least I'm still able to at least make the music I want to, and still

01:47:55.400 --> 01:47:56.920
[Guest]: have a roof over my head.

01:47:56.920 --> 01:47:58.520
[Guest]: But that could change, you know, another day.

01:47:58.520 --> 01:48:04.080
[Guest]: And then I may have to totally, you know, re-tweak, maybe I have to do 30 second songs

01:48:04.080 --> 01:48:05.080
[Guest]: or whatever.

01:48:05.080 --> 01:48:09.080
[Guest]: I mean, I worked in advertising for a very long time, so I know how advertising music

01:48:09.080 --> 01:48:10.080
[Guest]: works.

01:48:10.080 --> 01:48:13.880
[Guest]: And there is definitely like a certain formula that has to work in context, like it can't

01:48:13.880 --> 01:48:17.520
[Guest]: get in the way of the voiceover, for example, that's like the golden rule, otherwise they

01:48:17.520 --> 01:48:18.520
[Guest]: will pull it down.

01:48:18.520 --> 01:48:22.200
[Guest]: The music track gets pulled down and the voiceover is on top of everything.

01:48:22.200 --> 01:48:25.680
[Guest]: That VO is God.

01:48:25.680 --> 01:48:31.000
[Guest]: So with confirming to certain parameters, now, obviously, the parameters you confirm

01:48:31.000 --> 01:48:35.840
[Guest]: to when you make music for yourself are your own preferences.

01:48:35.840 --> 01:48:38.440
[Guest]: You like things to sound a certain way.

01:48:38.440 --> 01:48:43.320
[Guest]: And you know, I'm a little bit old, so I still want to make an album rather than, you know,

01:48:43.320 --> 01:48:45.000
[Guest]: a TikTok reel.

01:48:45.000 --> 01:48:46.000
[Guest]: It may just change.

01:48:46.000 --> 01:48:50.240
[Guest]: Like my daughter may suddenly say, Dad, make me a song, which is 30 seconds, I'll make

01:48:50.240 --> 01:48:51.240
[Guest]: a song.

01:48:51.240 --> 01:48:52.240
[Guest]: I want to see if you're happy.

01:48:52.240 --> 01:48:53.240
[Guest]: So I'll do it.

01:48:53.240 --> 01:48:54.240
[Guest]: You know, that sort of thing.

01:48:54.240 --> 01:48:58.760
[Guest]: So I'm never going to like discount, like saying this is the right way or that is the

01:48:58.760 --> 01:48:59.760
[Guest]: wrong way.

01:48:59.760 --> 01:49:03.280
[Guest]: Everything is like at this point in my life, everything goes.

01:49:03.280 --> 01:49:06.800
[Guest]: You see what you like and you latch on to that.

01:49:06.800 --> 01:49:08.840
[Guest]: And there's so much music out there.

01:49:08.840 --> 01:49:13.240
[Guest]: So let's, you know, try to keep ourselves happy by listening to music we like.

01:49:13.240 --> 01:49:18.320
[Guest]: Apart from that, you know, the attention spans are different these days.

01:49:18.320 --> 01:49:23.440
[Guest]: So, you know, where a double album would be something that people could consume in one

01:49:23.440 --> 01:49:28.720
[Guest]: sitting in this day and age, I don't think a majority of people, even I find myself like

01:49:28.720 --> 01:49:32.760
[Guest]: there are certain times like once everyone's gone to bed, then I can put on an album and

01:49:32.760 --> 01:49:34.640
[Guest]: listen to it in entirety.

01:49:34.640 --> 01:49:38.520
[Guest]: And these days also, I find like, I'll just not, you know, do something else.

01:49:38.520 --> 01:49:42.240
[Guest]: Like I'm always like something or the others there that, you know, like in my room, I'll

01:49:42.240 --> 01:49:44.960
[Guest]: be cleaning up something or something while doing it.

01:49:44.960 --> 01:49:51.560
[Guest]: But at least my musical attention is focused on what's playing, you know, in that sense.

01:49:51.560 --> 01:49:57.280
[Guest]: So for me, it's like, again, the trick is to keep finding music that makes you feel

01:49:57.280 --> 01:49:58.280
[Guest]: that way.

01:49:58.280 --> 01:50:02.880
[Guest]: And, you know, the old stuff, there'll be certain music, which no matter how many times

01:50:02.880 --> 01:50:04.520
[Guest]: like my daughter and I listen to The Beatles.

01:50:04.520 --> 01:50:10.200
[Guest]: So I listen to Blackboard in my car literally nine or ten times on repeat.

01:50:10.200 --> 01:50:14.000
[Guest]: And I don't get, I don't have a problem with that, you know, it's a cool song.

01:50:14.000 --> 01:50:16.480
[Guest]: So no worries with it on repeat.

01:50:16.480 --> 01:50:23.480
[Guest]: So the people who are making music by formula, I have no problem with them doing that because

01:50:23.480 --> 01:50:25.560
[Guest]: that's what they have to do at that point of time.

01:50:25.560 --> 01:50:30.200
[Guest]: So, you know, if you write for Bollywood, now the director becomes your, you know, your

01:50:30.200 --> 01:50:31.200
[Guest]: God.

01:50:31.200 --> 01:50:32.200
[Guest]: You have to cater to his whims.

01:50:32.200 --> 01:50:37.960
[Guest]: And the director, whoever's paying you, has to be happy, everyone is happy, you know,

01:50:37.960 --> 01:50:40.960
[Guest]: and then it becomes like that approval by committee.

01:50:40.960 --> 01:50:44.520
[Guest]: That's the process I hate the most because everyone feels they have to give some feedback.

01:50:44.520 --> 01:50:48.280
[Guest]: Otherwise, their job is not warranted, you know, they're just sitting there like useless

01:50:48.280 --> 01:50:49.520
[Guest]: people otherwise.

01:50:49.520 --> 01:50:55.200
[Guest]: So that is not something that I'm personally fond of, in that sense, at least I want to

01:50:55.200 --> 01:51:00.040
[Guest]: be able to, you know, at least with my own music, if I put it out under like Warren Mendonca

01:51:00.040 --> 01:51:04.600
[Guest]: or Black Style Blues, at least I want something that, you know, goes out with me being happy.

01:51:04.600 --> 01:51:11.840
[Guest]: And then there's a good chance of other people being happy as well, by default.

01:51:11.840 --> 01:51:16.080
[Amit Varma]: Like you mentioned short attention spans, you know, five years back, when I started

01:51:16.080 --> 01:51:21.160
[Amit Varma]: this podcast, my impression was that attention spans are short, you got to hook them in the

01:51:21.160 --> 01:51:26.200
[Amit Varma]: first 15 seconds, don't do an episode more than 10-15 minutes, and so on and so forth.

01:51:26.200 --> 01:51:31.620
[Amit Varma]: And I realized I was spectacularly wrong, because tons of people crave deep content.

01:51:31.620 --> 01:51:34.960
[Amit Varma]: And especially in the case of podcasts, people are a captive audience when they're listening

01:51:34.960 --> 01:51:37.880
[Amit Varma]: to podcasts, they're commuting or working out or whatever.

01:51:37.880 --> 01:51:41.000
[Amit Varma]: They're listening at higher speeds, which of course doesn't happen with music, but they're

01:51:41.000 --> 01:51:42.880
[Amit Varma]: listening to podcasts at higher speeds.

01:51:42.880 --> 01:51:45.560
[Amit Varma]: And people just crave depth, nobody else gives you depth.

01:51:45.560 --> 01:51:49.040
[Amit Varma]: And like you said, there are times of the day when you have a short attention span,

01:51:49.040 --> 01:51:53.360
[Amit Varma]: and there are times where you really want to sit down and listen to that double album.

01:51:53.360 --> 01:51:54.880
[Amit Varma]: And this was something I realized.

01:51:54.880 --> 01:52:00.440
[Amit Varma]: But the question I'm coming to is this, that what I have noticed is that for content that

01:52:00.440 --> 01:52:05.560
[Amit Varma]: goes deeper, your absolute numbers may not be as high as something that is shallower

01:52:05.560 --> 01:52:08.440
[Amit Varma]: and something that is hooking you in 15 seconds and all that.

01:52:08.440 --> 01:52:13.520
[Amit Varma]: But the level of engagement is way, way, way, way higher, your audience cares so much more

01:52:13.520 --> 01:52:14.520
[Amit Varma]: about you.

01:52:14.520 --> 01:52:16.880
[Amit Varma]: It's personal, it's intimate, all of that is happening.

01:52:16.880 --> 01:52:23.400
[Amit Varma]: So the dual question to you is that both as a consumer of music, and as a creator of music,

01:52:23.400 --> 01:52:27.920
[Amit Varma]: have you felt that connect that, you know, when you're doing stuff that makes you happy,

01:52:27.920 --> 01:52:32.800
[Amit Varma]: I think you're automatically guaranteed, perhaps to not reach out to as many people as you

01:52:32.800 --> 01:52:36.400
[Amit Varma]: would, but to everyone you reach out to, you're making them happy as well.

01:52:36.400 --> 01:52:42.240
[Amit Varma]: So do you feel that deeper connect both from your listeners towards yourself, and also

01:52:42.240 --> 01:52:47.000
[Amit Varma]: from you towards the music you like that you just feel this more intimate connection towards

01:52:47.000 --> 01:52:48.000
[Amit Varma]: this person?

01:52:48.000 --> 01:52:53.600
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, for me, when I meet people who have never met before, but they tell me like,

01:52:53.600 --> 01:52:56.280
[Guest]: I really love the music you do.

01:52:56.280 --> 01:53:01.240
[Guest]: There's part of me which is like that rush song limelight, like I can't pretend a stranger

01:53:01.240 --> 01:53:04.840
[Guest]: is a long lost friend, you know, that part of me is like, there's nothing real about

01:53:04.840 --> 01:53:09.880
[Guest]: this interaction, if I have never met you before, but I have to shut off that part of

01:53:09.880 --> 01:53:14.560
[Guest]: me and say, this person is actually connecting to me as a human being, because they first

01:53:14.560 --> 01:53:16.280
[Guest]: connected to my music.

01:53:16.280 --> 01:53:21.760
[Guest]: And the whole idea of having like Blackstar Blues as a, you know, a moniker or a project

01:53:21.760 --> 01:53:24.560
[Guest]: name was just to say, okay, this is the music.

01:53:24.560 --> 01:53:26.720
[Guest]: Now you listen to the music and you leave me alone.

01:53:26.720 --> 01:53:31.400
[Guest]: You know, I'm not part of this whole relationship, your relationship is between you as a listener

01:53:31.400 --> 01:53:36.600
[Guest]: and the music, not between you and the listener and me as the person, maybe me as a musician.

01:53:36.600 --> 01:53:37.600
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:53:37.600 --> 01:53:40.960
[Guest]: So there has to be that disconnect and then you have like, social media and everything

01:53:40.960 --> 01:53:43.840
[Guest]: coming with that line gets a bit blurred.

01:53:43.840 --> 01:53:49.040
[Guest]: And then I guess also like being a dad, I've kind of become less of that, you know, it

01:53:49.040 --> 01:53:53.520
[Guest]: doesn't really get to me because like, there's a certain kind of social awkwardness I have

01:53:53.520 --> 01:53:54.520
[Guest]: in any situation.

01:53:54.520 --> 01:53:59.280
[Guest]: If I don't know someone, it's very hard for me to relate to them unless they say, like,

01:53:59.280 --> 01:54:04.920
[Guest]: if they start talking about the Beatles automatically, like they become my friends.

01:54:04.920 --> 01:54:09.400
[Guest]: I mean, if I know that they know what they're talking about, that's something I like, even

01:54:09.400 --> 01:54:12.720
[Guest]: people actually interested in something, they can talk about anything as long as they're

01:54:12.720 --> 01:54:16.800
[Guest]: actually interested in it and they have a proper knowledge of it.

01:54:16.800 --> 01:54:19.920
[Guest]: And there are people who just like to fill the air with conversation with, you know,

01:54:19.920 --> 01:54:23.560
[Guest]: meaningless conversation, I can't deal with that.

01:54:23.560 --> 01:54:27.520
[Guest]: So sometimes at social gatherings, like, you know, I have to kind of hide me and my wife

01:54:27.520 --> 01:54:30.620
[Guest]: and that sort of thing.

01:54:30.620 --> 01:54:34.920
[Guest]: So even in these situations, like after gig, I make it a point to stay back and talk to

01:54:34.920 --> 01:54:38.200
[Guest]: everyone who wants to talk to me, you know, so if they feel like they feel like connected

01:54:38.200 --> 01:54:43.560
[Guest]: to me as a person, who am I to say that's not real, you know, in that sense.

01:54:43.560 --> 01:54:47.480
[Guest]: So it's progressively become easier over the years for me to do that.

01:54:47.480 --> 01:54:51.000
[Guest]: Like, initially, I remember that gig where Chuck first came at Miti Bai College, people

01:54:51.000 --> 01:54:55.400
[Guest]: taking photographs, and he wanted to take photographs of me, I was like, no, I don't feel comfortable

01:54:55.400 --> 01:55:00.520
[Guest]: doing this, please let me just play on stage and go home, that's what I want to do.

01:55:00.520 --> 01:55:07.720
[Unknown]: And to quote your bassist from that gig, you tried to introduce the band, you did a pretty

01:55:07.720 --> 01:55:09.040
[Unknown]: bad job of it.

01:55:09.040 --> 01:55:13.160
[Unknown]: And Bobby grabbed the mic and said, as you can all see, Warren is very new at this mic

01:55:13.160 --> 01:55:14.280
[Unknown]: business.

01:55:14.280 --> 01:55:17.960
[Unknown]: What he means is can all of you come forward, I still have a video of that.

01:55:17.960 --> 01:55:18.960
[Unknown]: That was pretty hilarious.

01:55:18.960 --> 01:55:24.120
[Unknown]: But yeah, your banter skills have improved dramatically since then.

01:55:24.120 --> 01:55:28.160
[Guest]: Someone just asked me once, what was the biggest difference between Blacksand Blues and Zeo?

01:55:28.160 --> 01:55:30.800
[Guest]: I said, well, in Zeo, I didn't have a mic in front of me.

01:55:30.800 --> 01:55:32.560
[Guest]: That was amazing.

01:55:32.560 --> 01:55:35.920
[Guest]: The moment I hear my voice on the monitors, I instantly feel awkward.

01:55:35.920 --> 01:55:39.320
[Guest]: And then I just start mumbling and then it becomes worse because I'm just like talking

01:55:39.320 --> 01:55:40.320
[Guest]: like that.

01:55:40.320 --> 01:55:42.040
[Guest]: No one can understand what I'm saying.

01:55:42.040 --> 01:55:46.040
[Guest]: I remember one gig, they delayed our soundcheck severely.

01:55:46.040 --> 01:55:49.080
[Guest]: So I was super pissed off because it was early in the morning, I was like, listen, don't

01:55:49.080 --> 01:55:51.000
[Guest]: call a band for like a seven o'clock soundcheck.

01:55:51.000 --> 01:55:55.200
[Guest]: If you can't meet that requirement, just call them and say, come later, you know.

01:55:55.200 --> 01:55:56.720
[Guest]: But that wasn't the case.

01:55:56.720 --> 01:55:59.000
[Guest]: I was damn pissed off by the time we got on stage.

01:55:59.000 --> 01:56:01.800
[Guest]: And apparently that was the best I've ever been behind the mic.

01:56:01.800 --> 01:56:04.560
[Guest]: We played like a smashing set because everyone was pissed off.

01:56:04.560 --> 01:56:10.200
[Guest]: Apparently, I was very loud and audible because our front of house engineer told me, you don't

01:56:10.200 --> 01:56:11.760
[Guest]: have to keep pushing up my fader.

01:56:11.760 --> 01:56:17.600
[Guest]: In fact, I had to pull it down, he was shouting on the mic.

01:56:17.600 --> 01:56:22.200
[Amit Varma]: So my question for you, Chuck, was this, that the same thing what I asked him, you were

01:56:22.200 --> 01:56:27.000
[Amit Varma]: actually one of the early big fans of Zero and Warren and so on and so forth.

01:56:27.000 --> 01:56:31.560
[Amit Varma]: So what what connected you feel like, like, do you feel there's something to that?

01:56:31.560 --> 01:56:37.760
[Amit Varma]: Do you feel, for example, that a fan of someone like Warren or a similar musician or whatever,

01:56:37.760 --> 01:56:42.320
[Amit Varma]: will have a deeper engagement than say a fan of somebody more popular?

01:56:42.320 --> 01:56:46.840
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to be disrespectful to someone by taking names, but say a Justin Bieber,

01:56:46.840 --> 01:56:50.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, do you feel that the connect would be, you know, that connect would be broader

01:56:50.640 --> 01:56:52.240
[Amit Varma]: but shallower?

01:56:52.240 --> 01:56:53.240
[Unknown]: Yeah, 100%.

01:56:53.240 --> 01:56:56.280
[Unknown]: I think it will definitely be broader and shallower.

01:56:56.280 --> 01:56:57.280
[Unknown]: I'll answer.

01:56:57.280 --> 01:56:58.760
[Unknown]: I mean, there were multiple questions there, right?

01:56:58.760 --> 01:57:03.080
[Unknown]: So I'll answer what drew me to Warren's music for the first time, and I won't embarrass

01:57:03.080 --> 01:57:04.080
[Unknown]: you too much.

01:57:04.080 --> 01:57:06.840
[Unknown]: I think I've done that enough through all the articles and stuff that I wrote.

01:57:06.840 --> 01:57:12.160
[Unknown]: I think I was just blown away by the fact that an Indian musician could make guitar

01:57:12.160 --> 01:57:16.760
[Unknown]: solos like this, honestly, and, and, and, of course, the band themselves, the songs

01:57:16.760 --> 01:57:19.800
[Unknown]: by themselves were pretty great.

01:57:19.800 --> 01:57:22.040
[Unknown]: So I was just blown away by that.

01:57:22.040 --> 01:57:26.360
[Unknown]: And from there, I was, I actually, I wasn't an early fan of Zero, I would actually call

01:57:26.360 --> 01:57:29.880
[Unknown]: myself one of the later fans of Zero and an early fan of Blackstar Blues, because I got

01:57:29.880 --> 01:57:33.440
[Unknown]: in at around that time, I actually discovered Zero when Warren was out of the band and was

01:57:33.440 --> 01:57:35.080
[Unknown]: in Auckland at that time.

01:57:35.080 --> 01:57:39.040
[Unknown]: So I was right bang in the middle, and that transition happened, and that blew me away

01:57:39.040 --> 01:57:41.400
[Unknown]: that you can do this and this at the same time.

01:57:41.400 --> 01:57:43.140
[Unknown]: And I think that's what really drew me in.

01:57:43.140 --> 01:57:48.440
[Unknown]: And arguably, if you had continued playing the way you did, as Zero, maybe I wouldn't

01:57:48.440 --> 01:57:52.360
[Unknown]: have been as much of a fan because I think that transition and the fact that you balance

01:57:52.360 --> 01:57:55.360
[Unknown]: both so effortlessly, was important to me.

01:57:55.360 --> 01:57:56.360
[Unknown]: To the second question.

01:57:56.360 --> 01:57:57.520
[Unknown]: Yes, there's no doubt about it.

01:57:57.520 --> 01:58:03.280
[Unknown]: I think there is something about fewer fans, but deeper engagement, again, something that

01:58:03.280 --> 01:58:07.160
[Unknown]: we discussed so much on when I came on when I was talking about the Australian band Neo

01:58:07.160 --> 01:58:13.840
[Unknown]: Blizzard is for example, I think it is there, I think, I think if there is a deeper connect,

01:58:13.840 --> 01:58:17.600
[Unknown]: not only will they be evangelists for the music more, but and Warren, you can correct

01:58:17.600 --> 01:58:21.360
[Unknown]: me if I'm completely off the mark on this, but also be willing to support you more for

01:58:21.360 --> 01:58:26.160
[Unknown]: this either by spreading the music, buying the music as opposed to streaming on Spotify,

01:58:26.160 --> 01:58:27.160
[Unknown]: etc.

01:58:27.160 --> 01:58:29.100
[Unknown]: That's my feeling as a fan.

01:58:29.100 --> 01:58:32.920
[Unknown]: And I've done that for artists that I am a supporter of.

01:58:32.920 --> 01:58:35.280
[Unknown]: So yeah, that's my perspective on that.

01:58:35.280 --> 01:58:38.760
[Guest]: Yeah, the guys who like it really like it.

01:58:38.760 --> 01:58:41.480
[Unknown]: Yeah, well, I'll tell you that for sure.

01:58:41.480 --> 01:58:44.640
[Guest]: Because there's been guys who have been listening from the first album.

01:58:44.640 --> 01:58:50.520
[Guest]: I remember there's one guy at the time where I put it on my website for free.

01:58:50.520 --> 01:58:54.560
[Guest]: And I said, this is my PayPal account, you know, if you feel like donating some money

01:58:54.560 --> 01:58:58.440
[Guest]: so I can buy some better recording gear, then you know, feel free.

01:58:58.440 --> 01:59:04.320
[Guest]: So one guy donated $200 at the time, which was like, wow, you know, so that guy wrote

01:59:04.320 --> 01:59:10.080
[Guest]: back to me, I said, dude, thank you so much, like, this is really come at a good time.

01:59:10.080 --> 01:59:13.860
[Guest]: You get the album advanced release for free for life.

01:59:13.860 --> 01:59:19.760
[Guest]: So I make it a point now before every release, I send a copy.

01:59:19.760 --> 01:59:23.960
[Guest]: So I never really forgot that, you know, gesture of his.

01:59:23.960 --> 01:59:28.640
[Guest]: But there have been people who have been there from the first album, like, you know, Chuck,

01:59:28.640 --> 01:59:32.060
[Guest]: who still are, you know, listeners and support the music.

01:59:32.060 --> 01:59:34.000
[Guest]: So I'm really grateful for that.

01:59:34.000 --> 01:59:37.320
[Guest]: I mean, I cannot like, you know, be more thankful.

01:59:37.320 --> 01:59:45.040
[Guest]: But the whole thing is like, then when you have people who don't see your music as a

01:59:45.040 --> 01:59:50.720
[Guest]: disposable commodity, yeah, then you kind of feel that interaction is a little bit more

01:59:50.720 --> 01:59:54.400
[Guest]: real, you know, the way someone is just listening to Black Star Cruise, because their friends

01:59:54.400 --> 01:59:57.720
[Guest]: said they're a cool band, and tomorrow they've forgotten about it.

01:59:57.720 --> 02:00:02.600
[Guest]: I mean, these are not the people that tend to, you know, engage long term with your brand

02:00:02.600 --> 02:00:04.480
[Guest]: or your music or whatever.

02:00:04.480 --> 02:00:08.480
[Guest]: So I'm really grateful for the people who really like it enough, like when I put out

02:00:08.480 --> 02:00:14.960
[Guest]: this most recent album, I put it on sale for Bandcamp first, and then it went on to streaming

02:00:14.960 --> 02:00:16.780
[Guest]: two weeks later.

02:00:16.780 --> 02:00:20.240
[Guest]: And it pretty much covered the entire recording cost of the album.

02:00:20.240 --> 02:00:25.400
[Guest]: I was like, wow, you know, really, I wasn't expecting that at all.

02:00:25.400 --> 02:00:29.760
[Guest]: But it kind of made me feel like nice and warm about the whole thing that there are

02:00:29.760 --> 02:00:33.520
[Guest]: people who actually care about your music, they know they're going to get it for free

02:00:33.520 --> 02:00:40.080
[Guest]: on your streaming services on YouTube or whatever, they'll still, you know, take the effort to,

02:00:40.080 --> 02:00:46.400
[Guest]: you know, support you and put their money where their love for the music is.

02:00:46.400 --> 02:00:50.880
[Amit Varma]: So I want to talk about the commercial aspect of it, because, you know, one of the areas

02:00:50.880 --> 02:00:55.760
[Amit Varma]: like you talk about the high engagement and where that directly leads is that today creators

02:00:55.760 --> 02:01:00.800
[Amit Varma]: are able to connect directly with whoever's reading them or listening to them or whatever,

02:01:00.800 --> 02:01:04.160
[Amit Varma]: and monetize some of that capture some of that value, because anyone who listens to

02:01:04.160 --> 02:01:07.720
[Amit Varma]: your music is in a sense paying for it, because time is money.

02:01:07.720 --> 02:01:12.240
[Amit Varma]: You spend one hour listening to blackstrap blues, you know, you're spending it and today

02:01:12.240 --> 02:01:17.400
[Amit Varma]: we are in that unique age where you don't have to go through intermediaries like platforms

02:01:17.400 --> 02:01:20.200
[Amit Varma]: and advertising and so on, you can capture some of it.

02:01:20.200 --> 02:01:25.760
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I've had this experience when I opened up support for my podcast as well,

02:01:25.760 --> 02:01:30.240
[Amit Varma]: and was very touched by a response I didn't expect, which has been enough to kind of keep

02:01:30.240 --> 02:01:32.960
[Amit Varma]: me independent all this while and doing what I do.

02:01:32.960 --> 02:01:36.680
[Amit Varma]: You know, when things started going well for you, blackstrap blues happened, all that happened,

02:01:36.680 --> 02:01:42.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, in a musical sense, commercially, there was so much flux, that the revenue models

02:01:42.400 --> 02:01:47.720
[Amit Varma]: of the music industry kind of were going through this crazy flux, all the labels come, they

02:01:47.720 --> 02:01:51.960
[Amit Varma]: sue Napster and all that, they get that shut down, then iTunes comes and there's nothing

02:01:51.960 --> 02:01:56.360
[Amit Varma]: they can do because Apple has more lawyers and so on, as Ted Joyer says, and everything

02:01:56.360 --> 02:01:57.560
[Amit Varma]: kind of goes to hell.

02:01:57.560 --> 02:02:00.720
[Amit Varma]: And you do this very interesting thing where you say that, look, I just want my music to

02:02:00.720 --> 02:02:04.360
[Amit Varma]: reach people, I want people to listen to it, you put it up for free, and your first two

02:02:04.360 --> 02:02:07.120
[Amit Varma]: albums are out there, they're up for free.

02:02:07.120 --> 02:02:13.480
[Amit Varma]: How have things evolved since then, because the downside of all of this, it seems to me,

02:02:13.480 --> 02:02:19.720
[Amit Varma]: is that creators are also forced to simultaneously be entrepreneurs, right?

02:02:19.720 --> 02:02:23.680
[Amit Varma]: Someone may be a talented musician, but they may not have a head for business or a head

02:02:23.680 --> 02:02:29.520
[Amit Varma]: for how to use social media, and so on and so forth, and be able to do the rest of that.

02:02:29.520 --> 02:02:35.600
[Amit Varma]: So how have you therefore handled all of that in terms of sure, you make stuff for yourself,

02:02:35.600 --> 02:02:40.000
[Amit Varma]: and that makes you happy, but you also have deeply committed fans and so on and so forth.

02:02:40.000 --> 02:02:41.240
[Amit Varma]: How has it evolved so far?

02:02:41.240 --> 02:02:43.360
[Amit Varma]: Where do you see it going from here?

02:02:43.360 --> 02:02:48.320
[Amit Varma]: And do you think for musicians in general, how should musicians in general approach this

02:02:48.320 --> 02:02:49.840
[Amit Varma]: new world that we are in?

02:02:49.840 --> 02:02:53.760
[Amit Varma]: Like 30 years ago, the model would have been that maybe you tour a little bit, build a

02:02:53.760 --> 02:02:59.840
[Amit Varma]: bit of local following, attract a record label, label comes out, and, you know, either you're

02:02:59.840 --> 02:03:03.840
[Amit Varma]: lucky enough to make it big, or, you know, you're back to whatever, being a journeyman

02:03:03.840 --> 02:03:04.840
[Amit Varma]: band.

02:03:04.840 --> 02:03:05.840
[Amit Varma]: Today, that's really kind of different.

02:03:05.840 --> 02:03:10.400
[Amit Varma]: So take me through a little bit of this landscape, and what are your thoughts on it and so on?

02:03:10.400 --> 02:03:16.760
[Guest]: Well, the cost of recording has been coming down significantly due to the advance of technology.

02:03:16.760 --> 02:03:18.840
[Guest]: So that's the first thing we need to look at.

02:03:18.840 --> 02:03:22.240
[Guest]: So by the time I did the first Blackstrap Blues album, my recording costs were literally

02:03:22.240 --> 02:03:26.680
[Guest]: nil because I'd already owned all the equipment I needed to make that album.

02:03:26.680 --> 02:03:32.600
[Guest]: Now, obviously, now, as an artist, you sometimes tend to grow in the scope of, you know, what

02:03:32.600 --> 02:03:36.800
[Guest]: you're trying to achieve and what you're trying to capture for posterity.

02:03:36.800 --> 02:03:40.440
[Guest]: So then, say, tomorrow, you decide you've written a piece of music that requires an

02:03:40.440 --> 02:03:41.440
[Guest]: orchestra.

02:03:41.440 --> 02:03:43.960
[Guest]: Now, that is not something I can record in my bedroom.

02:03:43.960 --> 02:03:47.920
[Guest]: I can program it, you know, to a certain extent, but it's not going to sound like an orchestra.

02:03:47.920 --> 02:03:48.920
[Guest]: Now, you have to decide.

02:03:48.920 --> 02:03:52.760
[Guest]: Now, if I have to have that orchestra, then the money is going to come from somewhere.

02:03:52.760 --> 02:03:56.000
[Guest]: So either I put it in myself, or I have to apply for funding.

02:03:56.000 --> 02:03:58.240
[Guest]: At least here, the New Zealand government is awesome about that.

02:03:58.240 --> 02:04:00.280
[Guest]: They have funding avenues that you can apply for.

02:04:00.280 --> 02:04:05.520
[Guest]: I mean, the competition is severe, but you can if your music is deemed good enough and,

02:04:05.520 --> 02:04:08.040
[Guest]: you know, commercially viable enough.

02:04:08.040 --> 02:04:14.840
[Guest]: So there's some gatekeeper in that sense, you know, the moment your personal investment

02:04:14.840 --> 02:04:17.380
[Guest]: is exceeded by the cost.

02:04:17.380 --> 02:04:23.760
[Guest]: So for me, personally, as long as I was able to produce the album to the best of my financial

02:04:23.760 --> 02:04:26.960
[Guest]: and artistic ability, I was happy with it.

02:04:26.960 --> 02:04:31.440
[Guest]: It was cool, you know, because the first album, no recording cost, second, I was able to use

02:04:31.440 --> 02:04:32.680
[Guest]: studio downtime.

02:04:32.680 --> 02:04:34.840
[Guest]: So you know, got away with that.

02:04:34.840 --> 02:04:41.560
[Guest]: Third album, we recovered our investment on studio time from iTunes sales.

02:04:41.560 --> 02:04:46.960
[Guest]: Now, that time, you could actually sell music on iTunes and OK, listen, and all these sites

02:04:46.960 --> 02:04:50.320
[Guest]: where people actually pay 100 rupees or whatever.

02:04:50.320 --> 02:04:56.160
[Guest]: And if say, you know, 1000 people bought your album at 100 rupees, that's what like one

02:04:56.160 --> 02:05:01.520
[Guest]: lakh, you know, which at that time was kind of what the recording cost was.

02:05:01.520 --> 02:05:03.320
[Guest]: So we were pretty cool there.

02:05:03.320 --> 02:05:09.080
[Guest]: We were still making most of our music as a band playing live.

02:05:09.080 --> 02:05:13.120
[Guest]: But even that wasn't enough to, you know, sustain a life in Bombay.

02:05:13.120 --> 02:05:17.720
[Guest]: I had to play with Vishal Shekhar and Amit Srivedi and ARMR and stuff that I enjoyed

02:05:17.720 --> 02:05:22.280
[Guest]: doing that totally because that was a totally different aspect of being a musician, you

02:05:22.280 --> 02:05:23.280
[Guest]: know.

02:05:23.280 --> 02:05:28.440
[Guest]: But that is what kind of kept things alive in terms of having a lifestyle and being able

02:05:28.440 --> 02:05:29.440
[Guest]: to afford that.

02:05:29.440 --> 02:05:34.600
[Guest]: Now, the moment that's gone with the whole pandemic thing and everything and I've moved

02:05:34.600 --> 02:05:40.200
[Guest]: back here, it becomes a little bit more of a, you know, a juggle and you kind of have

02:05:40.200 --> 02:05:45.360
[Guest]: a more short term budget in terms of making sure your mortgage payments are met and so

02:05:45.360 --> 02:05:46.560
[Guest]: on and so forth.

02:05:46.560 --> 02:05:51.520
[Guest]: So as long as you're above that, I can continue to do what I do.

02:05:51.520 --> 02:05:55.880
[Guest]: Now, there's also a lot of commercial music that I've been involved in, which is kind

02:05:55.880 --> 02:05:57.840
[Guest]: of what still, you know, pays the bills.

02:05:57.840 --> 02:06:01.720
[Guest]: And then I mix stuff for other people, I do guitar sessions and stuff like that.

02:06:01.720 --> 02:06:09.000
[Guest]: So as long as, you know, those two sides are juggled, it's like our heads above the water.

02:06:09.000 --> 02:06:11.840
[Guest]: The moment that doesn't happen, anything could change, you know, I mean, the world we live

02:06:11.840 --> 02:06:15.360
[Guest]: in right now is just like every day, something new is happening.

02:06:15.360 --> 02:06:19.560
[Guest]: And like the life that we knew six months back is gone.

02:06:19.560 --> 02:06:22.720
[Guest]: Something else, you got to do this, and then it becomes the norm.

02:06:22.720 --> 02:06:28.880
[Guest]: So again, till I guess this COVID thing stabilizes a bit, and then we actually have a stable

02:06:28.880 --> 02:06:29.880
[Guest]: income stream.

02:06:29.880 --> 02:06:35.640
[Guest]: We kind of have to, you know, for me, teaching has really helped because during the moment

02:06:35.640 --> 02:06:39.840
[Guest]: the gig stopped, I was like, look, I've got like three or four months before I've got

02:06:39.840 --> 02:06:41.920
[Guest]: to move to New Zealand.

02:06:41.920 --> 02:06:44.480
[Guest]: So you know, I might as well find something to do with time.

02:06:44.480 --> 02:06:46.840
[Guest]: So I started teaching on Zoom.

02:06:46.840 --> 02:06:51.120
[Guest]: And like that kind of paid for the whole move, you know, the whole moving costs and everything

02:06:51.120 --> 02:06:53.340
[Guest]: I met with, but just teaching.

02:06:53.340 --> 02:06:55.960
[Guest]: So that again, fluctuates up and down.

02:06:55.960 --> 02:06:59.680
[Guest]: I think every time there's a lockdown, the amount of students goes up and everything

02:06:59.680 --> 02:07:04.040
[Guest]: things open up as people find other things to do.

02:07:04.040 --> 02:07:08.200
[Guest]: I mean, I still have a few students that, you know, stuck around for like, since like

02:07:08.200 --> 02:07:09.640
[Guest]: I started teaching.

02:07:09.640 --> 02:07:15.160
[Guest]: So you know, it's a bit of a very up in the air kind of thing.

02:07:15.160 --> 02:07:21.640
[Guest]: And you're trying to make sense of, you know, random events and sequences of things happening.

02:07:21.640 --> 02:07:28.880
[Guest]: And all you have to do is kind of manage to keep the bike balanced.

02:07:28.880 --> 02:07:29.880
[Guest]: Anything could happen.

02:07:29.880 --> 02:07:32.480
[Guest]: One, you could hit a stone, but if you hit a stone, then you kind of, you know, regain

02:07:32.480 --> 02:07:33.480
[Guest]: your balance.

02:07:33.480 --> 02:07:37.720
[Guest]: But, you know, as long as you keep the bike, you know, on two wheels and don't fall down,

02:07:37.720 --> 02:07:38.720
[Guest]: it's all good.

02:07:38.720 --> 02:07:41.600
[Guest]: So when that happens, then you cross that bridge when you come to it.

02:07:41.600 --> 02:07:46.280
[Guest]: So it's very hard actually to make long term plans at this point, you have to be flexible

02:07:46.280 --> 02:07:51.120
[Guest]: enough to kind of just adapt to, you know, what every day brings.

02:07:51.120 --> 02:07:54.600
[Guest]: That's one thing I guess the pandemic has taught me like, you know, just every day is

02:07:54.600 --> 02:07:55.600
[Guest]: a blessing.

02:07:55.600 --> 02:07:59.920
[Guest]: So you don't know if you're going to be around tomorrow, let's do the best we can.

02:07:59.920 --> 02:08:06.000
[Guest]: And in terms of like the actual stuff that you make as an artist, that's going to survive

02:08:06.000 --> 02:08:08.920
[Guest]: long after you've bounced from this planet.

02:08:08.920 --> 02:08:14.180
[Guest]: So you know, that's something at least you put all of your current available energies

02:08:14.180 --> 02:08:16.480
[Guest]: into to at least kind of leave something.

02:08:16.480 --> 02:08:17.640
[Guest]: And now at least I have a daughter.

02:08:17.640 --> 02:08:22.000
[Guest]: So that's something else that will survive me, you know.

02:08:22.000 --> 02:08:26.920
[Guest]: But it's like, you just do the best you can every day man, it's like so hard to, you know,

02:08:26.920 --> 02:08:30.560
[Guest]: I'm the last person that will actually give you, you know, concrete advice and say, this

02:08:30.560 --> 02:08:32.160
[Guest]: is what you should be doing.

02:08:32.160 --> 02:08:35.680
[Guest]: And this is, you know, invest your money, you don't invest, I don't know all that sort

02:08:35.680 --> 02:08:36.680
[Guest]: of thing.

02:08:36.680 --> 02:08:42.440
[Guest]: You know, it's like, as long as you get to play guitar tomorrow, that's a good thing.

02:08:42.440 --> 02:08:48.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about teaching because one of the you know, when I started my writing

02:08:48.000 --> 02:08:53.880
[Amit Varma]: course, and I started teaching, I realized that I actually started learning more and

02:08:53.880 --> 02:08:57.260
[Amit Varma]: looking deeper into a subject I thought I knew pretty well, right?

02:08:57.260 --> 02:09:00.720
[Amit Varma]: So how has teaching changed your appreciation of music?

02:09:00.720 --> 02:09:03.920
[Amit Varma]: And has it actually changed you as a musician and just the way you think of the work you

02:09:03.920 --> 02:09:04.920
[Amit Varma]: do?

02:09:04.920 --> 02:09:10.760
[Guest]: Yeah, I've become a better communicator of ideas, I'm able to edit my, you know, thought

02:09:10.760 --> 02:09:12.160
[Guest]: process really quickly.

02:09:12.160 --> 02:09:16.020
[Guest]: And you know, because sometimes I can be thinking of five things at once, but then that person

02:09:16.020 --> 02:09:18.640
[Guest]: doesn't have the time to listen to all five.

02:09:18.640 --> 02:09:23.920
[Guest]: So you have to pick the best thing that you're thinking of, and communicate that.

02:09:23.920 --> 02:09:28.680
[Guest]: Yeah, I've had to kind of actually study what I do, because sometimes they asked me to like,

02:09:28.680 --> 02:09:29.680
[Guest]: how did you play that?

02:09:29.680 --> 02:09:33.280
[Guest]: And I can't say I closed my eyes and it came out, you know, which is actually the truth.

02:09:33.280 --> 02:09:37.520
[Guest]: But you have to kind of go back and deconstruct the process, even though that was something

02:09:37.520 --> 02:09:40.360
[Guest]: you were never thinking about at the time.

02:09:40.360 --> 02:09:44.520
[Guest]: So you kind of have to go back and trace your steps and say, okay, what was I thinking of

02:09:44.520 --> 02:09:48.560
[Guest]: when I when I played that, you know, kind of trying to give them an idea of

02:09:48.560 --> 02:09:53.320
[Guest]: my headspace, because that's very important to whatever it is I play.

02:09:53.320 --> 02:09:56.680
[Guest]: There's no chance I would have played the same thing if I was feeling it, you know,

02:09:56.680 --> 02:09:57.680
[Guest]: different.

02:09:57.680 --> 02:10:04.520
[Guest]: And then the whole idea of communicating how to channel emotion and vibe into what you're

02:10:04.520 --> 02:10:06.360
[Guest]: playing becomes tough.

02:10:06.360 --> 02:10:09.920
[Guest]: Then you start having to tell them more about the technicalities, like, okay, this is not

02:10:09.920 --> 02:10:13.120
[Guest]: in tune, and that is not in time, and that sort of thing.

02:10:13.120 --> 02:10:21.080
[Guest]: So, you know, a lot of people, I think, also tend to disregard simplicity, when my thing

02:10:21.080 --> 02:10:24.960
[Guest]: is like, look, it's the hardest thing to actually play simple things well, because there's nothing

02:10:24.960 --> 02:10:29.520
[Guest]: to hide behind, you know, you got to have to have full conviction or whatever it is

02:10:29.520 --> 02:10:34.460
[Guest]: you're playing, if you're playing like three notes that span this much of time.

02:10:34.460 --> 02:10:39.000
[Guest]: So you have to, you know, be able to communicate that to someone in that sense, like saying,

02:10:39.000 --> 02:10:45.360
[Guest]: you know, take it easy, we'll do it one step at a time, because they always want to, like,

02:10:45.360 --> 02:10:50.120
[Guest]: you know, learn the complicated stuff at first, and I've said, I never even, I used to enjoy

02:10:50.120 --> 02:10:54.120
[Guest]: listening to complicated music, but I never thought that I would actually play it.

02:10:54.120 --> 02:10:57.680
[Guest]: Now is the time I go back and learn those solos, which I always admired, you know, like

02:10:57.680 --> 02:10:59.160
[Guest]: Steely Dan and stuff like that.

02:10:59.160 --> 02:11:04.480
[Guest]: Now is the time I'm able to do that, when I can actually have the faculty to take it

02:11:04.480 --> 02:11:07.440
[Guest]: apart and then learn how to play it.

02:11:07.440 --> 02:11:12.600
[Guest]: So I never set my sights too high in that sense, I set my sights on low hanging fruit

02:11:12.600 --> 02:11:15.800
[Guest]: and learned how to, you know, capture it really well.

02:11:15.800 --> 02:11:20.280
[Guest]: Once I was able to do that well, then I was able to go to the next stage and start, you

02:11:20.280 --> 02:11:22.460
[Guest]: know, getting all that stuff.

02:11:22.460 --> 02:11:28.920
[Guest]: So like, I have to tell them, like, look, it's fine, just do simple stuff well, we'll

02:11:28.920 --> 02:11:32.240
[Guest]: deal with that, you know, later.

02:11:32.240 --> 02:11:38.680
[Guest]: It kind of reinforces your own taste as well, you know, because it's also like giving someone

02:11:38.680 --> 02:11:43.480
[Guest]: the reassurance that you'll get there sometime, just put in the time.

02:11:43.480 --> 02:11:48.160
[Guest]: Very few people actually have the time that is required to get to the level they have

02:11:48.160 --> 02:11:49.440
[Guest]: in mind.

02:11:49.440 --> 02:11:54.600
[Guest]: So I was like, let's just aim at getting better.

02:11:54.600 --> 02:11:58.680
[Guest]: And then because you're doing that, you notice like certain things in my own playing, which

02:11:58.680 --> 02:12:04.080
[Guest]: I would find to be like weaknesses, I was never able to use this finger that well.

02:12:04.080 --> 02:12:07.840
[Guest]: But then you can't tell someone that, look, you have to use that finger, and then not

02:12:07.840 --> 02:12:09.160
[Guest]: be able to do it yourself.

02:12:09.160 --> 02:12:12.120
[Guest]: So first you have to learn how to do that.

02:12:12.120 --> 02:12:15.240
[Guest]: And someone's like, how do I alternate pick this and I can't say like, look, dude, I can't

02:12:15.240 --> 02:12:16.240
[Guest]: play that.

02:12:16.240 --> 02:12:20.880
[Guest]: So I show them how to play it slowly and say like, well, now you have to just sit and ramp

02:12:20.880 --> 02:12:21.880
[Guest]: up the speed.

02:12:21.880 --> 02:12:24.680
[Guest]: And if I do that, I'm going to get better because sometimes I can find like, you know,

02:12:24.680 --> 02:12:29.640
[Guest]: the certain exercises I give the student, I practice it during the week.

02:12:29.640 --> 02:12:34.200
[Guest]: So when we meet again, we're both like, okay, we've both practiced, okay, now let's see

02:12:34.200 --> 02:12:35.200
[Guest]: where we are at.

02:12:35.200 --> 02:12:41.760
[Unknown]: Well, that's, that's remarkable, like, almost like musical first principles in some way

02:12:41.760 --> 02:12:43.800
[Unknown]: what you're talking about.

02:12:43.800 --> 02:12:47.920
[Unknown]: Just going back to the headspace, it's not the complex stuff, it's not the scales, it's

02:12:47.920 --> 02:12:52.440
[Unknown]: not the theory, but it's more about the vibe, the understanding.

02:12:52.440 --> 02:12:56.400
[Unknown]: Yeah, musical first principles, like I said, it's kind of feels that way.

02:12:56.400 --> 02:12:59.640
[Unknown]: Sorry, that was just a visceral reaction to what you just said.

02:12:59.640 --> 02:13:03.760
[Guest]: There was one guy I remember, like, he suddenly became better when I when I told him only

02:13:03.760 --> 02:13:04.760
[Guest]: play when you're exhaling.

02:13:04.760 --> 02:13:09.080
[Guest]: Don't play when you inhale, because he was playing a lot.

02:13:09.080 --> 02:13:10.240
[Guest]: He was trying to do too much.

02:13:10.240 --> 02:13:15.680
[Guest]: And I said, Okay, now look, when you breathe, you know, there's an inhale process, you spend

02:13:15.680 --> 02:13:16.680
[Guest]: for do that.

02:13:16.680 --> 02:13:25.440
[Guest]: So suddenly felt like, okay, there's more like, you know, the intent in what he was

02:13:25.440 --> 02:13:26.440
[Guest]: playing.

02:13:26.440 --> 02:13:27.440
[Guest]: The intent is the hardest thing.

02:13:27.440 --> 02:13:29.800
[Guest]: I mean, you can't fake it, you know.

02:13:29.800 --> 02:13:33.840
[Guest]: And if you keep on thinking of yourself as like, I'm never going to be good, I'm never

02:13:33.840 --> 02:13:34.840
[Guest]: going to be good.

02:13:34.840 --> 02:13:39.240
[Guest]: Sometimes it can kind of cripple you and you'll never get there unless your part of your brain

02:13:39.240 --> 02:13:40.920
[Guest]: says, no, I can do this.

02:13:40.920 --> 02:13:44.480
[Guest]: Because like, there are things that I'll be able to play if I'm not thinking about it.

02:13:44.480 --> 02:13:48.280
[Guest]: But when I think about it, there's like that critical thing that comes in, like, say, you're

02:13:48.280 --> 02:13:51.560
[Guest]: fucking it up, you're fucking it up, you're fucking it up.

02:13:51.560 --> 02:13:53.640
[Guest]: It automatically makes things go to shit.

02:13:53.640 --> 02:13:58.360
[Guest]: So you have to find a way of telling that guy, shut up, be quiet, go sit in the other

02:13:58.360 --> 02:13:59.360
[Guest]: room for two minutes.

02:13:59.360 --> 02:14:00.360
[Guest]: Let me just do this.

02:14:00.360 --> 02:14:03.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, in cricket, there's a term called the yips in sports.

02:14:03.360 --> 02:14:07.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's a term called the yips where people just freeze at something that they've

02:14:07.000 --> 02:14:08.000
[Amit Varma]: done so well before.

02:14:08.000 --> 02:14:14.320
[Amit Varma]: I think a famous example is Jana Nowotna was playing a match in the mid 1990s, sometimes

02:14:14.320 --> 02:14:18.440
[Amit Varma]: and she was 5-0 up in the last set and she just lost, she just froze, she couldn't do

02:14:18.440 --> 02:14:19.440
[Amit Varma]: it.

02:14:19.440 --> 02:14:23.080
[Amit Varma]: And the theory behind that, there's a famous Malcolm Gladwell essay on this also, the theory

02:14:23.080 --> 02:14:27.320
[Amit Varma]: behind that is that there's stuff that we've just internalized, it's reflexive to us, we

02:14:27.320 --> 02:14:28.440
[Amit Varma]: do it easily.

02:14:28.440 --> 02:14:31.960
[Amit Varma]: But if you start thinking consciously about it, you're just not able to do it because

02:14:31.960 --> 02:14:35.080
[Amit Varma]: that's a different part of the brain and it becomes a problem.

02:14:35.080 --> 02:14:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And I want to therefore ask you about processes, right?

02:14:40.000 --> 02:14:44.200
[Amit Varma]: Just in terms of processes, whether it's processes in terms of practicing, you're playing and

02:14:44.200 --> 02:14:49.000
[Amit Varma]: learning, whether it's processes in terms of songwriting, what are your processes like?

02:14:49.000 --> 02:14:53.400
[Amit Varma]: Are there sort of hacks that have worked for you in terms of, you know, getting into flow,

02:14:53.400 --> 02:14:58.560
[Amit Varma]: as they say, where the song just plays itself and like you mentioned, sometimes your student

02:14:58.560 --> 02:15:00.680
[Amit Varma]: will ask you about how did you play that?

02:15:00.680 --> 02:15:03.160
[Amit Varma]: And at the time you played it, you weren't thinking, right?

02:15:03.160 --> 02:15:07.360
[Amit Varma]: So is it easy to get into that kind of state where you're just in the groove and things

02:15:07.360 --> 02:15:08.360
[Amit Varma]: are happening?

02:15:08.360 --> 02:15:12.040
[Amit Varma]: Do you have routines, processes, ways to work towards it?

02:15:12.040 --> 02:15:17.320
[Amit Varma]: Like one of the things that you know, is common advice for writers to give is that you cannot

02:15:17.320 --> 02:15:18.520
[Amit Varma]: wait for inspiration.

02:15:18.520 --> 02:15:22.200
[Amit Varma]: It's all about, you know, getting your ass down on the chair and just working at it.

02:15:22.200 --> 02:15:23.200
[Amit Varma]: It's never easy.

02:15:23.200 --> 02:15:24.800
[Amit Varma]: It's always hard work, right?

02:15:24.800 --> 02:15:29.160
[Amit Varma]: So and you can balance that out with that thing that, you know, sometimes you can get

02:15:29.160 --> 02:15:33.280
[Amit Varma]: into flow when everything just happens easily, and it's just kind of happening by itself.

02:15:33.280 --> 02:15:36.960
[Amit Varma]: So what are sort of your thoughts on this?

02:15:36.960 --> 02:15:41.640
[Guest]: For me, the sound has to be right, you know, for me to be able to loosen up because the

02:15:41.640 --> 02:15:46.200
[Guest]: moment my guitar sound is not happening, it shuts me down like boom, and I have to just

02:15:46.200 --> 02:15:50.440
[Guest]: struggle my way, you know, because sometimes at some gig, like the amps not functioning

02:15:50.440 --> 02:15:53.200
[Guest]: well and everything, you know, you can only do so much.

02:15:53.200 --> 02:15:57.880
[Guest]: So you kind of have to say, sorry, audience, I know you paid money to come and see me today,

02:15:57.880 --> 02:16:00.640
[Guest]: but I'm just going to have to struggle through this and do the best you can.

02:16:00.640 --> 02:16:04.440
[Guest]: And some days it's just like your, your feet are almost off the ground throughout the gig,

02:16:04.440 --> 02:16:09.480
[Guest]: you know, like there was one gig I remember at Hard Rock Cafe in Pune.

02:16:09.480 --> 02:16:14.800
[Guest]: It was NH7 and all the other stages shut off one by one.

02:16:14.800 --> 02:16:19.040
[Guest]: And everyone started filtering into this gig, which was actually like one full on low public

02:16:19.040 --> 02:16:20.240
[Guest]: thing.

02:16:20.240 --> 02:16:23.280
[Guest]: But then it became like, you know, a full house and everything.

02:16:23.280 --> 02:16:27.000
[Guest]: So that gig, it was like the moment I got on stage and I hit the first note, it didn't

02:16:27.000 --> 02:16:28.000
[Guest]: matter.

02:16:28.000 --> 02:16:30.440
[Guest]: There was like 10 or 20 people in there to start.

02:16:30.440 --> 02:16:31.440
[Guest]: It just sounded so good.

02:16:31.440 --> 02:16:35.280
[Guest]: I was like, okay, now I'm gonna have a good gig, you know, it just like you're hearing

02:16:35.280 --> 02:16:37.720
[Guest]: everything clearly, that sort of thing.

02:16:37.720 --> 02:16:42.880
[Guest]: Now when I'm writing it, it could, you know, sometimes I could come up with something really

02:16:42.880 --> 02:16:43.880
[Guest]: quickly.

02:16:43.880 --> 02:16:46.040
[Guest]: Sometimes I have to just massage it a few different ways.

02:16:46.040 --> 02:16:50.080
[Guest]: And I don't really sit down to write a song, usually.

02:16:50.080 --> 02:16:55.240
[Guest]: I sit down to complete a song, but that writing, that initial idea, that spark or the idea

02:16:55.240 --> 02:16:58.960
[Guest]: that has legs, and I said, it can come anytime.

02:16:58.960 --> 02:17:02.600
[Guest]: Sometimes you're in the bathroom and you're hearing a melody in your head.

02:17:02.600 --> 02:17:06.360
[Guest]: I can't shut that off, by the way, if there's something playing in my head, it just goes

02:17:06.360 --> 02:17:12.360
[Guest]: on and through while I'm sleeping at night, it's goes on and on and on.

02:17:12.360 --> 02:17:14.120
[Guest]: And I can hear it in the dream sometimes.

02:17:14.120 --> 02:17:15.120
[Guest]: It's so weird.

02:17:15.120 --> 02:17:20.720
[Guest]: I'm like, you're also, it's gone, leave me alone for now, you know.

02:17:20.720 --> 02:17:26.720
[Guest]: So and then, like, especially if it's like a, like a musical problem, you know, like

02:17:26.720 --> 02:17:30.280
[Guest]: now you'll solve this problem and the bloody thing just keeps going, ding, ding, ding,

02:17:30.280 --> 02:17:31.720
[Guest]: ding, ding, ding, ding in your head.

02:17:31.720 --> 02:17:37.280
[Guest]: And you create like almost like 500 different permutations and combinations of, of what

02:17:37.280 --> 02:17:38.280
[Guest]: it could be.

02:17:38.280 --> 02:17:43.880
[Guest]: So that subconscious process, I still haven't, you know, come under full understanding of

02:17:43.880 --> 02:17:44.880
[Guest]: what it does.

02:17:44.880 --> 02:17:50.680
[Guest]: There are a few studies, you know, like one is called this is your brain on music or something

02:17:50.680 --> 02:17:51.680
[Guest]: like that.

02:17:51.680 --> 02:17:59.240
[Guest]: There's another guy called Anil Seth, who is a professor of consciousness.

02:17:59.240 --> 02:18:03.120
[Guest]: And he had a TED talk, which I was watching and it found it pretty fascinating.

02:18:03.120 --> 02:18:09.880
[Guest]: So I put his words in a song called Anesthesia, which was like, you know, the anesthesia is

02:18:09.880 --> 02:18:14.840
[Guest]: like this, it basically shows you what is, what is consciousness, you know, that sort

02:18:14.840 --> 02:18:15.840
[Guest]: of thing.

02:18:15.840 --> 02:18:16.840
[Guest]: When does consciousness stop?

02:18:16.840 --> 02:18:17.840
[Guest]: Where does it end?

02:18:17.840 --> 02:18:19.440
[Guest]: And all that kind of thing.

02:18:19.440 --> 02:18:23.560
[Guest]: So I find that a fascinating subject, but there's parts of my brain, which I still don't

02:18:23.560 --> 02:18:27.160
[Guest]: understand, you know, how it works and that sort of thing.

02:18:27.160 --> 02:18:29.020
[Guest]: I know what I like, you know.

02:18:29.020 --> 02:18:32.720
[Guest]: So I try to set up the process, like I have a template that I've made in Cubase, like

02:18:32.720 --> 02:18:35.760
[Guest]: everything is connected in a certain way.

02:18:35.760 --> 02:18:38.800
[Guest]: So if I want to start writing, I can start doing that pretty quickly.

02:18:38.800 --> 02:18:40.560
[Guest]: I can pull up a drum track.

02:18:40.560 --> 02:18:44.920
[Guest]: I find it sometimes it works, if you're stuck, you put on a, you know, a loop or something

02:18:44.920 --> 02:18:48.480
[Guest]: like that, that can tend to, you know, flow that.

02:18:48.480 --> 02:18:52.040
[Guest]: And sometimes just jamming with other people, that's like the best thing for me, you know,

02:18:52.040 --> 02:18:55.880
[Guest]: like the most creative I'm in is with other people in the room who are on the same, you

02:18:55.880 --> 02:18:58.760
[Guest]: know, wavelength as you are musically.

02:18:58.760 --> 02:19:06.080
[Guest]: There was one song, Focus 3, I wrote that just before I left New Zealand to come back

02:19:06.080 --> 02:19:08.140
[Guest]: to India 2011.

02:19:08.140 --> 02:19:14.060
[Guest]: And my friends had organized this little jam and we were playing and then we had some stimulants

02:19:14.060 --> 02:19:17.120
[Guest]: that were part of the, you know, the evening and everything like that.

02:19:17.120 --> 02:19:20.240
[Guest]: So there came to a point like where three of us were jamming and it sounded so good.

02:19:20.240 --> 02:19:26.480
[Guest]: I almost felt like myself like levitate off and see us from, you know, above, it was so

02:19:26.480 --> 02:19:27.480
[Guest]: weird.

02:19:27.480 --> 02:19:29.600
[Guest]: I mean, obviously you're connected with the instrument and everything, but it's almost

02:19:29.600 --> 02:19:34.520
[Guest]: like you're looking at it from like five feet higher than, like the only time that it was

02:19:34.520 --> 02:19:37.560
[Guest]: like a tangible, you know, experience like that.

02:19:37.560 --> 02:19:40.640
[Guest]: I don't know if the stimulants had something to do with it or whatever.

02:19:40.640 --> 02:19:45.360
[Guest]: So the funny thing is, I remember that exactly how it went.

02:19:45.360 --> 02:19:49.360
[Guest]: And so when I came back to India, I remember I'd done this gig with Ehsan at the Garden

02:19:49.360 --> 02:19:51.320
[Guest]: of Five Senses in Delhi.

02:19:51.320 --> 02:19:55.600
[Guest]: And I had to do a song of my own and Jai was playing drums and Loy was playing bass.

02:19:55.600 --> 02:19:59.600
[Guest]: I was like, hang on, I wrote this riff, let's just, you know, see where that goes.

02:19:59.600 --> 02:20:08.200
[Guest]: And there was a sarangi player, Suhail from Advaita, and he started singing something

02:20:08.200 --> 02:20:11.080
[Guest]: on top of it because I think the idea was, you know, to have him to collaborate with

02:20:11.080 --> 02:20:12.760
[Guest]: us on that song.

02:20:12.760 --> 02:20:15.420
[Guest]: And then I think Loy shaped it a little bit differently.

02:20:15.420 --> 02:20:20.120
[Guest]: So that whole process took a very tangible idea, which is something I'd almost completed,

02:20:20.120 --> 02:20:22.280
[Guest]: but he shaped it in a very cool way.

02:20:22.280 --> 02:20:27.080
[Guest]: So then, you know, I kind of wrote a little thank you to both of them for their help in

02:20:27.080 --> 02:20:28.860
[Guest]: those melodies.

02:20:28.860 --> 02:20:33.000
[Guest]: So that's where you kind of hear a little bit of that Indian influence and that kind

02:20:33.000 --> 02:20:34.360
[Guest]: of thing.

02:20:34.360 --> 02:20:39.360
[Guest]: But the collaborative thing is also like, you need to be with people who, like, there's

02:20:39.360 --> 02:20:41.800
[Guest]: no egos and no hang ups.

02:20:41.800 --> 02:20:47.240
[Guest]: Everyone's just there to play music and not, you know, this is what color shoes I'm wearing

02:20:47.240 --> 02:20:49.760
[Guest]: today and what is none of that happening.

02:20:49.760 --> 02:20:58.840
[Guest]: So that that can open up, you know, and you tend to learn what are the triggers that open

02:20:58.840 --> 02:21:03.800
[Guest]: up those those doors, you know, it's almost like you're trying to break into another world

02:21:03.800 --> 02:21:07.000
[Guest]: and take something from them, pull it back into us.

02:21:07.000 --> 02:21:10.840
[Guest]: That's ideally what because many songwriters have, you know, kind of likened it to that

02:21:10.840 --> 02:21:15.400
[Guest]: person, like Tom Petty or something, I go like way up high and I pull something back

02:21:15.400 --> 02:21:16.980
[Guest]: down to the earth.

02:21:16.980 --> 02:21:22.680
[Guest]: So the more you learn to do that, the better your chances of actually doing that.

02:21:22.680 --> 02:21:24.520
[Guest]: You're not going to do it every time.

02:21:24.520 --> 02:21:27.840
[Guest]: I mean, you watch Sachin, there's not every batch that he makes, essentially, sometimes

02:21:27.840 --> 02:21:30.640
[Guest]: he gets out on a duck, but he's still Sachin, you know.

02:21:30.640 --> 02:21:33.840
[Amit Varma]: So it's like that.

02:21:33.840 --> 02:21:37.480
[Amit Varma]: Can you give examples of these sort of triggers that you mentioned where you can, you know,

02:21:37.480 --> 02:21:40.920
[Amit Varma]: you're collaborating with a bunch of people and shit happens?

02:21:40.920 --> 02:21:45.320
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, it's all over that second album.

02:21:45.320 --> 02:21:51.120
[Guest]: And do you want me to play you something?

02:21:51.120 --> 02:21:53.720
[Guest]: It's kind of pretty cool.

02:21:53.720 --> 02:21:57.220
[Guest]: Let me just see if I can find it because it's on some hard disk.

02:21:57.220 --> 02:22:00.040
[Guest]: But this is the first time we ever played North Star together.

02:22:00.040 --> 02:22:05.920
[Guest]: And I'd kind of put the whole thing together in terms of a basic arrangement, but I'd left

02:22:05.920 --> 02:22:11.520
[Guest]: things open into what would happen in that middle jam section.

02:22:11.520 --> 02:22:15.600
[Guest]: And one of the things we did in Black Star Blues when we came to that middle section

02:22:15.600 --> 02:22:21.480
[Guest]: was to just break it down and have Adi underpin something with a bass line or whatever, and

02:22:21.480 --> 02:22:25.400
[Guest]: then have Bevan move like, you know, chord shapes on top of it.

02:22:25.400 --> 02:22:27.840
[Guest]: So we kind of said, okay, this is the bass line.

02:22:27.840 --> 02:22:32.580
[Guest]: I gave it to him, like, you know that, and told Bevan, okay, this is the chords.

02:22:32.580 --> 02:22:37.320
[Guest]: But after that, what happened is, I'll play you that middle section.

